<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitchers risk careers &QL; 
with line-drive injuries
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The frightening, whack-whack sound of bat hitting ball and ball
hitting pitcher is becoming all too commonplace in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   When Astros reliever Billy Wagner was hit in the left ear by a
line drive off the bat of Arizona's Kelly Stinnett on Wednesday
night in Phoenix, it marked the fourth time in the past 14 months a
major-league pitcher has been struck in the head by a batted ball.
Though Wagner suffered a concussion and tissue damage to his ear,
he has no broken bones and could return in one to two weeks. That
is in contrast to three incidents since May 1997. In those cases:
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Willie Blair suffered a broken jaw when he was hit by
a line drive off the bat of Cleveland's Julio Franco on May 4,
1997. Blair missed about five weeks but returned to have a 16-8
season, his best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore reliever Norm Charlton was hit by Frank Thomas' line
drive this past April 29. Charlton received four stitches and
suffered a displaced nose fracture but did not go on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Just more than two weeks after Charlton was struck by Thomas,
Baltimore's Mike Mussina was hit by a line drive off the bat of
Cleveland's Sandy Alomar Jr. on May 15. Mussina suffered a broken
nose and a gash above his right eye and missed three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most well-known incident involving a pitcher struck
by a line drive occurred more than 40 years ago. Cleveland
lefthander Herb Score was hit in the eye by a line drive off the
bat of New York's Gil McDougald, altering a career that seemed
destined for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Score was 36-19 in two seasons before the accident, striking out
508 batters in 473 innings. He was 20-9 with 263 strikeouts in 1956
as a 21-year-old and was being hailed as a lefthanded Bob Feller.
But after Score was hit by McDougald's liner, he was 17-26 in five
subsequent seasons with Cleveland and the Chicago White Sox. He
retired in 1963 at the age of 28.
</P>
<P>
   Blair also was a different pitcher last season after being hit
by Franco's liner, which was clocked at 107 mph _ but it was for
the better. A journeyman righthander who'd had limited success with
Cleveland, the Astros, Colorado, San Diego and Detroit, Blair went
13-6 after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit pitching coach Rick Adair said he believed that after
Blair was hit, he changed his delivery to better protect himself
from line drives. Subsequently, Adair said, Blair kept the ball
lower in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who was in his free-agent season in 1997, parlayed his
13-6 finish into a three-year contract with Arizona. Pitching for
the expansion Diamondbacks, Blair is 3-13 and leads the majors in
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina, who won 19 games for Baltimore in 1995 and '96, was
109-51 over eight-plus seasons when he was hit by Alomar's line
drive. In his first three starts after returning to the roster,
Mussina was 1-2 with an 8.44 ERA. But he has pitched better lately
and is 7-5, 3.67 for a team that is well under .500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
