<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-TURNER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SLUGGISH SALES AND RATINGS, TURNER STILL UPBEAT ON GOODWILL
GAMES  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to clarify the time element in the lede graf and to add 4 new
grafs at the end; a few minor alterations elsewhere)   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who cares if the first three Goodwill Games have lost
$109 million? Not Ted Turner. A few days before the fourth edition
_ starting in New York Saturday with opening ceremonies at Battery
Park _ Turner abruptly dashed across his 29th floor office in Time
Warner's Manhattan headquarters to fiddle with his deskside
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha! I made $150 million today!'' he said, analyzing the
late-afternoon action of his 60 million shares of Time Warner
stock. Eyes twinkling, he told a visitor, ``But I've lost $50
million since you've been here!''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Turner's paper gain on Wednesday amounted to $251
million by 1:20 p.m. and had plummeted to $75 million when he
punched his computer keys. But it recovered to $120 million by
day's end. His shares were worth $5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the Goodwill Games _ a 15-sport spectacle starring
1,500 athletes from 60 countries _ are affordable, a minor item for
a $13.3 billion corporation. They were affordable before the Turner
Broadcasting System merged with Time Warner in October 1996. They
remain affordable now.
</P>
<P>
   And what's $109 million when you're ending the Cold War? ``Yeah,
we helped end the Cold War,'' he said, leaning perilously far back
in his chair and distractedly watching the Mets-Braves game on a
corner TV. ``It's hard to tell what's the first straw or the last.
You can't get too much goodwill.''
</P>
<P>
   There will certainly be more. Saturday at Madison Square Garden,
Turner will announce the site for the 2001 Goodwill Games, which is
expected to be in Asia or Australia. The usual four-year cycle is
being shortened once to avoid future conflicts for the attention of
viewers and advertisers with the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Turner keeping staging them? The Soviet Union is dead.
The United States won the Cold War. The truth is, he likes them.
They're not as big as the Olympics, but so what? He'll still
broadcast them in 130 countries. They will fill 47 hours on the TBS
Superstation, plus 10 on CBS and 8 on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't caused trouble,'' he said. ``How can getting
athletes on the field more often be bad?''
</P>
<P>
   And by paying prize money of $5 million, plus bonuses for world
records, he has lured Michael Johnson, Dan O'Brien, Michelle Kwan
and other world-class athletes. Ten athletes are being paid
six-figure fees to promote the games.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games are as much a pampered Turner scion as Cable
News Network, the Atlanta Braves or his new 24-hour ``Cold War''
series on TBS. He insisted that Time Warner never tried to axe the
Goodwill Games in the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lay down the law,'' said Turner, who owns 10 percent
of the company but is second in command to the chairman, Gerald
Levin. ``I'm not the big dog. But we were already committed to
doing this in New York, and Jerry was excited. It's like it was
predestined for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Schiller, the president of Turner Sports, said: ``He
really feels it's very good programming, with the sports that have
the most interest with the public. He thinks it's an event you can
put in places where the Olympics don't fit. And he loves the idea
of being in the biggest city.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wussler, the former president of Turner Broadcasting,
helped create the first Goodwill Games in Moscow in 1986. It
included the first competition between American and Soviet athletes
since the United States boycotted the 1980 Summer Olympics in
Moscow and the Soviets boycotted the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he created,'' Wussler said. ``It's his child
and he wants to continue it forever if possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games' impact on the Olympics will be long debated.
Turner brought the superpowers together when the Olympics couldn't.
If the Goodwill Games did not exist, would the boycotting nations
have gotten together in Seoul in 1988?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound, a member of the International Olympic Committee,
said: ``They've had any impact at all. If there ever was a use for
them, that time has past. They're just a made-for-TV Olympics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
