<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS BEAT CONE AND YANKEES, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The New York Yankees could average about two victories
a week the rest of the season and still make the playoffs. Now the
guiding force behind most of manager Joe Torre's decisions will be
what's best for the Yankees in October.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing David Cone to succeed or fail in the eighth inning
against Detroit Thursday night, as Torre did, injects Cone with the
knowledge that his manager has confidence in him, and maybe that
will benefit the Yankees in the postseason. Thursday night, Cone
allowed a tie-breaking single to Luis Gonzalez with two outs in the
eighth and the Yankees lost, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Brian Moehler threw eight and one-third innings to
become only the second pitcher to beat the Yankees twice this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Torre should have replaced Cone with the left-hander Mike
Stanton as the left-handed-hitting Gonzalez came to bat. Maybe not.
A debate team could probably win arguing either side. But it's all
about the big picture now with the Yankees, a byproduct of their
67-22 record. Any mental edge derived from Torre's decisions far
outweighs a loss that very likely will be meaningless to the
American League East standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nice, because it told me that he trusted me,'' said
Cone, who lost for the first time since June 19. ``It gives me
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said: ``What I like to do with starters is give them a
chance to win. But they deserve a chance to lose, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The near inevitability of a Yankee playoff appearance is why
Torre may decide to rest Darryl Strawberry, who has a sore left
knee, for the next two weeks. On Sunday, Torre did not use Paul
O'Neill to pinch-hit for the rookie Ricky Ledee in the ninth inning
of a tie game, primarily because Torre wants Ledee to adapt to
pressure situations _ such as he may face in October.
</P>
<P>
   Cone (13-3) is Torre's ace, the soul of his pitching staff.
Torre says he believes in Cone ``as much as I believe in anybody,''
adding, ``I trust his heart, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Cone work and struggle and eventually succeed in
his comeback from shoulder surgery, Torre wants Cone to feel this
trust.
</P>
<P>
   Cone allowed only five hits in the first seven innings; his
fastball was sizzling once again, his command excellent. His only
mistake had been throwing a high fastball to Raul Casanova in the
fifth inning that Casanova blasted into the right-field stands.
That tied the score at 1-1, matching a home run to lead off the
game by Chuck Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   But with one out in the eighth, Damion Easley, who had struck
out in his first three at-bats, worked the count to 3-2. Cone
thought about throwing Easley a fastball, but each of his
strikeouts had come with a sidearm slider _ the laredo, Cone
sometimes calls it. Cone came with the slider over the plate, and
Easley lined a double to left, directly at Ledee, and then over his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton was warming up in the bullpen, a left-hander preparing
to possibly face the next three hitters _ the left-handed-hitting
Bobby Higginson, the switch-hitting Tony Clark and
left-handed-hitting Gonzalez. Torre said, however, that Stanton was
more of a contingency, in case Cone tired quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone zipped a 3-2 fastball over the inside corner to strike out
Higginson, and both he and Joe Girardi thought at that moment that
they were going to get out of the inning. There were two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 0 for 20 in his career against Cone, went to a 3-2 count,
and again Cone thought about trying to throw a fastball inside.
Cone tried a clider instead and missed with it, walking Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez walked to the plate, Torre stayed in the dugout. Cone
threw a splitter that dived low and away, and Gonzalez managed to
pull a ground ball to the right side. An out, Cone thought for an
instant. He was wrong. Knoblauch, the second baseman, noted that
this ground ball never hit the grass _ it hit the dirt in front of
home plate, bounced over the grass that surely would have slowed it
and then skipped on the infield dirt and into right field.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, trying desperately to cut down Easley at the plate,
threw high and away, and Clark followed Easley across home with
Detroit's third run. Gonzalez's hit was the first with runners in
scoring position against a Yankee pitcher in 30 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there was no lamenting, no anger. They just got beat,
Cone said, by a team that played better. ``It sounds like a
cliche,'' he said, ``but it's true in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with Moehler, regarded as a solid but unspectacular
pitcher who throws sinkers and sliders. From the on-deck circle,
Chad Curtis said, Moehler is the type of pitcher about whom a
hitter thinks: ``O.K., as soon as he makes a mistake, I'm going to
get him. But he's not making very many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   On only five occasions this year has an opposing starter allowed
one run in eight or more innings to the Yankees. Moehler (10-5) has
done it twice now. ``It was nerve-wracking,'' he said, ``but lots
of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He had beaten Cone, a Cy Young Award candidate, and earned
well-deserved bragging rights for a day. But Torre is probably more
concerned that Cone win bragging rights against Chuck Finley or
Jaret Wright in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
