<HEADLINE>
INDIAN COMMUNITY SAYS RULING WILL FORCE AGREEMENT ON SLOT MACHINES
</HEADLINE>
 RIVER-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS 
 and VICTORIA HARKER 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A long-awaited ruling Thursday by the Arizona Supreme Court is
being hailed as a victory by the Salt River Pima-Maricopa Indian
Community, which says the justices' decision will force the state
to allow lucrative slot machines on its reservation near
Scottsdale's border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly requires the governor to sign a standard form of
compact with a tribe that doesn't have a compact,'' said Philip
Shea, the tribe's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Jane Hull had made no decision Thursday to sign an
agreement, saying instead she will meet with tribal officials to
discuss the high court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying whether we will sign or not sign the
compact,'' said Francie Noyes, Hull's spokeswoman. ``We are saying
we will talk about it. We just have to take it one step at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Merna Lewis, the tribe's vice president, also said
Thursday's ruling clears the way for full-fledged gaming on its
reservation bordering Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the decision we've been waiting for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal council Thursday night passed a resolution asking
Gov. Jane Hull to sign a compact
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale officials have said little about the neighboring
tribe's proposal to build a casino with slot machines near its
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale Mayor Sam Campana could not be reached Thursday, but
has said earlier that the city would not interfere with the tribe's
sovereign rights to operate a gambling hall.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' ruling stemmed from the appeal of a 1997 lawsuit
brought by a northeast Phoenix couple, Paula and Alan Sears. Their
suit challenged the legality of Indian gaming in Arizona, and also
asked then Gov. Fife Symington not to sign a compact allowing the
Salt River Community to operate slot machines on its reservation
near Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The high court was not asked to rule on the legality of gaming
on Arizona reservations, but to decide whether the Sears had
standing to bring the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The justices unanimously said that the Sears, who live two miles
from the Scottsdale border, could not prove that they had suffered
any special harm from gaming, and therefore had no standing to
bring the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sears had claimed in their lawsuit that a proposed casino
3.2 miles from their children's school would harm their values and
destroy tthe character of the surrounding community.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, the tribe's attorney, said that although the justices were
not asked to consider the legality of Indian gaming, their ruling
will nevertheless give the tribe the ``same gaming privaleges . . .
as the other 16 gaming tribes have had. . .,''
</P>
<P>
   But Neal Wake, the Sears' attorney, said the court's decision
does not ensure that the games will go on or that the Salt River
Community will get an agreement to open a full-blown casino.
</P>
<P>
   Wake says it is now up to Hull to bring a lawsuit challenging
the legality of casino gambling on Arizona Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   `` I hope Gov. Hull will decide not to disregard that serious
legal question and decide to allow the courts to resolve these
legalities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes, Hull's spokeswoman, said that the governor opposes
statewide gambling, but she will follow the law in deciding whether
to sign a compact. Noyes, also said it is too early for the
governor to say whether she will bring a lawsuit to clear up the
question of Indian gaming in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   While it awaits a compact, the tribe in June, opened a 42-table
poker room at 92nd Street and McKellips Road in order to cash in on
gaming revenues. The tribe does not have a compact for poker, but
has agreed to allow the state to oversee its games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Carol Sowers can be reached at 444-7482
 &UR; or at carol.sowers &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
