<SLUG> BC-HEAT-WAVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT RECORDS WILTING AWAY THROUGHOUT L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Suburban Chatsworth became the hottest spot in
Los Angeles with a record-breaking peak of 108 degrees, as a
blistering heat wave broke area records and filled the air with
choking smog. And it isn't going to get any better for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Chatsworth's Thursday scorcher broke the 1980 record by six
degrees. Nearby Burbank's 103 shattered a 62-year-old record, while
suburban Simi Valley's 100 reading beat the 1977 record by 3
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will remain scalding today through Tuesday, with
highs in the suburban San Fernando Valley expected to be in the
upper 90s to 108, the National Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   The scorching heat wave sent power use soaring as air
conditioners were running at full blast all day. But outdoors,
there was no escape from the blistering heat or the smog.
</P>
<P>
   Local hospitals and senior citizen homes reported no
heat-related deaths or cases of heatstroke, but Steve Kishineff,
emergency room physician at Providence St. Joseph Medical Center in
suburban Burbank, said he has seen about 10 percent more
respiratory problems than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any extreme weather changes affect people with respiratory
problems, like asthma and emphysema patients,'' Kishineff said.
``So I think it causes us to see higher volumes of asthma and
emphysema patients, and those we do see have more severe illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ailments might be related not only to the heat, but to
pollutants that accumulate in the warm, stagnant air.
</P>
<P>
   The South Coast Air Quality Management District issued health
advisories for the San Fernando and Santa Clarita valleys Thursday,
warning schools to keep students from vigorous and prolonged
outdoor activity and alerting people with heart or lung disease to
stay inside altogether.
</P>
<P>
   A pollution index that measures ozone, carbon monoxide and
particulates reached 175 in the eastern San Fernando Valley, 150 in
the West Valley and 163 in the Santa Clarita Valley, said AQMD
spokesman Sam Atwood. Anything over 100 is considered unhealthful,
and a level of 200 triggers a worst-case Stage 1 smog alert.
</P>
<P>
   Residents responded by cranking their air conditioners, pushing
up power use throughout the Southland. Peak power use at both
Southern California Edison and the Los Angeles Department of Water
and Power rose above average, but didn't break any records.
</P>
<P>
   The oppressive heat comes from a high-pressure zone that moved
across the southern United States with easterly trade winds,
sparking wildfires in Florida, killing more than 50 people and now
settling over the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   While the weather pattern itself is fairly common during the
summer, its results are more extreme than usual this year.
</P>
<P>
   The high-pressure area centered over Lake Mead on Thursday, said
James Murakami, staff meteorologist with the atmospheric sciences
department at UCLA. There it forced hot air downward, further
warming and compressing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analogy is something like a bicycle pump: When you pump it
downward it causes warming of the pump,'' Murakami said. ``Another
analogy is a pressure cooker. It's the increased pressure that
causes the warming.''
</P>
<P>
   Air circulating clockwise around the high-pressure zone sweeps
heated desert air west into the Los Angeles area, Murakami said.
</P>
<P>
   And while cool ocean air is keeping the coast from scorching,
that marine layer is too shallow to clear the Santa Monica
Mountains, leaving the San Fernando Valley without relief.
</P>
<P>
   The high-pressure zone's westward shift did provide some respite
to drought- and fire-stricken Florida, allowing rain to dampen some
of the blazes, Murakami said. However, Texas remains besieged by
heat.
</P>
<P>
   At least 25 people in Texas, 20 in Louisiana, six in Oklahoma
and one each in California and Arizona have died from heat-related
causes since mid-May. Many of those killed had heart disease or
another medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave comes in a warmer-than-average year for Los
Angeles. Normally the city averages 63 degrees, said Ken Reeves, a
senior meteorologist for AccuWeather. This year it has averaged 65
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
