A9520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SECRET-SERVICE-N     07-17 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SECRET-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SECRET SERVICE SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   Unless Chief Justice William Rehnquist intervenes, Secret
Service officers, including the head of President Clinton's
protective detail, will be required to testify before the Monica
Lewinsky grand jury. A federal appeals court ruled Thursday that
the testimony was required under law, but allowed the Justice
Department 24 hours in which to ask Rehnquist to schedule a hearing
before the full Supreme Court in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The main thrust of the appeals court's unanimous ruling, though,
was that Secret Service agents, as sworn law officers, should
testify and could do so without endangering presidential security.
We continue to believe the panel was correct in rejecting the
Clinton administration's invention of a new ``protective function''
privilege to block Secret Service testimony. To allow law
enforcement officials broad leeway to avoid cooperating with a
criminal inquiry cuts aganst the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling, however, if it stands, puts a heavy burden
on Kenneth Starr, the Special Prosecutor, to use good judgment in
calling Secret Service agents. Starr should remember that sooner or
later everyone will know whether he had sufficient reason to go to
the heart of the presidential detail and call Clinton's chief
bodyguard, Larry Cockell. If he is calling this agent as a means of
getting testimony about overheard conversations between Clinton and
his private lawyers, that would be an unacceptable attempt to
pierce attorney-client privilege. The White House has tried to
extend that privilege into inappropriate areas, but there is no
question that Clinton has a right to confidential conversations
with his personal lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The federal courts have ruled correctly that Starr has the right
to compel Secret Service testimony. For the moment, it is
impossible to know from the outside whether Starr's investigative
needs justify reaching so deeply into the Secret Service. But he
can provide reassurance that he understands his duty by announcing
now that he is not trying to get at conversations between Clinton
and his private lawyers. He should also make clear his
understanding that his threshold for summoning members of the
president's closest detail should be high, and any questions put to
agents should be focused on carefully developed areas of
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
