u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-535&AMP;ADD-N     07-17 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS START FRESH IN NEW TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ This is what happens to the Dallas
Cowboys when their play on the field is finally as bad their
behavior off it: They get a new sheriff and are plopped down in a
new frontier for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The new law is the organized and disciplined Chan Gailey,
formerly the Pittsburgh Steelers' offensive coordinator, who
replaces Barry Switzer. The new training camp is in this sweltering
town of 100,000 near the Oklahoma border, which was resourceful
enough to build a 54-foot cascade to replace its namesake natural
falls after they were washed away in a flood. It took 100 years,
but they did it.
</P>
<P>
   But Wichita Falls is also tradition-bound enough to treasure a
56-year-old barbecue joint called the Bar L Drive In, which
delivers succulent ribs curbside along with a pitcher of its
specialty drink _ a beer-and-tomato-juice concoction called Red
Draw _ all for under $11.
</P>
<P>
   The coach and community could both be excused for feeling like
afterthoughts. Cowboys' owner Jerry Jones took weeks and romanced
several suitors, including former 49ers coach George Siefert and
former UCLA coach Terry Donohue, before plucking Gailey out of
nowhere to turn around a team that was 6-10 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Wichita Falls grabbed its host role only after Austin,
the longtime incumbent, decided not to ask the Cowboys back after
players trashed the dormitories at a local college at the end of
last summer's camp. Next, San Antonio decided that Dallas' unruly
players were more trouble than they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fresh start, so we have a lot of optimism,'' defensive
tackle Chad Hennings said after a spirited running session Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, opening day was filled with a bonhomie veteran Cowboys
professed not to have seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Leon Lett spoke briefly to the news media while
his teammates meowed behind him, stunned that the normally
reclusive Big Cat was going public.
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders, the cornerback formerly known as Prime Time who
now preaches prayer time, showed that his religious conversion had
not dampened his theatrical flair. Though he still is recovering
from arthroscopic surgery on a left ankle injured while playing
racquetball, Sanders heard from his teammates as he tooled to the
cafeteria for lunch in his own customized golf cart. Jet black,
with a hard top and the words ``Full Time'' on its front, the cart
features a sound system that can be heard for blocks. In heavy
rotation was a gospel number with the repeated chorus, ``Prime
time.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys finally took the practice field at Midwestern
State University, they succumbed to Gailey's influence. He put them
through a series of crisp drills in shorts and helmets, unwilling
to throw them into the 102-degree heat with full pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not tried to be overbearing with this football team,''
said quarterback Troy Aikman, who has become Gailey's biggest fan.
``He's provided direction, and the guys are responding to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Gailey says the Cowboys must take care of
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people go off on their own tangents, my job is to get them
back in step,'' he said. ``If there's a problem, I'll take care of
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the next four weeks, Gailey has many decisions to make. The
Cowboys need to choose among Ernie Mills, Billy Davis, Macey Brooks
and Stepfret Williams for the receiver slot opposite Michael Irvin.
They signed Everett McIver, who played guard for the Dolphins, to
shore up an aging offensive line; the veteran Nate Newton showed up
60 pounds lighter, but at 36 is no lock to keep his starting job at
the other guard. And Seattle's Chris Warren was ostensibly signed
as a third-down back, but is here to challenge Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Wichita Falls has vowed to take care of its
high-profile guests. To a point. More than 15,000 people welcomed
the team with a pep rally Tuesday night, and a party atmosphere
reigns in a town projected to garner $4 million from the Cowboys'
four-week stay.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Bar L, however, Sunshine Payne is keeping her feet
firmly on the ground. For 22 years, she has tended bar and served
everyone from movie stars like Cybill Shepherd to just good folks
from down the road in Boyd. She's a Dallas fan and is certain the
players will find their way to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day the paper had a little line asking if you'd seen
your favorite Cowboy with a plate a ribs at the Bar L. They worded
it just right _ they didn't say `Dallas.' Just Cowboys. We get a
lot of them in here,'' she said with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Tough camp. Tough town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
