<HEADER>
A9526 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RANGERS-T     07-17 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DUMP STRUGGLING RANGERS, 9-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander Aaron Sele positioned the
Rangers for a potential venture into unchartered territory: One
week between victories.
</P>
<P>
   That became a distinct possibility after the Rangers sustained
their fifth consecutive defeat with last night's 9-3 submission to
the Baltimore Orioles at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's departure after 4 1/3 innings represented only the second
time this season that the Rangers lost consecutive games started by
Sele and right-hander Rick Helling through their 40 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five days ago,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said, ``we were
kings.''
</P>
<P>
   The rotation abdicated the throne.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starting pitchers will enter tonight's game 0-5 with an
11.51 earned-run average during this five-game losing streak, and
that does not bode well after the events of the past two evenings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost consecutive games with Sele and Helling
starting previously June 28 and 30, and that contributed to their
season-high, six-game losing streak June 27-July 3. A seven-game
losing streak remains realistic with left-hander Darren Oliver and
right-hander Todd Van Poppel scheduled to pitch tonight and
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver owns an 8.47 earned-run average during his past nine
starts, and Van Poppel's 8.84 ERA during four starts with the
Rangers does nothing to improve their prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Rangers' only grace might be the fact that the
expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays, the American League's worst team,
open a three-game series tonight at The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like everything is uphill right now,'' Oates
said. ``We'll get over that. We'll start downhill again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele (12-5) struggled to throw strikes consistently and issued
three walks during this 106-pitch appearance, and the Orioles
amassed 12 hits against the right-hander when he did throw strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At no time did Sele labor as he did during the Orioles' four-run
third inning. Sele required 39 pitches to complete that inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you do that,'' Oates said. ``I don't know how
long our defense was on on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Orioles catcher Lenny Webster, who matched his single-game best
for the second consecutive night with three base hits, delivered
the most significant blow with a two-out, two-run double that gave
the Orioles a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go out there and give your team a chance to win,
and I couldn't do it,'' said Sele, who hung a curveball to Webster.
``I couldn't get the ball down right out of the chute. I was trying
to make an adjustment, and I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Eric Gunderson, who relieved Sele, gave the Rangers
an opportunity to rally. Gunderson retired the first eight hitters
he faced, but the Rangers managed to score only once on a
seventh-inning, run-scoring single by second baseman Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing well enough,'' Oates said, ``to win right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Will that last for a week?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
