<HEADER>
A9528 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     07-17 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OFFENSE SO POWERFUL, SO MYSTERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ He came over the fence back at Valley
Ranch after a minicamp session one night this off-season, his eyes
glazed and his skin pale and sweating.
</P>
<P>
   He was just a fan, he mumbled to paramedics called to the scene
by a passing motorist, but he'd spent three grueling days secretly
watching new Cowboys head coach Chan Gailey installing the team's
high-tech, multiple-offensive system.
</P>
<P>
   It was more, he swore, than any human being should have to
absorb, which, by the way, may explain Nate Newton's drastic weight
loss.
</P>
<P>
   They rushed the poor survivor away _ for observation, they said
_ before he could be fully interviewed and his secret, the
unbelievable things he saw in those 72 hours of sheer hell,
disappeared with him.
</P>
<P>
   Until yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, with apparently no thought to the damage that might
have been incurred by hundreds of women and children on hand to
watch the Cowboys' first-ever preseason practice session at
Midwestern State University, Gailey and his offensive coaches again
cracked the lid on what could be the most potent force since
scientists built the first A-bomb at a secret laboratory in New
Mexico more than half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the third time now we've started all over with the
thing,'' Gailey calmly confessed afterward, bringing gasps from
veteran members of the media corps, who found themselves wishing
they'd brought along their old gas masks from the last Middle East
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   What, we timidly asked Gailey, has he named this electrifying
offense, this dark force from the bowels of hell? Something sexier,
surely, than the mundane, no longer chic, ``West Coast Offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Desert Storm II?
</P>
<P>
   The Sound and the Fury?
</P>
<P>
   Nukes 'R Us?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no names,'' Gailey said grinning. ``No names.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it's the No-Name Offense. And instant, certain destruction
to whatever defense stands in its way.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the way it's drawn up.
</P>
<P>
   It is an intriguing mystery, this Gailey offense, more
complicated, to hear players tell it, than Egyptian hieroglyphics,
more potent than a pitcher of Esparza's margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiple. Balanced. Those are probably the two words I would
use to describe it,'' Gailey said. ``Nothing is set in concrete in
this offense except that we are going to try to run the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we're going to try to get the best players on
the field and get the ball into the hands of the players who need
to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't let his calm demeanor fool you. If this works like Gailey
thinks it can, he'll be more famous than Oppenheimer (the dude who
built the A-bomb).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to force defenses to prepare for a lot more than
they've had to in the past,'' fullback Daryl Johnston said. ``It's
a little bit more complex. It's a multiple-set, multiple-formation
offense that people aren't going to be able to just walk in on a
few of the basic things that we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the same personnel in different formations. You
can bring in different personnel and put them in different
formations. It's going to give our opponents a lot to look at, a
lot to consider, on a weekly basis and at the beginning of the
season they aren't going to be sure what we're going to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Question is, are the Cowboys? This may not be brain surgery, but
then we're not dealing with a dorm full of Rhodes Scholars either.
That's why Gailey and his staff took the offense back to square one
_ for the third time _ yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't pick up where we left off'' from the last minicamp,
Gailey said. ``We went back and started back at the very beginning
and you could tell that. We got some timing and some work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting it slowly but surely. They understood it. They
were able to move along quicker today than we were the first two
times we put it in. This was how we wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It'll be similar to what the Steelers ran last season, but with
some interesting Cowboys twists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, people are going to be looking at the Pittsburgh
Steeler films and trying to gauge what we're going to take from
that and what Chan's going to put in on his own,'' Johnston said.
``I think it's going to give us an advantage early when teams are
trying to decide what we're going to do. It's going to be much more
difficult to prepare for us as an offense than it has in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't matter a bit, however, if the players don't execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it all along, what we did in the past was very
successful for us and I'm a huge fan of the offensive system that
we ran,'' quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``I don't think it was the
offensive system that caused our problems. If we don't execute this
year any better than what we did last year, then we're going to
have the same problems in this one that we had in the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes beyond that. We've got to execute better and take care
of the little things and be a little more detail oriented than what
we've been. If we do that, we're going to be a success. It's not so
much the system. Coaches do things different ways for different
reasons, but ultimately it's football.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was something in the wind yesterday, something new
and powerful and mysterious. Those of us who were there on July 16,
1998, will remember the day when we witnessed the first unveiling
of the ultimate offense _ Gailey's No Name Offense.
</P>
<P>
   And we've lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   So far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPE-SURGE-LADN     07-17 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-SURGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE OF SEX CRIMES HAS LAPD MARSHALING FORCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Police officials detailed a series of steps to
combat the surge in rape and sexual-assault crimes in Los Angeles,
including stepping up investigative efforts and using detectives
from the elite robbery-homicide unit to assist other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that rapes have increased while most other crimes
are declining sharply, Chief Bernard C. Parks and other Los Angeles
Police Department officials said Thursday they are developing a new
computerized tracking system for such crimes, similar to one
already in existence for homicides.
</P>
<P>
   They said this would improve the sharing of crime-report data
among detectives in different parts of the city and make it easier
to identify patterns that might indicate a serial rapist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to share all of the information so they can connect a
rape report from Hollywood with one in North Hollywood,'' said
Capt. Jim Tatreau, commanding officer of the Robbery-Homicide
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Tatreau and Parks first discussed the concept during a Police
Commission meeting earlier this week in suburban Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a change in philosophy in the way we deal with sexual
assaults,'' Tatreau said Thursday. ``What we're responding to is a
very serious crime that deserves the best attention we can give to
it to make sure it is prosecuted very aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   While overall violent crime in Los Angeles is down 14 percent
through July 7 compared with the same period last year, there have
been 742 rapes this year, up 8.6 percent from the 683 rapes during
the same period last year, according to the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburban San Fernando Valley, the North Hollywood
Division has seen the biggest increase in rapes -- 60 percent for
the first six months of the year. Rapes are up 33 percent in the
Van Nuys Division for the same period and 48 percent in the
Foothill Division.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD commanders, who recently held a meeting on the surge, are
uncertain what is behind it. In most of the rape reports, the
victim knew the suspect, often as a date, spouse, friend or family
member, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increase could be caused by the ``No Means No''
campaign, a stepped-up effort by rape crisis centers to get victims
to report their attacks, said Jane Blissert, the head prosecutor
for the District Attorney's Office's Sex Crimes Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, it is such an underreported crime,'' she said.
``You don't know if reporting is going up or the crime is going
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Blissert and Patricia Giggans, executive director of the Los
Angeles County Commission on Assaults Against Women, said they have
been impressed with the quality of LAPD rape investigations, but
welcomed the new effort to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad to hear that they are taking it more seriously and
more diligently,'' Giggans said.
</P>
<P>
   Tatreau said the LAPD needs to improve the way investigative
data on rape cases, including suspect-profile information, are
shared by detectives from different divisions.
</P>
<P>
   That has improved somewhat with bureauwide FASTRAC meetings the
department began holding this year, at which command officers use
computer analysis to identify crime trends and share strategies and
data on problem crimes.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is still not enough communication between
detectives working in different parts of the city, Tatreau said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the LAPD is developing a citywide computer tracking
and analysis system that will allow detectives to have easier
access to information from other sex crime investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will include all of the reports citywide with more
information than we are getting now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports will include modus-operandi data and other facts,
such as whether the suspect had a chipped tooth or a tattoo.
``Those are the kinds of things you need,'' Tatreau said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written report to the Police Commission, Parks said Tatreau
and LAPD detectives from the San Fernando Valley and elsewhere have
met with officials of the state Department of Justice to discuss
linking the LAPD crime database with those throughout Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracking `MO' crime trends throughout the city has
historically been accomplished via word-of-mouth, investigator
meetings, reading reports and sorting them by hand and, on a
smaller scale, computer systems,'' the report stated. ``This (new
computer) data will allow detectives to identify suspects, develop
leads, link crimes and identify MO similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   Another step requested by Parks is for the Robbery-Homicide
Division's specialized detectives in sex crimes to handle more
investigations now done by detectives assigned to geographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the shift has been caused by the effects of another
order by Parks -- to have field detectives assigned to major
assault crime desks focus on domestic violence cases, which leaves
investigators with less time for rape investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to pick up a lot more cases than in the past,''
Tatreau said of his division. ``There's a very good expertise in
(the Robbery-Homicide Division), and we have told the (divisions)
we are making ourselves available.''
</P>
<P>
   The department also is considering adding to the number of
Robbery-Homicide Division detectives assigned to handle sexual
assaults.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
