<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT G. DAVIS, 90, PROFESSOR OF ENGLISH AND LITERARY CRITIC
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Gorham Davis, a prolific literary critic and a professor
emeritus of English at Columbia University, died Thursday at the
Vernon Hall Nursing Home in Cambridge, Mass. He was 90 and lived in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was the author of influential studies of John Dos Passos,
C.P. Snow and James Farrell, and he wrote regularly for The New
York Times Book Review, Partisan Review, Commentary and the
American Scholar. He also wrote short stories that appeared in The
New Yorker and was the winner of an O'Henry Award for one of them.
Davis was the editor of an anthology of short stories, ``Ten Modern
Masters,'' and a companion volume, ``Ten Masters of the Modern
Essay,'' which were widely used as texts by college students.
</P>
<P>
   As a young professor at Harvard, Davis had as students John
Simon and Norman Mailer, and it was he who encouraged Mailer to
submit his first short story to Story magazine. The story won the
annual college prize.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also taught at Smith College, in Northampton, Mass., where
one of his students, he said, was Sylvia Plath.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was born in Cambridge in 1908. His father was a banker,
and the family traced its roots in Massachusetts to the landing of
the Mayflower. His grandfather was a Salem sea captain, and among
his forebears was Obed Brooks, a founder of the Brooks Academy, now
the Brooks Museum, in Harwich, Mass. Davis graduated from Harvard
College in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, the writer, Hope Hale Davis, he is
survived by a daughter, Lydia, of Port Ewen, N.Y.; a son, Stephen,
of New York, and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
