<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA COULD RETURN TO DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Dodgers left fielder Bobby Bonilla could become the
next player headed to the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who already spent two weeks on the DL with an
intestinal infection (June 17-July 3), has developed tendinitis in
his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla had an X-ray and an MRI exam on the wrist Thursday in
Los Angeles. It became swollen after Tuesday night's game against
San Francisco and doctors have placed it in a protective cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say he's going on the DL, but it looks like
that could happen,'' general manager Tom Lasorda said. ``One thing
is certain, he will not be joining us here in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   If he goes on the DL, Bonilla would join second baseman Eric
Young, shortstop Jose Vizcaino, pitcher Ramon Martinez and left
fielder Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, 35, underwent surgery on his left wrist during the
off-season. Doctors said a full recovery would take about a year.
Bonilla also had surgery last winter to repair a torn left Achilles
tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla is batting just .202 since joining the Dodgers on May 15
with one homer and 16 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Since getting hits in his first two at-bats Sunday,
first baseman Eric Karros has gone 1 for 15.... After starting the
Dodgers' past 21 games, catcher Charles Johnson was given the night
off. Johnson batted just .160 on the last homestand. He was rested
because the team didn't arrive in St. Louis until 4 a.m. Thursday.
Tom Prince started behind the plate and went 2 for 4 with a double
and run scored.... Former Dodgers second baseman Delino DeShields
is out of the Cardinals' lineup after undergoing arthroscopic
surgery last week on his left knee. DeShields, tied for the NL lead
with seven triples, is due back in early August....
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to get No. 3 hitter Mark McGwire more RBI chances,
St. Louis manager Tony LaRussa has been batting his pitcher eighth
and a position player ninth the past eight games. Since the move,
McGwire is 5 for 23 with three of his pace-setting 40 homers and
five RBI.... Speaking of McGwire and his record home-run pace, ESPN
is in town filming a documentary about all-time single-season
home-run champ Roger Maris, who ended his career with the Cardinals
in 1968.
</P>
</TEXT>
