<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-CAL200-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS IN NO HURRY TO QUALIFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Anything can happen in racing ... or it sure
seemed that way Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 32 cars entered in Saturday's California 200, only five
made qualifying attempts during Bud Pole qualifying that was marred
by 135-degree track temperature at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Harwick, who was the second car out, set the pole with a
lap of 173.779 mph. Scott Gaylord, 17th in order to qualify but the
fifth and final car out, was second at 172.410 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Rauchman, Dean Wanless and Mike Starr were the only other
cars to make attempts and will start third through fifth,
respectively. The remaining 27 cars failed to meet NASCAR Winston
West's five-minute rule and were placed in starting order per 1998
owners points, career owner victories and entry postmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Under Winston West rules, each entry has five minutes to take
the track after the preceding competitor finishes his qualifying
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Defending series champion Butch Gilliland, whose team is based
in Glendora, was placed 11th. Points leader Sean Woodside of Saugus
will start seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it,'' said Kevin Green, NASCAR
Winston West director of public relations. ``In essence, (each
competitor) knew that there were 32 cars trying to make a 36-car
field. Everybody was in the show. So essentially, they were just
standing on their times and using (Thursday's) practice to get
ready for Saturday's race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilliland didn't exactly agree with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready, we were in line,'' Gilliland said. ``I think
with the heat, the two hours of practice, everybody had to work on
the cars a little bit for qualifying. What it is is that (NASCAR)
is trying to run three shows here in a weekend, and it's too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what it is, too, is that NASCAR was flexing their
muscles. They were saying, `If you're not up in line to qualify,
you don't qualify.'''
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures expected to be above or near Thursday's
reading of 103 degrees throughout the weekend, fans attending the
event are advised to drink plenty of liquids and get in the shade
whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is to drink fluids, fluids and more fluids,''
said Dr. Greg Baumann, physician for Penske Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague gets sponsor: NASCAR Craftsman Trucks points-leader Jack
Sprague has obtained sponsorship for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague's No.24 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet S-10 will receive
backing from GMAC with a blue and white paint scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, the 1997 NASCAR Trucks series champion, has finished in
the top 10 at that past 11 events held on a speedway. His last
non-top 10 on a track of one mile or longer came at Texas Motor
Speedway on June 6, 1997, when he finished 31st after suffering a
blown engine.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, who finished 10th at Nazareth (Pa.) last week, begins
the weekend with a 26-point lead over Ron Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet home: Todd Bodine, recently released from ISM
Racing's Winston Cup team, will drive the No.30 Slim Jim Chevrolet
Monte Carlo for Team 34 at this weekend's Busch Grand National
Kenwood 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going home again to Team 34,'' said Bodine, who won the
inaugural Busch event at Fontana last season. ``Throughout my
career, (co-owners) Scott Welliver and Frank Cicci have there for
me when I've needed a place to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to know that I'll be back in such familiar
surroundings and with a team where each and every week I'll have
cars capable of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   HRs and race cars: Mark McGwire and five other major-league
baseball players are owners of the Chevrolet Monte Carlo driven by
Bobby Hillin in Sunday's Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   Fans attending today's Busch qualifying and Sunday's race can be
kept up to date with McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris' home-run
record. The rear deck lid and lower quarter panels of Hillin's car
will display McGwire's current home run total and change each time
he adds to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
