<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERNSTEIN-DANCE-REVIE     07-17 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNSTEIN-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BERNSTEIN DANCES': A REDUCTIVE REVUE OF BERNSTEIN'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Can one imagine Leonard Bernstein as a corn-fed
innocent arriving wide-eyed in the big city? I don't think so. But
that image is the springboard for John Neumeier's ``Bernstein
Dances,'' the tedious but not entirely hopeless dance treatment of
Bernstein's life and art that the Hamburg Ballet presented on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two-and-a-half-hour production, first performed in Germany
last month, was given its U.S. premiere at the New York State
Theater as part of the Bernstein Celebration within Lincoln Center
Festival '98.
</P>
<P>
   That Neumeier intended the work, which he calls a ballet revue,
as a tribute to Bernstein, is a given. With acolytes like this, who
needs critics?
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are dashed early on that Neumeier can place Bernstein the
man within his music in the way that Frederick Ashton did so
profoundly with Arthur Rimbaud in his ballet ``Illuminations,'' set
to Benjamin Britten's music. In the Ashton ballet, one saw the
artist wandering within his art, thanks to a poet-choreographer's
comment on poetry through metaphor, symbol and image and not
without reference to the so-called sordid.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, complexity is equated with simplicity in ``Bernstein
Dances.'' Despite a shrewd use of Bernstein's symphonic and popular
music, Neumeier fails to comment on the urban sophistication of
that music and the cosmopolitan influences that informed
Bernstein's life and his work as a composer and conductor.
</P>
<P>
   To identify the protagonist with a song that tells him to go
back to Ohio, however ironic, misses the mark. But Lloyd Riggins,
in a superbly sustained performance as the Bernstein figure, is
asked to remain a naif, Harvard education notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   He even requires an angel and guide, the only character with a
name in the program credits: Eros. Ivan Urban, certainly angelic
looking with his golden curls and purity of style, takes the hero
on a journey in which he finds his true self. That is, an
accidental embrace with a young man in the beginning is
recapitulated until at the end, the hero acknowledges his
homosexuality with a prolonged male duet at a New York soiree where
mate-swapping is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Like many biographers, Neumeier suggests that aspects of a
private life can illuminate our understanding of an artist. But he
is not a choreographer who knows how to distill the essence of
character and telegraph a basic truth. To reduce the first half of
the ballet to a character's confusion about his sexual identity is
too simple, especially in a ballet about Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Neumeier is at his best in pure-dance works rather than
narrative ballets. ``Bernstein Dances'' falls in between, and what
could have been sharp character vignettes become drawn-out
choreographic episodes. The dancers, in multiple allegorical roles,
are impossible to sort out.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography itself is more idiosyncratic than idiomatic.
The stylized balletic versions of show dancing are too feeble to
offer a real gloss on Broadway musicals, although there is a worthy
attempt at an abstract treatment of the rumble from ``West Side
Story.'' Costumed by Giorgio Armani, the ensemble gets a big number
when the men and women in suits evoke the big city. One of the best
and liveliest ensembles has the women in purple bras under open
purple suit jackets advancing in a wedge behind Jiri Bubenicek, who
erupts into a geyser of leg beats to ``Wrong Note Rag.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Comden and Adolph Green, who wrote the lyrics, were on
hand for the curtain calls, which were shared by the singers,
Angela Horn and Scott Cheffer, as well as Rainer Muhlbach, who
conducted the New York City Opera orchestra. Also taking a bow were
the instrumental soloists: Vadim Gluzman, whose violin solos were
important to the jagged outbursts in the composition inspired by
Plato's Symposium, ``Serenade.'' This piece was intercut by piano
solos played onstage by Sebastian Knauer, one of Riggins' alter
egos.
</P>
<P>
   The lively overture to ``Candide,'' which lifts the mood as
Riggins leads a wedge of dancers in some choreographed curtain
calls, also begins the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Riggins, as the young Bernstein in shorts, is seen slumped over
a piano. The singers sound the theme with the song ``Who Am I''
from ``Peter Pan'' as the composer's lyrics ask, ``Will I ever live
again as a rooster or a hen?'' The transcendental tinge is echoed
later by dancers in fashionable attire who drop into the lotus
position to meditate.
</P>
<P>
   Riggins, an American dancer who excelled in August
Bournonville's ballets in the Royal Danish Ballet, offers a
sensational acting and dance performance. More often than not, he
is surrounded by five others who amplify the hero's emotional life.
Heather Jurgensen is the adult woman in his life, Anna Polikarpova
and Otto Bubenicek get the awkward duets about alienation while
Jiri Bubenicek and Joelle Boulogne move the action along.
</P>
<P>
   Music from ``Facsimile,'' Jerome Robbins' 1946 ballet about a
love triangle, introduces a similar theme. Riggins kisses Ms.
Polikarpova but then finds himself in the arms of a man. Rose Gad
enters to introduce a theme of loneliness. Large in scale, Reinhart
Wolf's photographs of New York form the background as Ms. Gad, held
horizontally by Riggins, seems to levitate and then leaves him with
his arm over an empty chair.
</P>
<P>
   Selections from Bernstein's ``Mass'' attempt to introduce a
spiritual theme. In Part 2, set mostly to ``Serenade,'' the
successful artist looks back on his life. Certainly Neumeier has
ideas: There is a good touch when Ms. Gad adjusts Riggins' tie as
he stands in undershorts and evening jacket. But the last half is
drawn out: a long time to tell a tale of salvation in the city of
perdition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
