</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATIENTS'-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BATTLE LINES ON PATIENTS' RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   Congress is under heavy pressure to pass legislation governing
the operation of health maintenance organizations. Doctors have
been telling patients they are being restricted in giving care.
Patients believe that insurance bureaucrats are making medical
decisions once reserved for physicians. That is why Republicans and
Democrats in the Senate are vying to pass a patients' rights bill
before everyone becomes totally absorbed in the midterm elections.
The competing versions share some common ground, but the Republican
plan has a flawed design. It tries to placate consumer unhappiness
while causing as little inconvenience as possible for the insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The voter heat behind this issue has not been lost on the
Democrats, who have been staging a form of theater in Washington.
Everyone from President Clinton to working doctors has marketed
horror stories about insensitive, profit-driven health maintenance
organizations. All this put a fire under the Republicans, who
released their Senate bill on Wednesday and a House bill Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The competing Senate plans share several core principles. Both
would require HMOs to disclose information on costs, benefits and
quality of care. Both would guarantee emergency care. But there are
two big areas where the Democratic plan is superior. The Democrats
would extend their protections to 150 million health-care
consumers, while the Republicans would limit theirs to the 48
million covered by federally regulated plans in which employers,
mainly big companies, act as their own insurers. The Republicans
argue that the rest are adequately protected by state laws. That is
a subterfuge designed to deter the needed movement toward coverage
for all Americans. The Republican bill in the House is more honest
and less stingy. It would also cover 150 million consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The other big difference involves the law. The Democrats are
insisting that patients have the right to sue HMOs and insurance
companies in state courts when medical benefits are improperly
denied. The Republicans would allow patients to appeal the denial
of benefits to a panel of experts, but would not give them a right
to take the issue to court. This is an unwarranted protection for
corporations. Doctors can be sued when they make an incorrect
medical decision. So should the insurance company that, for
example, denies essential access to a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   There are, to be sure, ways to limit malpractice costs without
sacrificing the legal rights of consumers. The Democrats might
compromise by making review by an independent panel with the power
to award damages a prerequisite to the more extreme step of a legal
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been coy on the issue, but yesterday Clinton
defended the right to sue. ``You can write all the guarantees you
want into law here in Washington,'' he said, ``and if nobody can
enforce them, the delay in the system will still cause people to
die.'' He is right to stand up for the rights of consumers, even
though the GOP will say he is in the pocket of trial lawyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
