<HEADER>
A9551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     07-17 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES 4, METS 2 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any realists affiliated with the Mets had to figure
this was coming. They had crossed their fingers, crossed their legs
and crossed their toes each time a fly ball was hit in Todd
Hundley's direction for the first three games he played left field.
But it was inevitable that, sooner or later, the catcher hiding in
the outfield would mishandle a ball and it would destroy the Mets.
It happened sooner. It happened Thursday night. More than once.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's initial misplay occurred in the first inning, and it
turned the evening into a painful one for the Mets because they
tried to erase it during nine futile innings before succumbing to
the Phillies, 4-2, at Shea Stadium. Two Philadelphia runs scored
because of Hundley's weak judgment in left field in the first
inning, and a third one scored because his mistake kept the inning
percolating.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth run trotted in after Hundley allowed a simple fly to
nick off his glove in the eighth as he was preparing to throw home
for a possible play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're embarrassed,'' Hundley said. ``You're saying, `Where am
I?' I actually had to look around to find out where I was. You can
put this game on me. You can lay this game on my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Rico Brogna doubled into the left-field corner,
and Hundley's throw skidded by the cutoff man for an error that
allowed the runner to reach third base. No run developed, but it
hardly mattered: Hundley's miscues had done enough damage.
</P>
<P>
   So the four-game wild-card showdown between the sputtering and
grimacing Mets and the young and improved Phillies opened with
shabby play afield as well as at bat, where the Mets left 11 on
base.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 20,283 fans frequently booed the slumping Mike
Piazza; for now, Hundley was not verbally berated.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wasted Rick Reed's exceptional effort against the
mortal Mark Portugal and four relievers as they lost for the eighth
time in the last 10 games and the 24th in the last 39 games. The
Phillies, yes, the Phillies (48-44), nudged ahead of the Mets
(46-44) into second place in the National League East and forged
ahead in the wild-card race as well.
</P>
<P>
   A single, an infield popout, a force-play groundout and a rare
walk from Reed put Phillies on first and second with two out in the
first inning. Mike Lieberthal scorched a line drive to left that
should have been the third out. But Hundley froze, then took two
steps forward. As he tried to recover and retreat on the ball,
Hundley stumbled and never even leaped for the ball as it soared
past him and bounced off the left-field fence. Scott Rolen breezed
in from second base and Brogna chugged in from first.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal was awarded a double because Hundley never touched
the ball. The situation was exacerbated when Bobby Abreu singled to
left to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Reed (10-6) had yielded three or fewer earned runs in 13 of 18
starts; the misplay last night made him responsible for three
earned runs. Reed, however, was understanding. ``I wouldn't want to
do what he's doing,'' he said. ``He's still learning the position.
He's going to have games like these where he feels like he wants to
find a hole and crawl in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Manager Bobby Valentine: ``As long as he believes, I'll
believe. It's a tough night for him. I was hoping he wouldn't have
to go through one of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez's bloop single off Portugal (5-2) in the sixth
knocked in the only run off the Phillies' starter. The final Mets
run came on John Olerud's 10th home run in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
