</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HAQ-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAHBUB UL HAQ, 64, ANALYST AND CRITIC OF GLOBAL POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mahbub ul Haq, a former finance minister of Pakistan
and an early proponent of economic liberalization who in later
years argued that poor countries failed to prosper because they
neglected the basic development of their people, died Thursday in
New York. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was pneumonia, said his son, Farhan, a
reporter for the Inter Press Service, a news agency. The elder Haq,
who was visiting New York from Pakistan, collapsed early this week
and did not respond to treatment, former colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Haq, who had also been a governor of the International Monetary
Fund and director of policy planning at the World Bank, was the
author of several books, including ``The Poverty Curtain''
(Columbia University Press) and ``Strategy of Economic Planning''
(Oxford University Press).
</P>
<P>
   But he is best known for his creation in 1990 of an annual Human
Development Index, a measure used by the U.N. Development Program
to measure the wealth of nations by the level of living standards
their citizens have attained.
</P>
<P>
   His views did not make him popular in many developing countries,
nor in some Western capitals, where he also criticized foreign aid
policies and domestic social programs.
</P>
<P>
   A scrappy and articulate debater, he relished the controversies
he provoked. He traveled extensively to speak and gather
information and impressions for the United Nations' annual Human
Development Report, which was built around his index.
</P>
<P>
   James Gustave Speth, administrator of the U.N. Development
Program, said, ``I don't think anybody did more or even as much as
Mahbub did to bring balance back to development thinking when
everyone else was worshipping at the altar of GNP growth.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the U.N. Development Program in 1995, Haq returned
to Pakistan to establish the Human Development Center for South
Asia with the help of his wife, Khadija Khanum, an economist.
Measures of human progress in the region, especially in India and
Pakistan, had begun to slip badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``After producing seven global Human Development Reports, I had
to face the sad reality that the real challenge to human
development lay back home, in Pakistan and South Asia,'' he said.
``South Asia has been sinking fast into a quagmire of human
deprivation and despair, emerging as the most deprived region of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Haq, who is survived by his daughter, Toneema, as well as his
wife and son, studied at Punjab University in Pakistan, King's
College in Cambridge, Yale and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He was born on Feb. 22, 1934, and while still in his 20s he
became the chief economist of Pakistan's national planning
commission. In the 1980s, under the late President Mohammed Zia-ul
Haq, he served as minister of commerce, planning and finance. He
moved to Washington and the World Bank in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of the Third World Forum, a panel for discussing
development issues, Haq was also an adviser to the Brandt
Commission, which looked into economic relations between the rich
and poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time, he was a great reader of literature and
poetry. In 1985 he wrote a volume of poems titled ``An Elusive
Dawn.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I have struggled for a long time with the concept and practice
of development,'' Haq wrote in the preface to the first report on
Human Development in South Asia, in 1997. ``Emerging from the
Western citadels of learning _ Cambridge, Yale, Harvard _ in the
1950s, I was armed with the firm neoclassical conviction that the
real purpose of development was to increase national income.'' Over
half a century, he increasingly doubted that analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is widespread consensus today,'' he wrote, ``that the
purpose of development is not just to enlarge incomes but to
enlarge people's choices, and that these choices extend to a decent
education, good health, political freedom, cultural identity,
personal security, community participation, environmental security
and many other areas of human well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``A link between growth and human lives must be created through
conscious national planning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
