<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-DIRECTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY, WOMEN DIRECTORS WORKING LESS, REPORT SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Advocates for women and minorities trying to make
their way in Hollywood were outraged by a new report that shows
they are getting less and less work even as the movie and
television industry is booming.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 billion motion-picture and TV production industry added
17 percent more jobs in 1997. In 1998, the industry is expected to
have 12 percent more available, more than five times the county's
overall growth rate for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 of those jobs last year went to movie and TV
directors. Yet women and minorities worked 900 fewer days in 1997
than they did in 1996, according to a report released Thursday by
the Directors Guild of America.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics elicited cries of anger from those in the
industry actively working to get more women and minorities into top
Hollywood positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very telling that some things are hard to
change,'' said Iris Grossman, president of Women in Film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers speak for themselves. If there are men and women
out there, both of whom are qualified for the jobs, why aren't
women getting them?''
</P>
<P>
   The total number of days worked in 1997 by women film directors
dropped from 4,233 to 3,411. That's a decrease of 1.8 percent of
the total number of days worked by DGA women film directors in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Shea, president of the DGA, said he and the guild have been
working hard to solve that problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 3,000 more days worked, why should the women drop from
8.8 percent to 7 percent (of the total days worked)?'' Shea said
Thursday. ``That's a disastrous drop for women.''
</P>
<P>
   By pressing motion-picture companies to hire more women,
African-Americans, Latinos, Asian-Americans and other minorities,
the DGA has made progress, Shea said, adding that it appears
studios and the guild need to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need to get them out there where people can meet
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The DGA has tracked the number of minorities and women landing
directorial positions since 1983, the year the guild sued Columbia
Pictures and Warner Bros. for discriminatory hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was dismissed -- the judge ruled the guild couldn't
file a class-action lawsuit on behalf of women and minorities --
but it acted as a catalyst to the DGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, for a while, quite a white-male thing,'' Shea said of
directorial work in Hollywood. ``There seemed to have been
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for the inequity could be an age-old Hollywood
practice, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a networking business to a great extent,'' Shea said.
``That's how a lot of deals are made.''
</P>
<P>
   To change that, the DGA is staging mixers and seminars to get
exposure for women and minorities who don't have access to people
with the power to make their professional dreams come true.
</P>
<P>
   Nanci Rossov, a veteran theater director, founded Filmanthropic,
a new film production company, in large part to help newcomers get
the needed experience to get work in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad,'' Rossov said of the DGA's findings. ``The numbers
were small to begin with. This is perhaps disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time that the report reveals a discouraging
trend, Rossov said, it highlights the need for organizations like
Filmanthropic and work like the report compiled by the DGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a Catch-22,'' she said. ``It takes a lot of
knowledge and experience to be a director. But how do you get
experience if you don't have it?''
</P>
<P>
   Rossov is directing a Filmanthropic production titled
``Unbowed,'' a love story between a Lakota warrior and an
African-American woman.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
