<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Angels could not believe their good fortune as
they sailed through June, carried in large part by a starting
rotation that included two journeymen and a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The journeymen (Steve Sparks and Omar Olivares) and the rookie
(Jarrod Washburn) were a combined 12-3 when July began. Since then,
however, the baseball gods have determined there is a limit on such
luck.
</P>
<P>
   The three have combined to go 0-7 in July, which includes
Sparks' worst outing of the season in Thursday night's 8-1 loss to
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays before 24,015 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks (3-2), who lasted only one-plus inning, gave up five runs
and three hits. His biggest problem was that he couldn't find the
plate with his knuckleball -- he walked five, matching a
season-high.
</P>
<P>
   Normally against the last-place Devil Rays, a comeback might be
possible. But the Rays had 29-year-old rookie Rolando Arrojo on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, who defected from Cuba two years ago, gave up just one
run and three hits in seven innings, improving to 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels remained 1 1/2 games ahead of
second-place Texas in the A.L. West. Oakland, though, moved to
within seven games of the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks lost his previous start on July 11, but he could be
forgiven. He gave up only two runs and four hits in 6 1/3 innings
to Seattle, but lost to Randy Johnson, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   He had no such excuse on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays went into the game ranked last in the American
League in team batting average and last in the majors in runs
scored. All one really needs to know about the Rays' offense is
that that their cleanup hitter Thursday was Dave Martinez (.253,
seven homers, 35 RBIs going into the game).
</P>
<P>
   The Rays haven't scored more than eight runs in a game since
April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks' knuckleball stayed out of the strikezone and the Rays
didn't have to swing much to score. He made 57 pitches, and the
Rays swung at only 14.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was Aaron Ledesma's two-run single in a five-run
first inning. Quinton McCracken also drove in a run with a single
in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The other two runs came on bases-loaded walks to Paul Sorrento
and Miguel Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson, who figures to replace one of the three in the
rotation soon, relieved Sparks and pitched well. He gave up one run
-- an RBI single by Ledesma -- and five hits in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite falling behind, 5-0, after the first inning, the Angels
had a chance to get back into it. Singles by Garret Anderson and
Phil Nevin, and an error by Ledesma at shortstop resulted in one
run for the Angels in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 5-1 in the third, Darin Erstad led off with a walk and
Dave Hollins walked. But Jim Edmonds killed the rally when hit a
linedrive to the first baseman Sorrento, who doubled up Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon followed with a walk, but Arrojo responded by
retiring the next 12 hitters in a row. The streak was broken with
two out in the seventh when Justin Baughman reached on an error by
Cairo at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo got help from two relievers, and the Angels didn't get a
hit after Erstad's leadoff single in the third.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
