<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-VICTIM-NYT &LR;      07-17 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-VICTIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY PRAISE TO THOUSANDS AFTER VAIN BID TO SAVE A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Melissa Moy first asked people to help her
leukemic younger sister, Cindy, in January, she knew that the odds
were not good. Cindy, Melissa told people, had only a few months to
live if she could not find an appropriate bone marrow donor. And
historically, Melissa realized, an Asian-American's chance of
finding a match was slim, because of a longstanding Asian belief
that donating any part of one's body made one's soul incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,500 people in the United States, Canada and Asia
volunteered to have their bone marrow tested for Ms. Moy, a bright
lawyer who grew up in Queens, the youngest of three daughters of
Chinese immigrants. Many of the volunteers were Asian, according to
accounts in the Chinese-language press.
</P>
<P>
   A machinist in Singapore was determined to be a match for her.
And on March 20, doctors performed a transplant at the Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan, giving Cindy more time.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Moy succumbed to the cancer on July 9 at the
hospital; she was only 28. Still, her family was grateful that she
had somehow defied the odds for just a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this difficult period, Cindy's spirits were constantly
uplifted by the thousands of people who brought her great comfort
in their get-well wishes,'' said a Web page put up by the Moy
family. ``We hope that as a result of Cindy's case, awareness of
this incredibly painful disease has been heightened, and more
people will come forward to join the donor pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Moy's story was notable because her family made a very
public appeal on her behalf. Articles appeared in the
Chinese-language press, as well as in The Daily News, Newsday, The
Chicago Sun-Times and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Moys contacted more than a dozen Asian bone marrow banks,
and organized bone marrow drives in the United States and Asia,
some through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   After the operation, Ms. Moy improved enough so that by June,
she was able to return home, her sister said in an interview on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a precious time for a close family. ``We were enjoying
the simple things in life, like going to Central Park and walking
to a favorite Italian restaurant of hers,'' Melissa Moy said. ``The
simple things that you take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Moy had graduated from the Bronx High School of Science in
1988 and received a Bachelor of Science degree from New York
University in 1992. In 1996, she graduated from Benjamin Cardozo
Law School. Linda, the middle sister, is a doctor. Melissa, the
oldest, is a graduate of Columbia Business School and a banker.
Their father, Fee Yee Moy, is an engineer; their mother, Suk Yee
Wong, is a homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   But on July 5, Cindy fell ill again. She was rushed back to
Sloan-Kettering. She never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   After Ms. Moy's death was announced in the Chinese-language
press last week, many people mourned. So the family has scheduled a
public wake on Sunday at Ng Fook Funeral Services at 36 Mulberry
Street in Chinatown. Donations to the Moy Fund (77 East 12th
Street, Apartment 7A, New York, N.Y. 10003-5005) are to go to the
Singapore Marrow Donor Programme.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Times in March, Melissa hinted at how
the family's campaign to find donors had come a long way. ``When
you grow up in China, you believe that once something leaves your
body it's never replaced,'' she said. ``It's very difficult to
overcome that, even with your own family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
