<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-WINE-$ADV19-1     07-17 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-WINE-$ADV19-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLING A SECOND-CAREER DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 19)  
(mk) 
 By ALICE FEIRING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you've socked away a fortune, developed a passion for wine
and have decided to ditch the rat race, take to the country and
make an award-winning bottle of vino. Quite a goal, especially if
the closest you've come to agriculture for the last 30 years is
mowing the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you never know. Consider Norman Kiken. He used to have the
tidy hands of an accountant, but now, they are nicked and scraped,
just like a farmer's, as he enters his fifth year as a winemaker in
the Napa Valley of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Kiken's interest in wine started innocently enough. It was 1973,
he was 30, and he read an article about wine in his dentist's
office while waiting for a root canal. With characteristic
enthusiasm, he plunged into intense study and tasting. Twenty years
later, to the shock of his New Jersey wine-tasting group, he quit
his job as chief financial officer at Leucadia National Corp., an
insurer in Manhattan, and with his wife, Evelyn, headed west.
</P>
<P>
   Kiken (pronounced KICK-en) bought 40 acres on Diamond Mountain
in the Napa region, outside Calistoga, for $1.4 million and built
himself a home and a winery, called Reverie. His modest goal was to
make ``the best red wine in the world.'' He is not there yet, but
he is gaining considerable acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, The Wine Spectator cited Reverie as one of a dozen new
wineries to watch. Then came a recommendation by Robert Parker Jr.,
the wine rater. ``Terrific raspberry nose that leaps from the
glass,'' Parker wrote in his publication, The Wine Advocate, of
Kiken's 1995 Cabernet Franc, priced at $35. Kiken now sells every
bottle he produces, and his wines are on the lists of restaurants
like Jean Georges and the Four Seasons in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kiken has had more rapid success than others, he is by no
means the only winemaking refugee from the corporate world. Lewis
Perdue of Wine Investment News, an industry newsletter, calls it a
trend. ``There are certainly more of these change-of-life
winemakers now than 10 years ago,'' he said. ``It's a function of
people being successful in other careers who love wine and who like
the lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, he said, are dilettantes, people with vacation
homes in wine country who become weekend gentlemen-farmers.
``They'll plant a few acres of vines,'' Perdue said. ``But they
know nothing about making wine. They need the professional vineyard
management companies who can plan, run and harvest the vineyard.
They need consulting winemakers and enough facilities to lease.
This kind of support mechanism didn't exist 15 years ago. But now
it's in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Others get their hands dirty, and not just in Napa. Antony
Champ, the former chief executive of Fiber Industries, a polyester
producer in Charlotte, N.C., took a buyout offer in 1989 and wound
up making wine in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kiken, Champ was in his early 50s when he jumped corporate
ship. He and his wife, Edith, traveled around wine-growing areas
before deciding where to plant vines and build their home.
</P>
<P>
   They considered the West Coast, but not too seriously. ``We
could afford it,'' he said, ``but it's not our style. We're East
Coast people.''
</P>
<P>
   They dismissed upstate New York because of the cold winters.
Long Island? Too much traffic. They found a site in Crozet, Va.,
under the shadows of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Champs planted their grapes in 1991 and their winery, White
Hall, lost money for five years before breaking even on a cash-flow
basis last year. Reaching that point took longer _ and was more
backbreaking _ than Champ had thought.
</P>
<P>
   He joins vineyard managers and other hands in working the
fields. ``We currently have 18 acres with about 500 vines per
acre,'' he said.``We visit each vine about four times a season. We
tie them. Position them. Prune them. Weed them. We're walking the
acreage. And consider that right now it's in the high 90s down
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fall crush comes, we harvest the fruit into lugs,''
he said, referring to the containers used to convey the ripe
grapes. ``Last year we handled 57 tons of grapes, so we're carrying
all of that in 30-pound parcels at a time. During the crush,
especially if we have to pick the grapes quickly before bad weather
comes, we could be having 20-hour days.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Champs have no complaints. The winemaking life, they
say, is refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In parts of the business world, people will cut your throat
for a tenth of a cent, but not here,'' he said. ``If you're in a
jam, people help you out in this industry. It's more about
community than making money.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this is a labor of love, not a fabulous
investment. First-time winemakers hear ad nauseam the old joke:
``How to make a small fortune in the wine business? Start with a
large one.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have work experience that can translate. Champ had a
background in chemistry and experience in marketing. And when
Leucadia invested in a financially troubled California winery,
Kiken learned about the potential financial pitfalls of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Kiken had no marketing or sales experience, so he has learned on
the fly about finding distributors and working the market, choosing
to sell only in California and states he likes to visit: New York,
New Jersey and Florida. On such trips, he makes contacts and sales
calls and attends trade shows. He also publishes a chatty
semiannual newsletter, updating winery visitors about the harvest,
new varietals and the like.
</P>
<P>
   But can such vintners make money? That is generally not the
goal, Perdue said. ``When people make lifestyle choices like this,
they're looking for a break-even situation, or something that
doesn't lose too much money,'' he said. ``Having a gigantic return
on assets doesn't figure in as one of the prime considerations.''  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vic Motto of Motto, Kryla &AMP; Fisher, an accounting firm in St.
Helena, Calif., specializing in the wine industry, has held
people's hands through the winemaking process for 16 years. ``If
you don't have a million dollars of annual discretionary assets,
you probably shouldn't even think of entering the market,'' Motto
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical winemaker with a winery invests $3 to $5 for every
dollar of sale, less for a custom crush,'' he added. ``Can you make
money? Maybe in 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a devoted winemaker can see a decent return, especially
by entering the market with wine that sells for at least $20 a
bottle. ``Wine has never been as profitable as it has been in the
past three years,'' said Jon Fredrickson of Gomberg, Fredrickson &AMP;
Associates, a San Francisco company that tracks the industry.
``There have been at least 10 times more successful start-up
wineries than failures.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical winery investor who visits Mark Brody, a vice
president and manager at the commercial banking office of Sanwa
Bank in San Francisco, is male and 50 or older _ and someone who
could easily start his business without a loan but does not want to
tie up that much cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go for so many years without making a dime in this
business,'' Brody said, ``that people who come to us for wine money
must have deep pockets themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley is the most expensive viticultural area in the
country. Land already planted with disease-resistant, grape-bearing
vines sells for more than $60,000 an acre. Plantable land costs
considerably less _ $20,000 an acre. But going the bargain route
involves as many as five years for the vines to bear usable fruit,
and a minimum of two more years to get the bottles on the shelves.
That is a seven-year wait to see any return on investment _ six
years if the product is white wine, which requires less aging.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the large overhead involved, prudent newcomers ease
their way into the business. The cheapest way to start _ the
``custom crush'' method _ is to rent equipment and to buy other
people's grapes.
</P>
<P>
   This path is commonplace; Kiken said it takes $250,000 to
produce a modest 2,500 cases. Three to four years later, when those
cases finally reach the shelves, profitability is unlikely, but
cash-flow break-even can be reached, he said, if the bottles each
sell at $22 to $23.
</P>
<P>
   A key point in this kind of operation is to sign up a
high-profile winemaker as a consultant, even though these services
might start at $18,000 and run as high as six figures for a few
months of work. Such consultants can provide contacts for buying
the crucial, first-rate grapes, and can attract attention for a new
winery _ assuring that premium prices can be charged, even by an
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Produced this way, a red wine, from crush to bottle, could be
ready for that Robert Parker rating in little more than 18 months.
Kiken started out on a variation of this plan, but he always used
his own grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with a custom job,'' Kiken said,
``except that the more control you have over your wine, the more
you can control your own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, the banker, warns every prospective winery owner seeking
a loan about the risks and the barriers. Even so, he admits to some
envy. With complete conviction, he asked, ``Doesn't everyone who
loves wine has a dream to make it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
