<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JACOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGINA JACOBS HAS A LIST OF ACCOMPLISHMENTS ABOUT A MILE LONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Since the early 1980s, American track and field has
showcased such female stars as Florence Griffith Joyner, Jackie
Joyner-Kersee, Mary Slaney, Gail Devers, Joan Benoit Samuelson and
now Marion Jones. All this time, Regina Jacobs has been there,
quietly winning titles and breaking records.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1997, the Californian won seven U.S. championships
at 1,500 meters outdoors. Four weeks ago, in the oppressive heat of
New Orleans, she won the national title at 5,000 meters with a
blazing last 400-meter lap in 59.8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's world outdoor championship, she won the silver
medal at 1,500 meters, the only American woman or man to capture a
medal at that distance or longer. As a full-time runner, she earns
a six-figure income.
</P>
<P>
   With all those credentials, Jacobs, at age 34, remains a great
unknown. On July 4 in Brunswick, Maine, she set an American record
of 14 minutes 56.06 seconds for 5,000 meters, but few people have
heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   Her next race should gain more attention. On Monday night in the
remodeled Mitchel Athletic Complex in Uniondale, N.Y., she will run
the Goodwill Games women's mile against such stars as Svetlana
Masterkova, the Russian who won two gold medals in the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics, Suzy Hamilton of the United States and Sonia O'Sullivan
of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect from one who holds a bachelor's degree in
English and communications from Stanford and a master's in business
administration from the University of California, Jacobs accepts
that others are more famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it,'' Jacobs said on Thursday. ``But then
I'll walk through an airport and the person behind the desk will
say: `Oh, I know you. You going to run somewhere?' And coming home
from a trip, I was walking through the Chicago airport when I
overheard a young man saying to his friend, `I told you it was
her.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Craig is Jacobs' husband and coach. ``I think she's like
Martina Navratilova,'' he said. ``It took years before people
realized how good Martina was. Regina has been out there a long
time as a journeywoman. Only in the last three years did she break
out. In our society, everything has to be now.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakout will be more dramatic with another fast 1,500
meters. Slaney and O'Sullivan have come close, but no women has
broken all three barriers: 2 minutes for 800 meters, 4 minutes for
1,500 meters and 15 minutes for 5,000 meters. Jacobs' respective
bests are 1:59.36, 4:00.46 and 14:52.49.
</P>
<P>
   Until December 1996, Jacobs seldom ran anything longer than a
mile. Then O'Sullivan ran away from her in the Waikiki Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Tom why,'' Jacobs said, ``and he said it because she
trained like a 5,000-meter runner with 1,500-meter speed. He said
if you want to be strong, you have to do 5,000-meter training along
with 1,500-meter training. I had not done the mileage, and who
wants to do long workouts for the 5,000 when you can do short ones
for the 1,500? But I decided I would do hard interval training.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig remembered. ``She said the pain was so bad that it was
like going to the dentist,'' he said, ``but she did the work. The
day after that Waikiki race, she ran six miles. The next day, she
ran eight 800's with a one-minute recovery. They weren't fast, but
it was a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' lithe, 5-foot-6-inch, 112-pound body blends unusual
speed with unusual strength, and she enjoys racing now at any
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the competition,'' she said. ``I love being in the best
possible shape and being next to someone doing the same thing.
That's exhilarating. If I feel that, it doesn't matter who wins or
loses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs has heroines of her own in the 39-year-old Slaney and
Merlene Ottey, the 38-year-old Jamaican sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to see people like Mary Slaney and Merlene Ottey
still competing,'' Jacobs said. ``Seeing older people do that
confirms for me that I can do that. I don't worry about getting
older. Every year I get better and better and my mind gets stronger
and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me if I wished I was 25 again. I said no, that
I'd hate it. A certain confidence comes with getting older. You
know your limits. You know how far you can push yourself. I have a
focus, an inner strength, a confidence I didn't have when I was
younger.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
