<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT CARDINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Tom Lasorda waded across the crowded Dodgers
clubhouse for only one reason _ to plant a kiss on the cheeks of
Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, the Dodgers new general manager, knows there is only
one way to save this season. It's using his old shtick to pump up
his indifferent team.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda then pulled back from Valdes, who had just defeated the
St. Louis Cardinals 8-2 Thursday night at Busch Stadium and yelled
in Spanish ``if you pitch like this, you will make the big money.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a thought seemed unlikely under the old regime of manager
Bill Russell and pitching coach Goose Gregson.
</P>
<P>
   Russell and Valdes nearly came to blows last season in the
dugout during a game.Valdes and Gregson never were in sync.
</P>
<P>
   But since those two were let go last month, Valdes has shown
signs of the pitcher who won 28 games in his first two full
major-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what it has meant to me to have Tommy
around,'' Valdes said. ``The communication is so much better. We
laugh a lot, we joke around. He gives me big hugs. He makes me feel
like I am part of something.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 90-degree night, Valdes (7-9) limited the Cardinals to six
hits and two runs. He struck out eight and did not walk a batter.
Perhaps just as important, Valdes shut down Cardinals' slugger Mark
McGwire, who is bidding to break Roger Maris' single-season record
of 61 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes also moved the Dodgers a half game closer in the National
League wild-card race. They are five games behind idle San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how important he is to this team,'' Lasorda said.
``I'm not trying to change anything mechanical. All I want to do is
put my arm around him and show him that we care.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt Thursday that Valdes was supported by eight runs,
including seven in the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi hit his 21st homer and Gary Sheffield added his
16th, both off Cardinals' left-hander Kent Mercker (5-7).
</P>
<P>
   For Mondesi, it was his fifth homer and 14th and 15th RBI since
moving to the third spot in the order 15 games ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield also had two singles and has reached base in 28
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Wilton Guerrero, who went 7 for 18 in place of injured Eric
Young during the Dodgers' recent homestand, had three hits and
scored two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens it makes everything easier,'' said Valdes,
who left after seven with a cramp in his right leg. ``I have felt
my confidence building in the last few weeks but when you get a
game like that, it really soars.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence is the biggest change new pitching coach Charlie
Hough sees in Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Including his two-hit, 1-0 victory over Oakland on June 10, and
a near-perfect game versus Pittsburgh on June 26, Valdes has won
just three times. But his earned run average has dropped from 5.48
to 4.12.
</P>
<P>
   All that is good news for Valdes, who is eligible for salary
arbitration after the season. He is earning $2.8 million in 1998
and could double that with a big year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Valdes also won on the road, where he came in 2-6 with
a 5.30 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember this guy is just 24 years old,'' Hough
said. ``There is still so much to learn. He has to learn to pitch
on the nights when he doesn't have his best stuff. That can be
tough. Right now, he is back on his game. It is great to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
