<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
  
Christenson Ignites A's Victory  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Even Rickey Henderson wasn't on to A's rookie
center fielder Ryan Christenson coming into the year, so you can't
really blame Royals manager Tony Muser for just not getting it.
</P>
<P>
   Christenson was a walk-on back at Pepperdine University, before
he played his way into a scholarship and led his conference in
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   He has always been the anti-Grieve, the guy who comes along with
no fanfare but plays like a guy you should have been trumpeting the
whole time. He's Mike Bordick, only in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Muser played the percentages Thursday, intentionally walking
Mike Blowers in the sixth to face Christenson with the bases loaded
and the game tied 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense on paper, going for the double play. But in
real life, Christenson has yet to hit into a double play this
season in 163 at-bats, and he wasn't about to start, not after he
had been challenged. He singled to left to bring home two runs and
kick-start the A's toward a 5-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't insulted,'' Christenson said. ``It's the play to do.
But you do kind of take it personally. You want to get a little
respect out of it. You want to plant a seed in his mind that next
time he wouldn't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Muser did not exactly give his choice the hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a real fix, tie ballgame, one out, grasping for
straws,'' he said. ``Maybe we'd get a double play. We took a chance
on getting a double play some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up as just one more spike in the up-and-down realities
of A's manager Art Howe's ongoing memoir, ``Life With the Kids.''
This time, it was a beautiful thing watching as another talented
A's rookie found out a little more about himself as a ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Christenson has been the A's top center fielder since Jason
McDonald went down in May, and he has become a fixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not really expected to be on the team, you want to
show you belong,'' Henderson said. ``He got a break and he's done a
lot with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Christenson is a guy you can watch every minute he's out there.
He doesn't just run hard when he pops up a ball into the shallow
outfield, he busts it down the line and makes his crisp turn just
as if he has foreknowledge the ball is going to drop. If it doesn't
fall, he lopes back to the dugout, just happy to be giving it his
all.
</P>
<P>
   He has such great instincts in center field, the lines he traces
are clean and eloquent. You almost want to see them collected and
superimposed on a TV screen, like the arcs traced by the long balls
during the All-Star Game homer contest.
</P>
<P>
   The result, at the very least, would be a whole lot better than
anything by LeRoy Neiman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably one of the best center fielders in the league,''
teammate Matt Stairs said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to starter Blake Stein's fine effort, the A's (45-49)
bounced back from an anemic little loss to the Royals the night
before. They are back to four games under .500, and they get three
games against Minnesota (42-51 going into Thursday) this weekend to
try to improve that mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge win,'' Stairs said. ``We took Kansas City maybe
a little lightly. Today we kind of woke up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein gave up two runs in the third, and that was all. He held
the Royals to four hits in his 7 1/3 innings, and seems to be
gaining something as the season progresses. He was more fluid, more
confident, than earlier in the year, and that was one more plus for
a rotation on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, A's starters are 4-1 and have given up
just eight earned runs in 571/3 innings for a 1.25 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
