<HEADER>
A9581 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-JENKS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-17 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-JENKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Woods Back in The Hunt &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; SOUTHPORT, England _ I was next in line at the portable toilet
when Tiger Woods suddenly appeared, with no time to spare on his
way to the 10th tee.
</P>
<P>
   What a great opportunity to become an obnoxious American, like
the guys who heckled Colin Montgomerie at the Olympic Club. ``No
dice, pal,'' I would say to Tiger. ``Get in line like the rest of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lurching back to reality, I moved back about five paces. At
Royal Birkdale Thursday, the whole British Open stepped aside for
him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific slice of the Tiger Woods we like to see: Out
in front, crushing his drives, lofting gentle chip shots and
sinking the big putts. I spent 18 holes watching him get back into
the major-tournament mainstream. It was just one round, but like
all the great ones _ Hogan, Snead, Palmer, Nicklaus _ Tiger doesn't
need much to stir up attention. By the final five holes of his
opening-round 65, his gallery looked like the Champs-Elysees on
World Cup Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a shocking development, the British summer arrived along with
Tiger. I walked to the first hole in a long-sleeved shirt,
turtleneck and heavy windbreaker, just out of habit after three icy
days. By about the 5th hole, I wanted to grab a pair of trunks and
race out to the Irish Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just perfect,'' said Woods. ``I think you might get
some people with heat stroke out here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a rich and satisfying summer they have over here, by the
way. It might last all the way to this morning. By this afternoon,
they're expecting a grim return to rainstorms and high winds,
lasting right through tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that sounds a bit more like it,'' said crafty Nick
Price, who was in Woods' threesome Thursday and shot a crisp 66.
``This stuff today is too good to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' gallery saw many sides of him Thursday. They saw him
jogging purposefully on a bathroom break (his first of two, after
the 4th hole), and he looked good doing it. You'd imagine him
running the 400 meters and smoking the field.
</P>
<P>
   They also saw Tiger on his hands and knees, looking for someone
else's ball. What a way to start the British: Per-Ulrik Johansson
hit his very first tee shot into high shrubbery, surely scattering
a few newts and bar-tailed godwits into hiding. Even with course
marshals at the ready, this baby was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The three players searched for nearly two minutes before they
found it, hopelessly buried. Johansson got a penalty drop, took a
triple-bogey and did damn well to finish at 74 with his two
partners playing so spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   This was a fabulous day to be out on the course. It's an awfully
far cry from the Olympic Club or so many great American layouts
with their steep hills and massive trees. Here you look across the
flatlands forever, as far as the eye can see. The crowds appear to
be larger because they're so prominent: a sight of humanity _ or
anything _ on the stark landscape. Stately, red-brick houses loom
far in the distance. If there ever was an Earl of Shank, he
probably lived in one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is exceptionally polite, acting only in unison with
tremendously polite applause. The occasional out-of-context shout
is heard, but most of these people sound like BBC television
commentators, whispering under their breath as a shot lands on the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well-played.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Struck with purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Journalists have read all week about Royal Birkdale's celebrated
wildlife. It remained something of a mystery Thursday. I didn't see
a single toad, mute swan or moorhen (although I heard they'd all
gone off to join Lee Westwood's gallery).
</P>
<P>
   The human faces were priceless, though. I saw a lot of
dignified, white-haired gentlemen who reminded me of my San
Francisco-raised father-in-law, the good Irishman Joe Stanton. And
there's another distinct brand of British Isles spectator, a
craggy, red-nosed sort who loves his Famous Grouse Whiskey and
looks like he's been working an anvil for the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and rugged, but mostly craggy, these guys are course
fixtures _ caddies, players, or just lovers of the game. They speak
English, but in a manner impossible to understand. It falls
somewhere in the middle of Scottish, cockney and craggy.
</P>
<P>
   One of these men spotted my press badge and addressed me as I
walked along the 15th hole Thursday. Dearly wanting to respond, I
became a fake but instant Scot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aye, the gorse,'' I said. ``Aww, it's one wee bonny of a
firth.''
</P>
<P>
   The man grimaced at me, revealing two of his three teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The most pleasant fellow on the grounds? Tiger Woods, in a real
upset. He was delighted with his patience and maturity out there,
managing the course like Old Tom Morris himself. As the day
progressed, steady hands like Fred Couples, Ernie Els, Justin
Leonard and Bernhard Langer found themselves in hopeless,
deep-in-the-rough predicaments. Tiger seemed to be living a charmed
life all day.
</P>
<P>
   Normally somewhat aloof, in his own little world, Woods had some
nice interactions with the crowd _ reporters, even. Passing a group
of us as he walked down a dirt road from the 14th tee, he smiled
and said, ``Moseying along the old dusty trail ... when you get on
the grass, it's amazing how quiet it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   That can mean only one thing. Life is a little too good at the
British Open. With any luck today, there will be no sleet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
