A9586 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-2NDLD-W     07-17 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT REJECTS EFFORT TO KEEP SECRET SERVICE OFFICIALS FROM
TESTIFYING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 12th and 13th grafs for new material on Justice Department's
latest petition to Supreme Court)  (With CLINTON-STARR-TEXT) 
(sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Acting with unusual speed, nine judges on the
federal appeals court here unanimously rejected a last-minute
request by the Clinton administration to block the testimony of
Secret Service officials, including the head of President Clinton's
protective detail, in the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department immediately responded with an emergency
petition forwarded to Chief Justice William Rehnquist of the
Supreme Court. The sealed petition asks Rehnquist, who is in Europe
while the court is in recess, to delay any testimony by Secret
Service officials until the full court can consider the
administration's appeal, lawyers involved in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief order on Thursday, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia declined the administration's request
to have the full bench reconsider the argument for a novel
privilege that would shield Secret Service officials from having to
testify. A three-judge panel of the appeals court had sided with
the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, on the issue just last
week. The administration's move was seen as a desperate gambit,
particularly because the full court does not often grant such
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   And a terse order issued earlier on Thursday by three of the
nine appeals judges once again signaled that the administration
faced long odds. ``We also believe, for the reasons stated in our
opinion of July 7, 1998, that the Justice Department's likelihood
of success before the Supreme Court is insufficient to warrant
further delay in the grand jury's investigation,'' said the three
judges, who first heard the appeal last month.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, had sought the testimony of a few uniformed Secret
Service officers for several months. After court decisions were
issued in his favor, including the appellate ruling last week by
the three-judge panel involved in Thursday's action, Starr cast a
wider net this week. He subpoenaed the agents closest to President
Clinton, setting off a firestorm of criticism by administration
officials and laying the groundwork for a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was punctuated by a flurry of legal briefs and
rapid-fire court rulings that started early on as seven Secret
Service officials under subpoena prepared to enter the grand jury
room on Thursday morning. Their testimony was temporarily put off
at the last minute so that appeals could be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, administration officials began bracing
for the possibility that some of the agents may have to appear as
early as next week when the grand jury resumes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agents subpoenaed this week was Larry Cockell, the
head of Clinton's detail who spends more time with the president
than any other Government employee. Anticipating that Cockell, an
18-year-veteran of the Secret Service, may soon have to spend
considerable time being questioned, the agency on Thursday
temporarily reassigned him to a less demanding job. Officials said
it would be impossible for him to be at the president's side in
Washington and on the road if he must also spend time as a grand
jury witness.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision on Thursday moves the Secret Service
officials one step closer to testifying before the grand jury, it
also foreshadows future court disputes between the independent
counsel and the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's private lawyers have expressed concern that
investigators may ask Secret Service agents what they may have
overheard of conversations between Clinton and his lawyers. Such
questions would be all but certain to prompt a new round of legal
wrangling over the parameters of the lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The blanket rejection of the administration's appeal came
remarkably quick, just two days after Attorney General Janet Reno
pleaded for the judges to intervene and avert what she said ``is
likely to result in a national tragedy.'' The Secret Service has
been maintained that if agents are forced to testify, they will no
longer be able to protect the president adequately because he could
be inclined to push them away.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, the Justice Department filed another
petition asking the Supreme Court to consider the case on the
merits. ``History leaves no doubt that the nation will face future
Presidential assassination attempts,'' the brief stated. ``The
Secret Service stands between the Nation and the calamity of
assassination. The Court of Appeals' refusal to recognize the
protective function privilege will undermine the Secret Service's
ability to step into the breach and protect the Nation from
profound and predictable peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Its first emergency petition was lodged early on Wednesday night
with the clerk of the court. And it moved on Thursday have the
papers put in Rehnquist's hands. The appellate court gave the
Secret Service until Friday at noon to seek a stay from Rehnquist.
But the order by the three appeals court judges reduced the chances
that the chief justice would intervene.
</P>
<P>
   They found that the Justice Department had failed to show a stay
was necessary to avert an ``irreparable harm.'' Supreme Court
practice requires Rehnquist to make such a finding before issuing
any stays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Justice has not made a sufficient showing
that irreparable harm will result unless a stay and an order are
issued, and it has not made a sufficient showing that it will
ultimately prevail in establishing the privilege it alleges,''
wrote the three judges, Douglas Ginsburg, A. Raymond Randolph, and
Stephen Williams. ``The privilege is said to be necessary because,
without it, the President will distance himself from Secret Service
agents charged with the duty of protecting him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The harm asserted is future harm, depending on a prediction
about what the President will do in the absence of the privilege.
This court has ruled that the privilege does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If harm of the sort the Department envisions is now occurring,
it therefore must be because the President does not believe the
Supreme Court will sustain the privilege,'' the order said.
``Neither a stay nor an order under the All Writs Act can alter or
prevent that alleged harm. Testimony today by Secret Service agents
regarding past events cannot change our ruling. And such testimony
cannot affect how the Supreme Court will rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's assertion of a special privilege for the
agents has been rejected by every judge who has considered it. Even
several of the president's advisers predicted that in light of
Thursday's decisions, it would be unlikely that Rehnquist would
issue a stay. The Supreme Court does not begin hearing cases until
it returns in October.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   White House officials, who have said that Clinton has not been
involved in the Secret Service appeal, declined to comment on
Thursday's ruling. But they took issue with a concurring opinion to
the full court's ruling rejecting the administration's request for
review.
</P>
<P>
   In the concurring opinion, Judge Laurence Silberman wrote that
the attorney general was ``acting as the President's counsel under
the false guise of representing the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mindful of the terrible political pressures and strains
of conscience that bear upon senior political appointees of the
Justice Department when an Independent Counsel (or special
prosecutor) is investigating the President of the United States,''
Silberman wrote. ``Those strains are surely exacerbated when the
President's agents literally and figuratively `declare war' on the
Independent Counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge's comments were disputed by Charles Ruff, the counsel
to the President.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have stated before, the attorney general and the
secretary of the Treasury have made their decisions on how to
proceed in this matter with complete independence, guided by the
advice of career law enforcement professionals,'' Ruff said. ``They
have had only one interest _ to ensure that the Secret Service is
able to perform its vitally important duties. Any suggestion to the
contrary is without foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Secret Service officials received a reprieve from
having to appear the grand jury, the jurors continued their work on
Thursday by hearing from Linda Tripp for the sixth time. It was
Mrs. Tripp who began the Lewinsky inquiry when she called the
independent counsel's office last January and said she had secretly
recorded conversations with, Ms. Lewinsky, her former Pentagon
colleague, that suggested an unlawful coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp is scheduled to return to the grand jury when it
resumes its deliberations next Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
