</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRAND WIN FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's no sense wondering why they can't do it every
night, but the Red Sox went on an offensive rampage Thursday night
_ and they did it against a Cleveland team that is destined for the
American League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Only one night after scratching out a 1-0 victory, the Red Sox
exploded for 17 hits in a 15-5 rout of the Indians at Fenway Park
that gave them a two-game series sweep and restored their
credibility that vanished following the All-Star break. Troy
O'Leary and Nomar Garciaparra each drove in five runs to lead the
way. O'Leary hit a grand slam in the fourth to wipe out a 4-1
deficit. Garciaparra hit a three-run dinger in the fifth to make it
an 8-4 game.
</P>
<P>
   And just to add salt to the wound, the Sox scored seven more
runs in the eighth when they sent 12 men to the plate. This might
happen more often if the Red Sox could stay close to home. Alas,
the next six games are on the road, three each in Detroit and
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six home games, the Red Sox scored 15 runs in four
of them. The question remains, which Red Sox team will show up
Friday night in the Motor City?
</P>
<P>
   ``O'Leary's grand slam put us back in there,'' said manager Jimy
Williams. ``Then came Nomar's home run. It's not just at home. I
think we play pretty good everywhere. That's the nature of the
game. Good pitching shuts down good hitting. Sometimes it's the
other way and hitting gets contagious. It just happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting was contagious Thursday night, and it wasn't just the
Red Sox. Home runs accounted for four of the five Cleveland runs,
all off winner Tim Wakefield who went 7 1/3 innings to pick up his
11th victory. Travis Fryman and David Bell homered in the second
inning to wipe out a 1-0 Boston lead. Dave Justice hit a solo shot
off Wakefield in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But after blowing a 1-0 lead, the Red Sox went to work for their
knuckleball specialist who has a reputation for keeping games
close. By the time Wakefield left, Boston was ahead, 8-5. Relievers
Ron Mahay and Derek Lowe mopped up. Good pitching also appears to
be contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It begins with your starters,'' said Williams. ``I talk about
Wakefield giving quality innings. He does. But just innings don't
mean a thing to me. But to pitch 200 inning, you have to pitch good
innings. You feel like you've got a chance to win a game everytime
Wake's out there. He kept us in that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians starter Dwight Gooden was coasting along in the fifth
when the Red Sox brought out the heavy artillery. Darren Bragg led
off with a double to left. Garciaparra and Vaughn walked, loading
the bases. O'Leary, not known as a home-run hitter, just wanted to
get the ball in the air and bring home a run. He got the ball into
the air and into the left-field screen for a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been awhile since I hit a home run,'' said O'Leary. ``I'm
not a home-run hitter. I didn't want to hit into a double play. I
got the ball in the air and it went out. I'm not surprised that
this team battled back. We have a lot of guys with a lot of heart
on this team. All these guys can hit, too. Hopefully, with things
going the way they are going right now, we will be able to maintain
it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary has come a long way, added Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does a lot of things to help our ball club,'' said the
manager. ``He's improved immensely defensively. Now he hits well
and drives in runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Gooden was replaced by Chad Ogea. With one out,
the one-time starter gave up a single to Darren Lewis and a walk to
Bragg. Garciaparra then hit a shot 422 feet into the bleachers. The
rest of the night was a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basicially, we've played good baseball,'' said Lewis. ``We
lost four one-run games on the road but we've been in every game.
When you go down, you have to turn the page as quick as possible.
We did it last night and we were able to come back tonight and do
the same thing. It was nice for us to be home and in comfortable
surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his start, Wakefield was comfortable, too. He has
pitched at least six innings in 17 of 20 starts. He has won five of
the last six and despite a 4.31 earned run average remains among
the league's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see we scored some runs tonight,'' said Wakefield,
eager to share the credit for his fine start. ``I think it will
open the door for guys' confidence to keep going. We played some
tight ballgames with Baltimore and Tampa Bay. We've been in every
ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers aren't important until the year is over with. I
couldn't tell you my numbers. Only thing I can look at is innings
pitched and I see I'm there 6-7 innings most starts. I take a lot
of pride in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
