<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON HURLS ONE-HITTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He mumbles to himself perhaps more now than ever
before. But what Randy Johnson is saying remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever occupies his mind, however, Johnson is throwing with a
renewed sense of purpose. He is throwing as hard as he ever has.
And Thursday night, he flirted with his second career no-hitter
during the Mariners' 3-0 victory over the Minnesota Twins at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has been virtually lost in a season of discontent,
is back.
</P>
<P>
   The big left-hander punished an opponent from the mound for the
second time in as many starts. Last Saturday, he pitched a five-hit
shutout against Anaheim, striking out 15. This time, he held
together a no-hitter for 71/3 innings and finished with a
one-hitter, 11 strikeouts and his second consecutive shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of our guys got rung up? Boom! Boom! Boom!,''
Minnesota manager Tom Kelly said. ``Randy pitched great. He had
no-hit stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy's on top of his game right now,'' concurred Mariners
manager Lou Piniella. ``His fastball really had some hop on it. He
located it well. There wasn't anything that wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had that no-hitter in the seventh, I thought he would
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had one out in eighth when former Mariner Brent Gates,
hitting from the No. 8 spot in the order, lined a base hit over the
second base bag. Gates hit an outside fastball off the end of his
bat and just over Johnson's outstretched glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to break it up,'' said Gates. ``He's the best
pitcher in the American League. He's very intimidating, very
dominant. I got to see a lot of that last year and it was a lot of
fun to watch. But it was not as much fun being on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting ahead of a lot of the hitters, throwing a good
slider. And he always has that dominating fastball. When he's
getting ahead and throwing a lot of strikes, he's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins' lone hit came after Johnson struck out 10, walked
three and committed a balk. Johnson, though, recorded his 94th
career game with 10 or more strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   It was his third career one-hitter. Johnson (9-8) also watched
his sixth no-hit bid falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw (the hit) I thought he was going to catch it. But I
think Randy thought it was hit harder than it was. I was bummed out
more than he was,'' said John Marzano, who has become Johnson's
regular batterymate.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Johnson did not seem tormented about not securing
the no-hitter. He did not speak to the media, and hasn't for the
past 1{ months. Johnson, in many ways, has become a loner in the
Mariner clubhouse because he wants to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson _ rattled earlier this season by his situation
_ is apparently focused. He took care of the Twins mostly on his
own _ striking out six straight hitters during one stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He ended the fourth with two strikeouts. Then, Johnson mowed
down three batters in the fifth and the first Twins batter he faced
in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's been pitching lately is unbelievable,'' Marzano
said. ``I think he can finish with 20 wins. . . . When he pitches
good, our team gets on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are now 10 games behind Anaheim in their quest to
crawl into the American League West race and are 6-2 since the
All-Star break. They've benefited from solid pitching and improved
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. supplied the only stirring catch Johnson needed
to preserve his no-hit bid in the early innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Minnesota's Ron Coomer launched a Johnson
fastball deep into centerfield. Griffey gave chase to the ball,
which tailed away, going to his right.
</P>
<P>
   When Griffey caught up to the ball, he ran with his back to home
plate, his head skyward and glove extended for the catch. It was
the second time this week Griffey's made the Willie Mays-like play.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Griffey robbed Texas' Will Clark with an identical
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pumped his fist after Griffey's catch. He shook his head
and then waved to Griffey in an act of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite boring for me,'' Griffey joked before adding:
``When he's on you just try to do the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took a 2-0 lead in the fourth inning after Shane
Monahan's clutch hit. The M's young left fielder laid his bat on a
low fastball, and lined a triple into the right centerfield gap.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui and Edgar Martinez scored after earlier hitting
back-to-back singles. The two-out at-bat produced Monahan's ninth
hit and fourth RBI since he entered the lineup nearly a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan accounted for all of the Mariners runs. His two-out
single to center drove in David Segui in the sixth, which ended
with the Mariners ahead for a 3-0 Mariner advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the only two mistakes Minnesota loser Brad Radke
(9-8) made all night. His just happened to pitch on the same night
as Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what he can do,'' Radke said of Johnson. ``He'll shut
you out in a heartbeat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
