u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-17 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BRITISH LINKS, WOODS REALIZES PATIENCE A VIRTUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Even English to English, some things don't
translate.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tiger Woods explaining how Thursday's conditions at Royal
Birkdale Golf Club reminded him of West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until the locals figure out that West Texas is hell's
exhaust pipe. British-American relations will be set back a hundred
years.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, the kid might not have been far off. Almost
incomprehensibly, Britain's western shoreline turned up hard and
dry, with a breeze but not a hurricane. No sagebrush was visible,
but the crunching brown underfoot of pennywort, creeping willow and
gorse made it feel like August in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the matter of the American idiom. Woods was
trying to explain to his international journalistic inquisitors how
he managed to tear asunder the British Open with his opening-round
65.
</P>
<P>
   Although he spent little time in the rough, he said it was so
gnarly that extricating the ball robbed it of the spin needed to
control the shot. The knuckleball was to be avoided at all costs on
these slick fairways and greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niekro would be proud of some of the shots you can hit to get
out of this rough,'' he said. Of course, no one but the smattering
of Yank scribes understood the reference to Phil and Joe, the
Niekro brothers of knuckleball pitching fame. Unfortunately, the
oblivious included the British transcriber, who produced the first
word in the transcripts as ``Negro.''
</P>
<P>
   Notified of the ironic gaffe, the horrified Royal &AMP; Ancient
staff, guardians of tournament propriety and protocol, snarfed up
as many errant copies as they could and quickly punched out a
corrected version.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to mind. It was a sports event hard to disturb. Be
it Niekro and Negro, Yank or Brit, all gloried in a day with which
Woods nearly ran away.
</P>
<P>
   Trailed by an unwieldy knot of cameramen and reporters, watched
by hordes clambering and stumbling over the grass-covered dunes,
Woods was the tournament's calm heart. Using his driver on just
four holes and often out-distanced by playing partners Nick Price
and Per-Ulrik Johansson, the American wunderkind exchanged his
standard heavy artillery for a craftier, almost flawless short
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it looked like he throttled back a little bit today,
which is good to see,'' said Price, who was a stroke back at 66.
``He went hard at one shot, which was a 2-iron into 15. That's the
only one I saw him go hard at. A year ago, he used to do that a
little more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He managed his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods acknowledged that the fireworks that usually accompany his
game have been occasionally counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just learning how to play golf,'' he said. ``I think it's
an evolutionary process every player goes through. If you ask any
player back in his early 20s and teens, they hit the ball pretty
hard. As they get older they learn to control their game. I'm no
exception to that _ still learning to flight the ball, learning a
lot of different shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I'm very pleased with my progress.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Woods hasn't already impressed an Open gallery. He
shot a 64 at last year's event at Troon. But it went with
lackluster rounds of 72, 74 and 74 that made for a 24th-place
finish at 284.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the tournament, the suspicion was that Woods was still
some years away from the patience and cunning required to master
the vagaries of British links courses. But he up and slapped
Birkdale so hard Thursday that his history might have telescoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things where I think I learned to play
smart golf, and understand that some of the lies you get here can
go a lot farther than they look,'' he said. ``I can hit an 8-iron
close to 190 in the air just because of some of the lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year (overclubbing the ball) happened to me because I
didn't really understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods came across the pond a week early with neighbor and fellow
Masters winner Mark O'Meara to fish and play golf in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed it because you get acclimatized to this
weather,'' he said. ``Unfortunately the golf got in the way of
fishing. That was the mindset we had last week _ stay relaxed,
prepare and understand you don't want to peak last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' 10 a.m. tee time, and his quick posting of red numbers on
the scoreboard, sent younger golf fans among the 37,000 in
attendance skittering across the dunes all afternoon to join the
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, the support was great,'' he said. ``You feel pretty good
about making birdie, but they kind of give you an extra little
boost. When you hit a good shot, some of the kids are screaming and
yelling. It was pretty neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ovation I got at 18, I haven't had that one in a long time
and it felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods can relate better than almost all of his contemporaries to
the youthful fury. The last time the Open was held here, Woods was
a 15-year-old high school kid.
</P>
<P>
   Probably trading Niekro baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
