<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BILLBOARD-INFLUENC     07-17 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BILLBOARD-INFLUENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLBOARD FIRM ALLEGEDLY PAID FOR STATE OFFICIAL'S VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A real estate firm owned by the president of a
Massachusetts billboard company picked up the tab for two luxury
suites at Disney World in 1995 for the chairman of the state agency
that regulates the billboard industry and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Genaitis, president of Rite Media Enterprises, said
Thursday the $6,410 hotel bill for Barton K. Hyte, chairman of the
Massachusetts Outdoor Advertising Board, and Hyte's family was paid
in February 1995 by the real estate firm affiliated with Rite
Media.
</P>
<P>
   Genaitis said his chief financial officer surreptitiously paid
the bill, and insisted he had not approved the arrangement. He also
said Hyte was unaware that the company, DORI Realty Trust, had paid
his bill.
</P>
<P>
   But a top-level former employee of Rite Media, however, told The
Globe that Hyte and Genaitis approved the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Hyte, who was reappointed last July by then-Governor William F.
Weld for a third three-year term, did not return phone calls or
respond to letters delivered to his Salem office and his home in
Marblehead.
</P>
<P>
   The payment of Hyte's vacation hotel bill is among several
allegations made by former Rite Media employees in recent months
concerning influence-peddling and fraud by Genaitis while the
company was in bankruptcy between 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The allegations are being investigated by the US attorney's
office in Boston and a federal grand jury has issued subpoenas in
the case, according to documents.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Hyte spent about a week at Walt Disney
World with his wife, their children, and a nanny, occupying two
penthouse suites at the Hilton Hotel in Lake Buena Vista, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Genaitis said that Hyte, upon checking out of his suites, was
told the bill was being paid for by the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   However, Genaitis said Richard Walker, Rite Media's chief
financial officer at the time, had paid the bill with a check drawn
on the bank account for DORI Realty _ a trust Genaitis owned. DORI
Realty owned the Revere building, Rite Media's corporate home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he (Hyte) appreciated having his bill paid, but I'm
also sure if he'd known if we were paying it he'd have said, `No
way,''' said Genaitis.
</P>
<P>
   But an ex-employee of Rite Media, who asked not to be
identified, disputed Genaitis's account. The former employee said
Genaitis had approved paying for Hyte's family vacation lodging
beforehand _ and that Hyte knew of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The former employee said Genaitis picked up Hyte's tab in hopes
of gaining favorable rulings on pending applications for new
billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Genaitis said Wednesday that the Outdoor Advertising Board
turned down most of Rite Media's applications, but the agency in
1994 had approved a request to modernize a billboard in New Bedford
that likely generated more revenue for the company.
</P>
<P>
   In several telephone interviews this week, Genaitis said that in
May Rite Media was ordered to deliver its financial records to the
federal grand jury in Boston. He said he was cooperating with the
investigation and denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The DORI check which allegedly paid for Hyte's family vacation
was one of the documents turned over, Genaitis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just some garbage being spread by a couple of
ex-employees who didn't like that I had fired them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a document filed by lawyers representing Chase Manhattan
Bank in Rite Media's bankruptcy case in April 1997 accused Genaitis
of transferring at least $382,124 by ``fraud, conversion, and
self-dealing'' from company accounts for his own benefit or the
benefit of other companies he controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan was Rite Media's chief debtor, having loaned the
firm $4.5 million during the early 1990s. According to the legal
summary filed with the bankruptcy court, the bank's investigation,
which was conducted by lawyers from the Boston law firm of Hale and
Dorr, as well as independent auditors, revealed that Genaitis
allegedly had:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Funneled $41,400 to two Rite Media subsidiaries to pay for
personal expenses;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Directed Rite Media to pay $51,000 to purchase Central
Outdoor Co., a billboard firm, and $27,366 to pay for taxes owed by
Central Outdoor;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Violated a court order and caused $47,250 to be paid to
himself as unauthorized salary;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)And directed Rite Media to buy tickets for sports events
at the FleetCenter which were ``primarily'' used by Genaitis and
his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   While the legal brief prepared by the Hale and Dorr lawyers
stated that these findings were supported by company records and
financial statements, it also noted that investigators had heard
additional allegations about Genaitis and Rite Media from Walker,
the billboard company's former chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the lawyers wrote, Walker had told them that
Genaitis had used ``roughly'' $19,000 of company money to ``make
contributions to local politicians with connections to the outdoor
advertising industry, so as to obtain political favors from such
politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank's lawyers did not specify which politicians had
received contributions and acknowledged they did not have
``indisputable'' proof to corroborate Walker's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Genaitis disputed the allegations contained in the Chase
Manhattan report. He said the bank wanted to control all aspects of
Rite Media's operation while it was in bankruptcy and that he had
no obligation to clear every expense with them.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Media's bankruptcy case ended last year _ and its debt to
Chase Manhattan was repaid _ after the company sold its assets,
about 100 signs in Massachusetts for $13 million to Acklerley
Communications, the largest billboard company in the state.
Genaitis has relocated his business to Florida and owns billboards
there and in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Genaitis acknowledged that he has appeared at fund-raisers for
various Massachusetts politicians, but denied making contributions
in hopes of influencing state billboard practices. Genaitis added
that Walker, whom he has accused of embezzling hundreds of
thousands of dollars from the company, was responsible for any
financial impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who pleaded guilty in November 1996 to one count of
filing a false tax return, declined to answer questions about his
work with the company. In a telephone interview Wednesday, he
denied embezzling any money from Rite Media.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Any action I took, any money I received from the company, I
did so with the approval of Mr. Genaitis,'' Walker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
