<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE CALLS MACH3 A BESTSELLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gillette Co. released second-quarter earnings Thursday
that were in line with Wall Street's expectations but noted that in
only its second week on the market, its new Mach3 was the
best-selling razor in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Citing figures from A.C. Nielsen Corp., Gillette claimed Mach3
accounted for 35 cents &UR;  &LR;  of every dollar that Americans spent on
men's blades and razors for the week ending July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the triple-blade razor was available in only about
60 percent of the country that week, it was still the nation's
best-selling razor, selling at twice the rate of other shaving
systems, according to Boston-based Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   And that was without Gillette spending ``a penny of
advertising,'' said Alfred M. Zeien, Gillette's chairman and chief
executive, who credited the media hype surrounding Mach3 as a
reason why ``people have been flocking into stores.''
</P>
<P>
   A yearlong $300 million media blitz for the Mach3 is set to
begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette began shipping Mach3 in the last week of June so Mach3
sales had little impact on the quarter that ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   For its second quarter, Gillette said sales for all its products
dropped 2 percent to $2.33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A strong dollar, which hurt Gillette's exports, and the
divestiture of its Jafra cosmetics unit partly accounted for the
dip. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Net income increased 11 percent to $372 million, and diluted net
income per common share was 33 cents, up 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That was in line with the estimates of analysts surveyed by
First Call Corp., a financial data company.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the 32nd consecutive quarter, our earnings per share
increased at a double-digit rate despite the continuing negative
effect of a strong dollar, softness in several key markets
including Asia'' and despite retailers' reducing their orders of
older razor lines to make room for the Mach3, Zeien said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said sales of its Braun electric shavers were off in
Japan and that sales for its toiletry lines, particularly its White
Rain brand, were ``down sharply.'' Sales for Sensor razors were
also lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their results were impacted by weakness in Asia, Brazil, and
Mexico, the strong dollar, and retailers cutting back on Sensor
orders,'' Prudential Securities analyst Carol Warner told Bloomberg
News.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics contend that Gillette has grown so big and
diversified that the company won't get the same boost from Mach3
that it got from Sensor, the shaving system it launched in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette released earnings after the stock market closed. On the
New York Stock Exchange, shares rose 9/16 to close at 60 3/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
