<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-SPECIAL-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to a
three-part series moving this weekend on the new identity being
forged by America's immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike immigrants of the past, many of today's new Americans are
choosing to straddle two worlds. They may live in the United
States, but with cut-rate phone cards and frequent-flier miles,
with modems, fax machines and video cameras, they can participate
in life back home with an immediacy unimagined by any previous
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The three articles will move in two forms: full length as
published in The New York Times and in abbreviated versions of
perhaps half or less of the full length. They will move on
Saturday, Sunday and Monday in the ``a'' news file and are for
publication beginning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the series follows:
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-IDENTITY (Undated) _ For a New York couple, many a day can
start in blaring traffic on the Grand Central Parkway Queens and
end on horseback in the verdant countryside of their native
Dominican Republic, cantering down to a river to feast on rum and
goat. They, like many modern immigrants, no longer consign their
homeland to the mist of memory or nostalgia. As the world has grown
smaller, the immigrant experience has become one of remaining
connected, economically, culturally, politically. Such a fluid
exchange between the homeland and the new land, which inevitably
alters both places, has unsettled many Americans, and this unease
underlies the current debates about immigration, multiculturalism
and bilingualism. By Deborah Sontag and Celia W. Dugger. (7,000
words.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use Sunday, July 19, and thereafter.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-TRADITION (Jaipur, India) _ In modern immigrant families,
where the bindings between here and there are stronger than ever
before, children almost inevitably find themselves pushed and
pulled between the culture and values of their parents and those of
the larger American society. Such ambiguities are perhaps never
more acute than when a decision about marriage is at hand. But what
emerges at defining moments like Vinit Sethi's traditional Indian
wedding, arranged by his parents, is the way many of these children
search for and find solace and grounding in their connections to
the world back home. By Celia W. Dugger. (5,500 words.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use Monday, July 20, and thereafter.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-GLOBALVILLAGE (Chinantla, Mexico) _ Almost every migration
story is the psychodrama of a family, its aspirations and
frustrations, its separations and reunions, its traditions and
compromises. For some Latin American and Caribbean immigrants, as
for the Cruz family of Chinantla, Mexico, it is also the story of a
town, a global village in the most literal sense. By Deborah
Sontag. (6,200 words.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use Tuesday, July 21, and thereafter.) &LR;
</P>
