<P>
   &UR; RESEARCHING YOUR FAMILY HISTORY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ABBY TANNENBAUM &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Diversion magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions often spark curiosity about one's ancestors.
With a bit of detective work, using oral interviews, government
records, genealogical associations, libraries and the Internet, the
family tree can be pieced together. Tannenbaum provides an
easy-to-follow guide for the novice researcher. (slugged:
BC-TRACING-YOUR-ROOTS-(SUMMER)-NYTSF, priority code r, category
code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SERIOUS TAN IS BEYOND THE PALE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (750 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By PAULA GANZI LICATA &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In her youth, Licata would join the legions on the beach seeking
the ultimate bronzed look. Many sunburns later, she resigned
herself to being unfashionably pale _ or, as her mother put it, the
``before'' picture in a Coppertone advertisement. Now, however, to
Licata's delight, pale is in vogue. (slugged:
BC-FASHIONABLY-PALE-(SUMMER)-NYTSF, priority code r, category code
l) &QL;
</P>
