<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-CAROLYN18-COX     07-17 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-CAROLYN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flying in the face of adversity
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Carolyn Loudenslager, president of the Bud Light
Air Force, has not lived a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   If she ever expected to, she should have known better.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Leo, was an aviation legend: seven-time U.S.
aerobatic champion, airplane designer, airline pilot and founder of
the Bud Light team _ the team that will fly the Bud Light Micro Jet
at this weekend's United States Air and Trade Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember my first airplane flight. I was probably 2
months old,'' Carolyn Loudenslager said Thursday. ``I remember my
first flight with my dad. I rode on his lap'' in his single-seat
Bud Light 200, a propeller-powered show plane her father had built
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Loudenslager's crowd-thrilling air show flights did not
thrill her, and she did not share his passion for airplanes or
flight. She studied political science in college and had no plans
to join her father's air show business.
</P>
<P>
   That changed abruptly in June 1997, when Leo was fatally injured
in an accident _ not in an airplane, but on his motorcycle near his
home near Memphis, Tenn., when a car swerved into his lane and hit
him head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Between his air show travels and his airline flying, Carolyn had
never seen much of of her father, even less after her parents
divorced when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he was gone. All that remained was the Bud Light team,
and its future was in question.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Loudenslager said the team's members _ pilots Bill
``Burner'' Beardsley and Jack ``Elk'' Ekl, and crew chief Bill
``Big B'' Beardsley, Burner's father _ did not know what their
sponsor, St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch Co., would want to do with
the team. They started negotiations that would run through the rest
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team needed someone to call president. Carolyn
took the title. ``But I really was a glorified secretary,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she calculated what it would cost to keep the team
together. It was much more than Anheuser-Busch had offered, but
Loudenslager went to face the big beer company herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured there was no way they were going to pay us what we
needed,'' she said. ``I figured I was signing off... I was sort of
brazen about it. But they essentially gave us what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 22, Carolyn manages one of the air show circuit's
highest-profile acts, helping a close-knit team stay together while
trying to come to terms with her own loss and trying to figure out
where her own life is going.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot fill her father's shoes. She is not a pilot, although
she has begun taking flying lessons. But she said she manages the
business side of the team more closely than her father ever did
while he juggled air show and airline flying with designing a new
show plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our schedule this year is the best we've had in 10 years,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But her pride is tempered by thoughts of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I get into this, the more I think, Gosh, I wish Dad
could have been here because we would have made the perfect team,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she admits she has not found the spark that fired her
father's aviation passion.
</P>
<P>
   While airplanes interest her, she said, ``I'll never be an
aviation enthusiast.... I don't know how long I'll be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, she is waiting until next week to learn whether
Anheuser-Busch will sponsor the team next year. Every year, the Bud
Light Air Force must compete for its share of the company's
advertising budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see my future past next year,'' she said.
``Whatever I find out next week is the fate that's meant to be.
I've come to peace with it.'' CONTACT Timothy R. Gaffney by e-mail
at Timothy_Gaffneycoxohio.com, or by phone at (937) 225-2390
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
