<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artists find creative outlet fashioning color, texture in their
pieces
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of us think art is something you hang on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Not Sister Mary Kay Finneran. For morning prayers, the nun wraps
her shoulders in an earth-toned wool shawl hand-woven by Atlanta
area artist Judith Krone. ``I don't make fashion statements,'' says
Sister Mary Kay. ``When I wear Judith's shawl, it's like being
wrapped in love. People will come up to me and touch it. They want
to feel its texture, which is what a piece of woven art is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Community volunteer Lucy Hutchinson gets the same reaction when
she wears her cotton fly-fishing vest hand-woven and custom-dyed by
Atlanta weaver Lynn Nickerson. ``Everyone's intrigued by the bright
colors,'' she says. ``I love to wear it with jeans and a
turtleneck. It's a timeless piece that I will keep forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone and Nickerson are two of seven Georgia weavers whose
wearable art will be showcased at fashion shows Friday night during
Convergence '98: Rhythms &AMP; Hues, the international weavers'
conference at the Westin Peachtree Plaza Hotel and Atlanta Market
Center. Juried by Holly Brubach, style editor of The New York Times
Magazine, the show features one-of-a-kind jackets, dresses, coats
and accessories. The weavers hail from 25 states and six countries.
</P>
<P>
   Brubach evaluated 187 photo entries before paring it down to 92.
Her judging criteria? ``Cut, in terms of how the outfit falls on
the body, color, details and innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the outfits can be worn, some run the risk of wearing
you,'' Brubach says.
</P>
<P>
   One that falls into the latter category is the 20-pound
``Penny'' dress, a long black strapless gown covered with
double-weave pockets. Pennies were tucked into the pockets by
student weaver Shannon Hamblett of the Kansas City Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Wearable pieces from Georgians include: Linda Jarrett's colorful
cropped suede-and-cotton jacket; Christine Stanton's cranberry wool
tent coat; and Roxanne Brown's green-gold-rust chenille jacket and
scarf.
</P>
<P>
   Judging the weavers' work, Brubach says, was educational. ``I
don't know that much about weaving,'' she admits. ``But I sensed
that the weavers were aiming for fashionable garments, not just
pieces of beautiful woven fabric.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, for me, took the clothes to the next level of
sophistication.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the weavers sell their creations through referrals or
through small boutiques. Others sell at festivals and art shows.
Individual pieces take two weeks to two months to weave. Prices
range from $200 for a shawl to more than $3,000 for a
special-occasion dress.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Janet Bealer, who's woven for 25 years, compares the
craft to dance. ``Once you start, there's a rhythm,'' she says.
``And it's meditative.''
</P>
<P>
   ART SHOW in Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Runway fashion shows of wearable art, 6:30 and 9 p.m. Friday,
$45, Peachtree Plaza Ballroom; display of wearable art show
clothing, 9 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturday and 9 a.m.-5 p.m. July 26, $10,
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags Room. Westin
</P>
<P>
   Peachtree Plaza Hotel, 210 Peachtree St. N.W. Information:
770-351-0233.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-15-98 1757E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
