A9910 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTER-REBUKED18-COX     07-17 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTER-REBUKED18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Living facility rebuked by state
 &HT;    By Kevin Wishard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Texas Department of Human Services officials
have reprimanded a Georgetown assisted-living center for negligence
after an 83-year-old resident who fell asleep during a sightseeing
outing was left in a parked bus for five hours as the temperature
reached 97 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was unconscious and suffering from heat exhaustion and
hyperthermia when discovered by center staff members, who failed to
search for her despite repeatedly recognizing her absence, state
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County District Attorney Ken Anderson said that
Georgetown police are investigating the incident, which happened
July 8 at Park Place Assisted Living.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred during a stretch when temperatures climbed into the
high 90s and low 100s. The excessive heat has claimed the lives of
27 people across Texas so far this summer, and many victims have
been older people whose health problems were exacerbated by the
heat. Officials in Dallas County, where 18 heat-related deaths have
been reported, declared a state of emergency on July 14.
</P>
<P>
   July 16 was the 24th day this year that Dallas hit temperatures
of 100 degrees or more. It was the 14th day for Austin, according
to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Austin area has seen one heat-related death _ a
56-year-old woman whose body was found May 28 on the railroad track
along North MoPac Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators said the temperature in the Austin area was
87.8 degrees when Park Place staff members found the resident lying
on the back seat of the bus at 10 p.m. At 4 p.m., when staffers
first noticed she was missing, the temperature was 97 degrees. The
report states the woman was unresponsive and had a temperature of
106.8 degrees when she arrived at Georgetown Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose name and condition were unavailable, remains
hospitalized. A report by state investigators said that had
suffered kidney failure, and her attending physician told
investigators last week her prognosis was poor.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators cited several problems at Park Place,
including failure to keep track of the number of passengers on the
bus, a breakdown in communications between staff members at shift
changes, a lack of training and policy directing staff members what
to do when a resident is missing, and failure to have sufficient
staff on duty to ensure appropriate resident care.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators reprimanded the center for negligence and failure
to protect the health and safety of residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most severe action we could take short of closing the
facility,'' said Rosemary Patterson, a Department of Human Services
spokeswoman. ``This was a systems breakdown. ... We're very
concerned that something like this could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   State investigators have recommended the agency's legal
department ask the attorney general's office to pursue penalties
against the center. The maximum penalty that could assessed against
an assisted-living center is $10,000 per day in fines, said Ward
Tisdale, a spokesman for the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the center, which is home to 29 residents, said
that policies have been implemented to correct all the deficiencies
turned up by state investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The state's report shows Park Place staff members realized the
resident was absent first at 4 p.m., again at 5 p.m., and again at
7:45 p.m. However, they did not begin searching for her until 9:45,
when administrator Jean Cagle was told the woman was still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Park Place officials, in a news release issued Thursday, said
staff members were not alarmed at the woman's absence because
residents frequently leave the center with family members.
Officials also stated that state-required sign-out procedures were
in place but inconsistently applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our residents are active and independent. They come and go as
they please, and several residents even drive their own cars,''
Cagle said. ``This has been a terribly unfortunate incident, and we
are each personally affected and profoundly saddened.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the bus did not tell other staff members the names
of the eight residents who were on the outing, investigators
reported. Upon returning to the center around 4:15 p.m., the driver
did not notice that the woman did not get out of the van. She did
not see anyone on the bus, but did not check to see whether it was
empty before parking it in the center's back lot and locking the
doors, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Cagle and other residents told investigators that the woman had
a history of falling asleep in various places.
</P>
<P>
   State records show investigations of three other complaints
against Park Place since it opened in February 1997. Only one, in
which a former employee was accused of asking a resident to sign
over a check, was substantiated, and center officials turned the
matter over to Georgetown police, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said Human Services officials will make an unannounced
inspection to see whether the center has corrected its problems. If
deficiencies are found, further licensing action could be taken,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County chief medical examiner Robert Bayardo said Austin
resident Erma Graves, 56, was found dead May 28 in the 12700 block
of North MoPac Boulevard. The temperature that day was high, and
when an investigation revealed no other cause, the death was ruled
as heat-related, Bayardo said.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer Brad Prendergast contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
