<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-GAMES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (FOR SUNDAY RELEASE)
 &HT;    Goodwill Games running strong
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Goodwill Games were born in 1986, after
back-to-back Olympic boycotts, as Ted Turner's extravagant way of
getting the super powers back on the same playing field. But, since
the first games were held in Moscow, the Berlin Wall has fallen,
the Soviet Union has fractured and much of the old East- West
animosity has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games, however, have survived, or perhaps refused
to go away. Cynics might call them Turner's Folly because they lost
more than $100 million in their first three incarnations. Now, over
the next 15 days they will have wrestlers, triathletes,
synchronized swimmers and gymnasts competing for the attention of
subway sports fans whose idea of global competition is the Mets vs.
the Yankees or the Giants vs. the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   But these Goodwill Games, which will have 1,300 athletes from 60
countries competing for $5 million in prize money, will make their
mark, perhaps as early as today when U.S. sprint sensation Marion
Jones runs the 100 meters. The games have become an oasis for
athletes who once had to wander four years in a competitive desert
between Olympics, and they're becoming a real windfall for the best
performers as bonuses for world records will be as much as
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a more lucrative track meet on American
soil,'' said Dan Pfaff, an assistant track coach at the University
of Texas and a veteran of international competition. ``I guarantee
every American coach has pointed for this. The Africans are geeked
up because of the prize money. The distance runners could be
scorching. If they get some good weather there it could be better
than the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The swimming competition will feature Russian Alexander Popov, a
double gold medalist in the Atlanta Olympics, and an us. vs. them
format in which teams from the United States, Germany, Russia,
China and the World All-Stars will swim head-to-head in a
succession of dual meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something new to make it move viewer friendly. It's
almost like college dual meets,'' said Austin's Josh Davis, a
three-time gold medalist at the Atlanta Olympics who will be
swimming the 200-meter freestyle and 200 individual medley and on a
relay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college there's not a person sitting in the whole place
during the relays, and these should all come down to the last
relay. The teams are that close.''
</P>
<P>
   The diving competition could be the biggest yet for a UT recruit
touted as the next Greg Lougainis, Troy Dumais, and UT's Laura
Wilkinson will challenge on the women's side.
</P>
<P>
   Figure skating will have the elegance of Michelle Kwan, and
women's gymnastics will have a pair of 'Niques, Dominique Dawes and
Dominique Moceanu. The U.S. team that can actually play soccer, the
women, will be on hand with a team that includes Mia Hamm and
Michelle Akers.
</P>
<P>
   In Central Park, men's and women's two-person teams, including
legend Sinjin Smith and the team of Karch Kiraly and Adam Johnson,
will be kicking up the imported sand.
</P>
<P>
   In track, often the showcase event at Olympic-style
competitions, Michael Johnson was slated to be the star. But
Johnson, a record-setting double gold medalist in Atlanta, is
coming back from injuries and will not compete in the 200 meters,
only the 400 meters and the 1,600-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson not quite 100 percent, the sprint star of these
Games could very well turn out to be Jones. She certainly doesn't
lack for confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I train to be the best,'' Jones said recently. ``Second place
isn't good enough. If I'm at my best I can't be beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 22, was a high school phenom in California. She qualified
for the 1992 Olympic team as an alternate for the relays but
declined to compete. In college, her track career had to share time
with her basketball dreams. She was a guard on the North Carolina
team that won a national championship. In 1996, in what should have
been a showcase year, Jones sat out the Olympics because of a
broken foot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she's been making up for lost time. Jones recently
became the first U.S. woman in 50 years to capture three national
titles, winning the 100- and 200-meter races and the long jump. Her
100-meter race today figures to get the Goodwill Games off to a
fast start.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has run a time of 10.71 seconds for that distance, and
only Florence Griffith-Joyner's 10.49 in 1988 is faster.
Griffith-Joyner's record was once thought to be unbreakable, but
there's now talk that Jones might be able to do it. She has said
she's capable of getting all three world records and would like to
get five gold medals, including two in the relays, in Sydney in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   An even better bet to get a world record here, and a big bonus,
might be decathlete Dan O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be stoked,'' Pfaff said. ``For a decathlete there's
never been a chance to get this kind of prize money.''
</P>
<P>
   While heptathlete Jackie Joyner-Kersee is unlikely to set any
records, she figures to be in the spotlight in her last big
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaff, who used to coach Donovan Bailey, is also looking forward
to the 100 meters. ``There's been a lot of injuries and a lot of
woofing going on,'' he said. ``That's why I got out of it. But the
100 could be really exciting. So should the hurdles. The hurdlers
have been hot and they've been running in terrible European
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the competition, the Goodwill Games also will
offer the United States a chance to rebound from the Atlanta
Olympics which, in addition to a tragedy, were marred by cheesy
commercialism and Third Worldesque transportation problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of people from other countries who were
turned off when we demolished the track stadium right after the
Olympics. Everybody mentions it,'' Pfaff said. ``This is a chance
to redeem our image.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
