<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION18-COX     07-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Board proposes more money for scholarships
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Saying too many Texans are being priced out of college,
state higher education officials are asking lawmakers to boost
spending for scholarships more than threefold _ to nearly $500
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a real crisis of access by everyone _ not
just minorities, but the middle class,'' said Joe Krier of San
Antonio, a member of the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board.
``If they (lawmakers) don't address this in a big, big way . . . we
believe they'll be looking at a dramatically declining number of
people in public higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers said they have hopes of substantially expanding
scholarships, which the state has not generously financed in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the board voted 15-2 against Texas A&AMP;M University's
request for a law school. A&AMP;M planned to offer law degrees in
partnership with a private institution in Houston, South Texas
College of Law, but the board was not persuaded the affiliation was
needed and would be cost-free to the state.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen said the proposal was ``one of the most
misunderstood academic initiatives'' his school had ever undertaken
and that A&AMP;M would pitch it again in several months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas colleges are considered a bargain, combined
annual tuition and fees have risen dramatically in the past five
years. At the University of Texas, those costs are up 78 percent
and will average $3,004 for undergraduates in the coming school
year, according to UT data.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff, chairman of the powerful Finance
Committee, said there is a lot of interest in boosting aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not many places, I think, where our money would be
better spent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Various aid proposals in the range of $500 million are floating
around the Capitol, including the Coordinating Board's
recommendation, which directs scholarships to the neediest Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, a Republican from Mount Pleasant, said he would like
nothing more than to give all Texas students with a B average and a
family income below $100,000 a free ride to the college of their
choice, public or private. Georgia has something similar, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for the Legislature to cough up $500
million all at once, Ratliff said, but it's too early to say how
much might be available.
</P>
<P>
   The state expects to have a record $3.7 billion budget surplus
at the end of this biennium, and state Sen. Teel Bivins,
R-Amarillo, who heads the Education Committee, said all of state
government will be competing for the money. He favors the
Coordinating Board's focus on helping the neediest Texans first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a huge first step,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said the interim legislative committee on education and a
separate panel considering the effects of Hopwood, a federal court
ruling that led to a dismantling of affirmative action programs,
are discussing dramatically expanding scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard time and again the affirmative action that is
needed is an affirmative increase in scholarships,'' Bivins said.
``Obviously, it's race-neutral, but it would be a benefit to all
people, especially minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Data provided by the Coordinating Board show that 46 percent of
Texans live in households with annual income below $25,000. Of
black and Hispanic households, more than 62 percent fall below that
income.
</P>
<P>
   The Coordinating Board's proposal targets 267,354 of the
neediest students for scholarships that would be about $2,000 a
year for most students and less for others. The cost is estimated
at $498 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The board's latest figures show that 135,946 students get
state-financed scholarships at a cost of $137.3 million, and that
doesn't come close to meeting the need, said Sharon Cobb, assistant
commissioner for student services.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government provides the bulk of the total $2 billion
annually in financial aid for Texas college students, Cobb said.
Most of that aid, however, comes in the form of loans, which must
be paid back, not in scholarships, which are free.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-16-98 2229E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
