<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton a persecuted minority
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ While sitting in on a televised panel discussion
on race, a big ol' white boy from Arkansas startled viewers around
the country when he solemnly announced that he was a minority. He's
part Cherokee, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that moment, everyone in America thought this man was just
a big, ol' white boy from Arkansas who happened to be president of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's surprise announcement was designed to demonstrate
that he was sincere. He felt the pain of all minority Americans.
</P>
<P>
   You scoff. No, no, this time it was different. This time he
could really felt your pain because, by golly, this time he was
you.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not merely sensitive to the feelings of those around
him, this time he actually assimilated their identities. ``We are
Willie Borg. You will be assimilated. Resistance is futile.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton's statement that he is part American Indian is
true or not remains to be seen. But that's always the way it is
with Clinton. By now Las Vegas sports books must have several
betting lines posted on this subject. My guess is that the odds are
two-to-one that he made up his Indian heritage on the spot. After
all, this is a white man has a history of speaking with a forked
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably even money that Clinton will claim some new Native
American privilege when he is asked to produce proof that his
grandmother actually was a quarter Cherokee, as he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno will have to decide whether she will
call for the appointment of another special prosecutor or run
interference again for another one of Clinton's invented claims of
privilege. Since she already holds world records in both of these
categories, this should be another even-money bet.
</P>
<P>
   I'd put my money on Reno calling for another independent counsel
to investigate Clinton's lying and covering up about his Indian
heritage. Think about it. If you recall, Reno seeks independent
counsels for everything Clinton does unless it involves laundering
campaign finance money or payoffs to the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   Vegas odds that FBI Director Louis Freeh will urge Reno to
appoint an independent counsel to investigate Clinton's Indian
heritage claim would be something like eight-to-one against.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is Freeh's boss, just as Clinton is Reno's boss. Freeh has
angered Reno by telling her that she is violating the Independent
Counsel Act by refusing to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate a campaign finance scandal that leads straight into the
White House. Freeh won't cross Reno twice.
</P>
<P>
   So far, independent counsel Kenneth Starr has not tied American
Indians to the Whitewater-Filegate-Travelgate-Monica Lewinsky
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But to be fair to Starr, which is not a popular thing to do, the
man only learned that he was dealing with the nation's first
American Indian president last week. This news was just as big a
surprise to Starr as it was to American Indians and all Americans,
which includes Cherokees and presumably Clinton's own family.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, Reno did call for the appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate credible criminal charges in a
matter that involves American Indians and a possible link to
campaign donations. This investigation, however, targets Clinton's
Secretary of Interior Bruce Babbitt, one of several Clinton cabinet
officers under criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it shouldn't surprise anyone that Clinton would become
a persecuted minority right in the middle of a discussion of
persecuted minorities. Put Clinton next to Ellen DeGeneres and he
would announce that he is a lesbian trapped in a man's body.
Clinton is more than Borg, he's a shape-shifter.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
