<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, July 18,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The digital revolution runs at warp speed.
Consider that when Bill Clinton arrived in the White House, hardly
anyone had even heard of the Internet. By the time Clinton's moving
van drives off, presumably in January 2001, 60 per cent of U.S.
families are expected to be full netizens.
</P>
<P>
   But the real issue is what kind of access we'll have, and at
what cost. And on that score, the signs look promising. (Glass, Cox
News Service) MOVED 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Congressional Republicans who are worried their
lousy environmental voting records may hurt them at the polls have
created a fake environmental organization and have started giving
each other trophies that declare them environmental champions _
something to show the home folks. It is a scam of breathtaking
brazenness. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox Newspapers columnist Howard Kleinberg is
on vacation. His column will resume for Wednesday, July 29.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ My New York editor friend, Larry Ashmead,
clearly thinks I am a nut about picnics. And, of course, he is
right. I come from a long line of women, even old ladies in their
80s, who often said, ``Let's take dinner and go to the woods.'' Our
theory is that whatever you have to eat tastes better under the
open sky, and ants in the cake and sand in the salad never bothered
one of us a whit. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
7/16.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ Cox Newspapers columnist Joe Murray is traveling
and reporting in Europe. His column will resume the week of July 27
with reports from abroad. (Murray, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ While sitting in on a televised
panel discussion on race, a big ol' white boy from Arkansas
startled viewers around the country when he solemnly announced that
he was a minority. He's part Cherokee, he said. Until that moment,
everyone in America thought this man was just a big, ol' white boy
from Arkansas who happened to be president of the United States.
(Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
