<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURES-BJT18-COX     07-17 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
July 18, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-GIFTS _ The garden is bigger than ever and garden
accessories, everything from fountains to wind chimes to patio
furniture, are in demand. Here's a look at what's hot. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD ATLANTA _ Judging from my mail, there has been a
sharp upsurge in the number of homeless birds, giving rise to a new
humanitarian movement called Habitat for Avian-ity. We have bird
bungalows, bird Tudors, bird Cape Cods, bird ranch houses, bird
apartments -- anything that humans enjoy living in -- scaled down
and fitted with holes instead of doors. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER-REBUKED _ GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Texas Department of Human
Services officials have reprimanded a Georgetown assisted-living
center for negligence after an 83-year-old resident who fell asleep
during a sightseeing outing was left in a parked bus for five hours
as the temperature reached 97 degrees. (Wishard, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-CAROLYN _ Carolyn Loudenslager, at age 22, manages one of
the air show circuit's highest-profile acts, helping a close-knit
team stay together while trying to come to terms with the loss of
her father and trying to figure out where her own life is going.
(Gaffney, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GOODWILL-GAMES _ NEW YORK _ The Goodwill Games were born in
1986, after back-to-back Olympic boycotts, as Ted Turner's
extravagant way of getting the super powers back on the same
playing field. The Goodwill Games, however, have survived, or
perhaps refused to go away. Now, over the next 15 days they will
have wrestlers, triathletes, synchronized swimmers and gymnasts
competing for the attention of subway sports fans whose idea of
global competition is the Mets vs. the Yankees or the Giants vs.
the Jets. (Maher, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED. EMBARGOED UNTIL
SUNDAY 7/19.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EDUCATION _ AUSTIN _ Saying too many Texans are being
priced out of college, state higher education officials are asking
lawmakers to boost spending for scholarships more than threefold _
to nearly $500 million a year. ``We're looking at a real crisis of
access by everyone _ not just minorities, but the middle class,''
said Joe Krier of San Antonio, a member of the Texas Higher
Education Coordinating Board. ``If they (lawmakers) don't address
this in a big, big way . . . we believe they'll be looking at a
dramatically declining number of people in public higher
education.'' (Roser, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WOVEN-ART _ Most of us think art is something you hang on a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Not Sister Mary Kay Finneran. For morning prayers, the nun wraps
her shoulders in an earth-toned wool shawl hand-woven by Atlanta
area artist Judith Krone. ``I don't make fashion statements,'' says
Sister Mary Kay. ``When I wear Judith's shawl, it's like being
wrapped in love. People will come up to me and touch it. They want
to feel its texture, which is what a piece of woven art is all
about.'' (Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. EMBARGOED
UNTIL JULY 19.
</P>
<P>
   EARRING-STYLE _ Close inspection of the latest looks in earwear
proves that ``sharp'' doesn't apply at all. The more apt word to
describe the best earring styles out now is ``nice.'' (Walton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS _ AUSTIN _ Syphilis, the sexually transmitted disease
that has crippled and killed people worldwide for more than 500
years, soon could be headed for eradication, thanks to breakthrough
Texas research. For the first time, scientists at the University of
Texas Houston Health Science Center have mapped the complete gene
structure of the screw-shaped bacterium that causes syphilis,
opening the door to development within five years ofa vaccine to
prevent and possibly eradicate it. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-WEAVERS _ Photo package and short story on a liturgical
exhibit that opens next week, part of Convergence '98, the
international biennial conference of the Handweavers Guild of
America. We focus on a half-dozen stunning examples of artwork,
including the efforts of local weaver Ase Blake. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-NEWBOOKS _ We explore the latest trends in books coming
out of the annual meetings of the Christian Booksellers Assocation,
held this week in Dallas. (Perkes, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JESUSJUNK _ Industry insiders at the Christian
Booksellers Association call it ``holy hardware and Jesus junk.''
Call it what you want but everything from Jesus toenail clippers to
pencils, napkins and clothes makes for a billion-dollar industry.
(Perkes, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-AUTHOR _ He was a Catholic monk for twelve years but
lately he has become known as something else, an expert on the
soul. Thomas Moore, author of ``Care of the Soul,'' and ``Soul
Mates,'' is one of the most popular self-help authors in the world.
Next week (July 23), Moore will visit Atlanta for a book-signing.
His latest book continues with his ``soul'' theme, this time look
at ``The Soul of Sex.'' A chat with Moore about how a former
Catholic monk became a best-selling author and New Age guru.
(Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-SOULOFSEX _ Review of Moore's latest, ``The Soul of
Sex.'' (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
