<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS, WADSWORTH WATCH SIGNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Former Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning wants to
be the first NFL rookie to receive a $10 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Washington State quarterback Ryan Leaf, taken one spot behind
Manning in last April's draft, isn't as conservative. He reportedly
is asking for an $11 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials are watching both negotiations with great
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contracts are going to be big,'' said one NFL executive
who has a top-10 first-round pick. ``You have the egos of two
big-time agents who have big-time quarterbacks who are going to
start from the outset. The teams can't afford to have the players
(hold) out.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning and Leaf were the first two players selected, right
ahead of former Florida State defensive end Andre Wadsworth, taken
third by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL executive said Wadsworth will get a signing bonus of
about $8 million, which is nearly $2 million more than St. Louis
Rams offensive tackle Orlando Pace received as the first player
picked a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the quarterbacks get $10 (million), (Wadsworth) will get $8
(million),'' the NFL executive said, adding that Wadsworth's agent,
Eugene Parker, is going to ask for a deal that piggybacks the
quarterbacks' deals.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Eric Swann was paid the biggest signing bonus
in Cardinals history of $7.5 million when he re-signed last
February, a deal worth $25 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Vice President Bob Ferguson, who is handling Wadsworth
negotiations, refused to comment on the possible contract terms.
</P>
<P>
   A league source said that Wadsworth and Charles Woodson, the
Michigan cornerback taken fourth overall by Oakland, are waiting to
see what deals Manning and Leaf get before signing. The source said
Woodson's deal will have little impact on Wadsworth's contract
because Woodson likely will sign long after Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Poston, Woodson's agent, has a history of lengthy holdouts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Manning and Leaf are expected to get six-year deals,
lengthy contracts that are more salary-cap friendly because a
signing bonus is spread out over the duration of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year deals for each could be worth as much as $30
million. A year ago, cornerback Tom Knight, the Cardinals'
first-round pick, signed a five-year contract. Defensive end Simeon
Rice, also represented by Parker, signed a four-year deal as the
team's top choice in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's agent, Tom Condon, and Leaf's agent, Leigh Steinberg,
are expected to ask for deals that include voidable years. The
contracts would void after two to four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals never have signed a contract that had voidable
years and don't want to give Wadsworth that kind of deal.
</P>
<P>
   A way around it could be to sign him to contract that includes
``buy-back'' years or ``escalators,'' a way of paying a player for
certain achievements, all of which are added to salaries in future
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also have never signed any players to contracts
with ``buybacks'' or ``escalator'' clauses and prefer not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have voidable years, buy-backs or massive escalators to
reflect the uncertainties of where contracts go,'' one agent said.
``In this market place, a rookie contract has no chance to be fair
after three years. You get the highest possible signing bonus
because you don't care what the contracts are (worth) at the end of
the deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who don't have as much cash on hand as some
teams, often defer some of the signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   An agent said the team likely would want to pay (Wadsworth) in
three installments.
</P>
<P>
   Parker represents Wadsworth and the Cardinals' unsigned
second-round pick, defensive back Corey Chavous of Vanderbilt. It's
a tricky situation with the same agent representing both, getting
each contract under the remaining money available in the team's
$4.391 million rookie pool.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Parker said the agent expects Chavous to sign
next week before training camp opens. Only one player in the top
five of the second round has signed. Chavous was taken third in the
round, No. 33 overall. &QL; 
Note
</P>
<P>
   Veteran center Mike Devlin's father, John, a longtime assistant
college football coach, died Wednesday of a massive stroke in
Bloomsburg, Pa. Funeral services are tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
