<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-KLASSEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLASSEN LIVES HIS DREAM 
 ROOKIE GREW UP ON BALL FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Think about living in the best of all worlds and
chances are your thoughts will finish second to what Diamondbacks
rookie Danny Klassen has already experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen grew up in the adolescent equivalent of paradise and now
resides in Eden, which is his view of the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that the 22-year-old shortstop/second baseman
is there. His is a case of destiny . . . and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell he has had a real good upbringing,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He has his feet on the ground and
understands what is important and what is frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the meat and potatoes of this thing and has a
pretty good feeling for the core of what playing pro baseball is
all about. It's a tribute to his mom and dad and the environment he
has been raised in.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Leamington, Ontario, to a hockey-playing father
who was also a devout fan of the Detroit Tigers, who played just 45
minutes from the family's doorstep. Vic Klassen moved his family to
Stuart, Fla., when his son was 2, but he never lost his love of the
Tigers or for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   His son never had to crawl under fences or clear a vacant lot to
find a suitable field for a pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived on about 10 acres of land, so when I was 9 years old,
my dad built me a regulation-sized Little League field (complete
with outfield fence) in my back yard,'' Klassen recalled. ``He
coached me all the way through Little League, and our team
practiced on the field two or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had a pond back there, so all of us would go fishing
after practices. When I turned 13, my dad expanded the field into
major league dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Complete with pond, of course. Might say it was the forerunner
of Bank One Ballpark's pool.
</P>
<P>
   He attended John Carroll High School, which featured the best
baseball program in the area. He lettered all four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always done things geared toward baseball,'' said
Klassen, whose parents were on hand Wednesday to witness his
clutch, two-out, two-strike hit in the 11th inning to beat Houston.
``My parents have been great in preparing me not only for baseball,
but also for life and how to act properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have played basketball or football and
those things, but my dad kind of discouraged it because he didn't
want me to get hurt playing football. Obviously, my best chance was
in baseball, and he could see it at an early age, so it was a
decision we made.''
</P>
<P>
   And one that worked. He's hitting .310 with three homers and
five RBIs in the eight games he's played with the Diamondbacks. He
had 10 homers and 47 RBIs during an injury-slowed 71 games in
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   A high school All-American, Klassen signed with Florida State
but opted for the pro ranks and a healthy signing bonus when
Milwaukee drafted him in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in the lower minors, his batting average jumped
some 50 points to .331 under hitting coach John Pont last summer at
Double-A El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, his fielding percentage almost matched his batting
average. Klassen committed 50 errors at shortstop, his position of
choice until being switched at Tucson a month before being called
up.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee foolishly gambled that the high error count, coupled
with his absence from winter ball, would cause the two expansion
teams to overlook Klassen in November's draft. But after Showalter
made a personal inspection of the El Paso ballpark, he determined
the ``rock garden'' field produced many of the errors.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took Klassen in the second round of the draft, to the
chagrin of Brewers management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it was a bad field. I never have,'' Klassen said.
``Buck said he didn't think it was in the best shape, but it was a
nice place to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fielding really frustrated me. I've always thought of
myself as a good fielder. I was kind of in a mental funk. My goal
this spring was to restablish myself as a good fielder.''
</P>
<P>
   Klassen has had three errors in eight games with the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The error barrage in El Paso helped him deal with what he thinks
is a major fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get frustrated very easily, and it's something I really have
to work on,'' Klassen said. ``I know I'm going to make mistakes.
Part of the growing process is learning not to carry your fielding
with you to the plate, or your bat into the field. You have to
separate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Showalter hasn't sensed any frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``When young players come up they often get caught up in the
emotion of the moment,'' he said. ``Danny has had good, controlled
at-bats. I like the way he takes batting practice. There's no ego
involved. He's not up there to impress you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll take a round or two to go the opposite way. He stays
behind and lets the ball go deep into the zone, which will give him
a chance to hit the breaking ball better. He's a humble kid. A lot
of guys let ego get involved in batting practice and try to make it
a home run derby. You can tell he's in there to get ready for a
game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1133EDT &QL; 
