<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS PITCHER `LUCKY'  
 WAGNER OK, LEAVES HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO AND TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A tired Billy Wagner left Phoenix ``in very good
spirts'' less than 18 hours after being struck on the side of the
head by a line drive during the Diamondbacks-Astros game Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner was released from Barrow Neurological Institute of St.
Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center on Thursday and flew back to
Houston to join his wife, Sarah, who is eight months pregnant with
the couple's first child.
</P>
<P>
   The relief pitcher suffered no long-term injuries after a ball
hit by Diamondbacks catcher Kelly Stinnett in the ninth inning went
off his head and ricocheted to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who never lost consciousness and was carried off the
field, is expected to be sidelined for one to two weeks, according
to Dr. Curtis Dickman, Wagner's neurologist at Barrow. He said
Wagner suffered a soft tissue injury (bruise) to his scalp and left
ear. There was no brain injury and no skull fracture, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dickman said that Wagner lost just a small amount of blood
despite the force of the impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very lucky,'' Dickman said. ``He was in very good
spirits today before he left. He was sore and dizzy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect this issue to resolve completely in one to two
weeks. Mr. Wagner will make a full return to playing baseball once
he receives medical clearance from his physicians in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickman said the dizziness was the result of a concussion to the
inner ear, which was caused by the impact of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's wife, who watched the play on television, received a
number of calls from the wives of other players Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a traumatic night for pitcher Mike Magnante, a close
friend of Wagner's, who entered the game after Wagner was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put it out of your mind,'' Magnante said. ``I
thought about it a couple of times out there when I'm facing Matt
Williams and we're calling a sinker away. But the bottom line is
you've just got to believe it's not going to happen or else you
can't play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pitcher's worst nightmare,'' Magnante said. ``You just
hope it never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett said, ``It was an unfortunate thing. Hopefully, he's
doing well. You always talk about guys hitting the ball up the
middle. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros General Manager Gerry Hunsicker said the team wasn't
considering placing Wagner on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is among the most popular of the Astros. The 5-foot-11
left-hander always sprints to the mound, jumping over the foul line
along the way. He throws hard, consistently in the upper 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary as hell,'' said Magnante, who was watching from the
bullpen. ``We were 350 feet away and we couldn't do anything except
for what everybody else was doing, which was watching and praying.
I got to talk to him right before they put him in the ambulance. He
just asked me to tell his wife that he was fine.'' &QL; 
Includes information from The Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
