<HEADER>
A9941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSS-ART-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-17 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSS-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSS PRIZE FINALISTS: CONTEMPORARY WORKS INTENDED TO PROVOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whatever else may be said about it, no one can
complain that the short list of artists eligible for the second
Hugo Boss Prize is not, er, multicultural. The six finalists
represent a wide geographical spread, from China and Korea to South
Africa to the United States, and a respectable ethnic mix.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the $50,000 award, given biennially by Hugo Boss
AG, a men's wear company based in Metzingen, Germany, and
administered by the Guggenheim Museum, will be named on July 29.
(The inaugural prize in 1996 went to an American, Matthew Barney.)
</P>
<P>
   The rainbow of candidates is apparently less about political
correctness than the far-flung, symbiotic interests of the two
parties involved in the selection. The Guggenheim has ''a global
approach to culture,'' said its director, Thomas Krens. And Hugo
Boss, which since 1995 has been sponsoring various exhibitions and
activities at the Guggenheim, has outlets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The award is meant to honor an international artist whose works
''have made a decisive contribution to the advancement of
contemporary art'' and ''whose ideas both challenge and provoke
us,'' writes Joachim Vogt, chairman and chief executive of Hugo
Boss in the exhibition catalog.
</P>
<P>
   In the same publication, the show's organizer, Nancy Spector,
curator of contemporary art at the Guggenheim, says that the notion
of finding a ''best'' artist ''pales in importance to the
possibility of raising crucial public awareness'' about
contemporary artistic practices.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prize, whatever its role in raising public awareness,
also generates _ for very little money _ a buzz that benefits the
donor at least as much as the recipient. But in this time of
shrinking support from governments and corporations, a prize is a
prize is a prize, and no one should sneeze at a gift of fifty
grand.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors, drawn from an international roster of curators,
could nominate up to 10 artists. Works by the six finalists _
Douglas Gordon, Scotland; Huang Yong Ping, China; William
Kentridge, South Africa; Lee Bul, South Korea; Pipilotti Rist,
Switzerland, and Lorna Simpson, United States _ are on view in
''The Hugo Boss Prize, 1998'' at the Guggenheim Museum, SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that although the nominees have had a fair
amount of exposure, they are not yet hackneyed names on the
international art scene. Still, there isn't a lot going on here
that couldn't be seen in a good midseason week of New York art
trotting. The difference is maybe in scale: the vast Guggenheim
spaces tend to magnify effects.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work is in film or video, with the exception of
contributions by Ms. Bul and Huang. Huang, whose use of live
animals and insects reflects their symbolic presence in Chinese
legends, presents an arresting environmental sculpture, ''The Saint
Learns from a Spider to Weave a Cobweb'' (1997). A giant web of
copper tubing that sprawls over the gallery's ceiling dangles a
dozen wire-mesh bags, each of which imprisons a live, alert
tarantula. An empty chair hangs from the web's center.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, we are told, refers to the teachings of a Taoist
alchemist, Ge Hong, who proclaimed the superiority of animals over
human beings. The empty chair that hangs from the web symbolizes
the presence of a saint who derives his creativity from observing
how nature works, i.e., the tarantulas. And they, quietly watching
for victims, represent a ``noncompeting strategy'' in the bustle of
the world. This intriguing work doesn't really encourage
contemplation _ suppose those nightmarish spiders got loose! _ but
there's strength in its calm silence.
</P>
<P>
   A more raucous event is Kentridge's ''Ubu Tells the Truth''
(1997), a mix of found film, stills and animation transferred to
videotape that makes the craven Ubu of Alfred Jarry's 1896 farce
into a symbol of apartheid. This Ubu is a racist killer whose
crimes are rendered by Kentridge in a surreal montage that melds
documentary scenes of South African atrocities with clever
animation. The film clobbers you with nutty segues from satire to
horror and back.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ''Hysterical'' (1995), a film installation by
Gordon, seems campy and overblown. He uses a short segment from an
early medical film that demonstrates a masked woman being treated,
presumably for a psychiatric disorder, by two doctors. As they lay
restraining hands on her in bed, the action is projected onto two
giant free-standing screens: at normal speed on one, slowed down
and reversed on the other. The brief scene is continuously
repeated, resulting in a boring back and forth of jumpy images
inviting scrutiny for less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simpson, known for her still photographs with evocative
texts about ambiguous relationships, has recently ventured into
film installation, and ''Recollection'' (1998) has its premiere
here. A black-and-white videotape, it depicts several women, Asian
and black, in one-sided telephone conversations that hint at
assignations and misunderstandings. Ms. Simpson's work transfers
well to film, intensifying the sense of ambiguity engendered by her
still photographs.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost walk into Ms. Rist's ''Sip My Ocean'' (1996), a
mammoth, dual-screen video environment projected into the angle of
two walls. Filmed mostly underwater, it's a lush paean to ocean
life _ coral gardens, dancing seaweed, crustaceans, romping fish _
into which the outside world intrudes in the form of floating cups,
dropped china, sensual glimpses of a woman's body. Over it all
floats the artist's voice singing a pop ballad about love. A sassy
piece of work, shot through with humor and a sense of sybaritic
merging with the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The show's most static exhibit is Ms. Bul's four white silicone
''Cyborg'' sculptures that hang from the ceiling, suggesting
robotic mutations of the female form, in which breasts are apt to
connect with legs and outer-space armor melds with body parts. The
cyborgs convey a futuristic view of women's gender strength, while
the out-of-sync bodies augur the menace of technology.
</P>
<P>
   And that, take it or leave it, is the Boss prize show. Who'll be
the winner seems, at this point, of less than momentous interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
