r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USAFRICA-TRADE-BOX-$A     07-17 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAFRICA-TRADE-BOX-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT PEOPLE ARE SAYING ABOUT THE U.S.-AFRICA TRADE BILL
 &HT;    With USAFRICA-TRADE-$ADV18.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, July 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROPONENTS
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a strong message that the only superpower left in the
world is concerned about trading with Africa.
</P>
<P>
   -Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., longtime civil rights proponent and
member of the Congressional Black Caucus
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first systematic attempt to incorporate trade and
investment in the overall policy toward Africa. We're not talking
about just a way to shoehorn U.S. businesses into Africa but a way
to address mutual concerns of both American businesses in Africa
and African businesses in America.''
</P>
<P>
   -Bill Jackson, The Africa-America Institute
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a global community where trade is the basis of most
capital. Until Africa becomes an active participant it will be hard
for it to attain self-sustaining development.''
</P>
<P>
   -Herschelle Challenor, Africa expert at Clark Atlanta University
</P>
<P>
   ``Years from now, I hope we can look back and be able to say
that we were there at a crucial juncture in Africa's growth and
development, that we played a constructive role in that change and
that we did the right thing at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   -Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   OPPONENTS
</P>
<P>
   ``The eligibility conditions, when met, will cause a great deal
of hardship at ground levels in countries and further constitute a
broad side assault on the sovereignty of these countries. I think
it is a bad piece of legislation. Unless it is amended, it will do
incalculable damage and bring hardship to people across Africa. It
was obviously crafted in a one-sided way to serve the interests of
the American corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
   -Randall Robinson, President, TransAfrica
</P>
<P>
   If there is not a conscious effort, by law, to structure African
Americans into the Africa trade bill we have virtually no hope of
benefitting from increased world trade in general. I don't know the
exact language, but such language could be found if there was a
will to be inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   -Rep. Jesse L. Jackson, Jr. (D-Ill.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition will increase as people understand more and
more what's at stake. When you start to read the fine print, you
realize it has different meanings and implications.''
</P>
<P>
   -William Lucy, American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees
</P>
<P>
   ``Our African colleagues oppose this bill because it grants
sweetheart deals for oil and other foreign corporations while
demanding African nations cut health, education and food programs
vital to their development.''
</P>
<P>
   -Lori Wallach, Public Citizen
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
