<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTOM LINE ON DEATH ROW: A MUSHROOMING POPULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Convicted double-murderer Bill Bradford _ who
had decided to drop his federal appeal and accept an execution date
of Aug. 18 _ reportedly has changed his mind, according to an
anti-death-penalty activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has decided to re-initiate his appeal,'' said Lance
Lindsey, director of Death Penalty Focus of California. ``It will
just be a matter of time before they vacate the execution date.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, 54, an amateur photographer, was convicted of luring
two Southern California women to their deaths under the pretext of
using them as models in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   His death sentence was upheld a year ago by the state Supreme
Court. An execution date of Aug. 18 recently was set by Los Angeles
Superior Court Judge Paul Boland after Bradford sent him a letter
that read, ``Please be advised that I am of sound mind and fully
agreeable with the selected date for execution of the death
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bradford has changed his mind, it means a California
death-penalty milestone _ two executions in four weeks _ will not
be marked.
</P>
<P>
   The death by lethal injection of rapist-killer Tommy Thompson on
Tuesday was the first execution in more than two years. Only five
men have died in San Quentin's death chamber since capital
punishment was reimposed by the state in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   For death-penalty proponents, the sluggish pace of prosecutions
poses a problem: a backlog of death row inmates. More than 500
inmates are on death row in California, about the same number of
people who have been executed since the state's first death-penalty
statute was enacted in 1851.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they execute one person a week, it would take 10 years to
go through the current (death row) population,'' said Lindsey.
``Because we put 35 to 40 new inmates on death row each year, you
would still have the same number there at the end of 10 years and
you would have to go through the same process of weekly
executions.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey believes that kind of speedup would not be palatable to
the population, which supports the death penalty by a substantial
margin, ranging from 70 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some increase in the rate of executions is inevitable because of
Congress' 1996 Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act,
which limits the time for filing a federal habeas corpus appeal to
one year and makes it harder to file appeals based on new evidence
of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But California is a long way from emulating Texas, where 37
people were executed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``What one could expect from California death cases in the
future is not that a trickle becomes a flood, but that a trickle
becomes a larger trickle,'' said Franklin Zimring, a professor at
UC-Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of Law. ``You would guess one or
two more executions this year, and probably similar magnitudes next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, condemned inmates who began their federal appeals
process before the 1996 act was passed are not affected. They can
file an unlimited number of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still have this long backlog over a number of years of
those petitions that were on file beforehand,'' said Kent
Scheidegger of the Criminal Justice Legal Foundation, a
pro-death-penalty organization in Sacramento. ``The main effect of
(the '96 act) is coming. It isn't here yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-2NDLEDE-$ADV19-     07-17 2583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-2NDLEDE-$ADV19-(2TAKES)- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR SPACE HERO JOHN GLENN, OCTOBER MISSION IS ALREADY UNDER WAY
 &HT;    Corrects spelling of ``accidentally'' in graf 44.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 19.
 &HT;    PHOTOS are available from The New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    EDS: If you have questions, please contact Ray Marcano at (937)
225-2323. After 2 p.m. Thursday, reach him by beeper at
1-800-817-7243, Pin Num. 255-2153
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A carnival-sized crowd in blue suits and neckties
abruptly pulled stakes at the end of the speech, and the carpeted
warehouse in which NASA keeps its biggest space training equipment
ebbed into a hush.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of the president can do that to a room, even one
this big and industrial: drain it of so many people so quickly it
feels like the air has left, too. Spectators, security officers,
television cameras with their clacking bird legs, all suddenly
gone. Out.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone split with President Clinton after his tour of
the Johnson Space Center on this hot April afternoon. The seven
bright crew members of the space shuttle Discovery still kicked
around on NASA's royal blue carpet, still buzzing a bit from the
VIP glow. With one exception.
</P>
<P>
   Payload specialist John Glenn, a native Ohioan, was not high on
the thrill of having been with the president, something he does now
and then in his day job. Instead he enjoyed a more precious moment:
hanging out with his space ship crew.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the glare, off camera, Glenn reveled in the
camaraderie of being John rather than Senator Glenn, dribbling out
M&AMP;Ms to all hands, swapping tastes of the space food that was
sampled by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing in the glory of it. Biting a steaming fork of
rehydrated shrimp cocktail offered by a crew mate who declared it
``the Cadillac of space food.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this is great!'' Glenn said, mouth open, chewing, hot.
``May have shrimp for breakfast, lunch and dinner, I don't know. I
found out one thing in tasting it: stir it up a little bit. If you
get down to the corner (of the plastic bag) where that horseradish
is concentrated, Ohhhhhh!''
</P>
<P>
   America is waiting for John Glenn's return to glory with the
shuttle launch in October, but Glenn himself is not. He turned 77
Saturday(NOTE: JULY 18), and for him the glory is already back.
</P>
<P>
   He is tenacious yet patient in the pursuit of his mission, and
those traits have served him well. That's why he broke the coast-to
coast flight record in 1957. Why, in 1962, he became the first
American in orbit. And that is why, come Oct. 29, he'll be the
oldest human to fly in space
</P>
<P>
   The launch is not for months, but the mission is already
underway. It's in the endless training on shuttle systems and the
poring over experiment manuals. It's him dangling down the side of
a life-sized shuttle trainer and mastering _ at long last since
he's been so slow warming to the new computers in his Senate office
_ the high-powered laptops that run some of the science experiments
aboard the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying every minute of it,'' Glenn said that day in
Houston, ``want to spend all the time here I can getting ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe that.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Lt. Col. Glenn rocketed through a clearing sky above
Cape Canaveral on that late February morning in 1962, he already
knew something about fame. Before the ticker tape parades and the
presidential medals and the speech before Congress, Glenn had
introduced his face to America.
</P>
<P>
   He teamed with youngster Eddie Hodges, who went on to a brief
Broadway career, to win about $25,000 on the television game show
Name that Tune in October of 1957. A former glee club member and a
life-long devotee to a good barbershop quartet, Glenn made big
money by quickly recognizing such tunes as Far Away Places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some gal just walked up to him... `` remembers Glenn's
longest, closest friend, retired Marine Corps Lt. Gen. Tom Miller,
75. ``She didn't recognize him or anything, said, 'How'd you like
to be on a show?'''
</P>
<P>
   Recognize him? Yeah, Glenn was famous even before that. Months
before this CBS talent scout spotted him shopping in the New York,
Glenn made headlines by setting a cross-country speed record. The
mission was Operation Bullet, which Glenn invented and named, and
it involved flying the F8U jet at supersonic speeds from Los
Angeles to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to wring out a supersonic engine over more than
three hours of high-powered flight time to see how it stood up. At
the same time, Glenn hoped to snag the spotlight for the Marines by
setting a record. Worked like a charm. The plane did beautifully
and Glenn, one of two pilots who took off that morning, was the
only one who didn't have to bail out before New York making the
trip faster than if he'd ridden a bullet fired from a .45 caliber
gun.
</P>
<P>
   When the Marines nominated Glenn for the Harmon Trophy, an
international aviator's prize that had previously been won by Chuck
Yeager and Howard Hughes, the Corps gave him all the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be worth mentioning that it was largely through
repeated efforts on the part of the major that the Navy and the
Defense Department permitted the flight to be made,'' the Harmon
application reads. ``Three times (Glenn) had submitted detailed
proposals and flight statistics before, on the fourth try, his
efforts bore fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn didn't win the award, but he chiseled out a reputation for
rare tenacity. Anyone who saw him make the speed record his
personal mission knew Glenn would be a guy who didn't just beat the
odds, he'd wear them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always starts from behind and winds up in the front
ranks,'' said retired Adm. James Stockdale, who was in Glenn's
class at test pilot school. ``Covered everything in his life
because he'll take on a task without necessarily having all the law
degrees and all that stuff. He's willing to get in there and learn
it as he goes. And he's still doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockdale became famous as Ross Perot's running mate in the
presidential election of 1992, but before his late-in-life
political debut he was a fighter pilot, Vietnam prisoner of war and
Congressional Medal of Honor winner. He tutored Glenn in physics
and calculus at the test pilot school in Patuxent River, Maryland
in early `54 because Glenn had left college before graduating to
fly in World War II. In exchange, Glenn taught the Naval Academy
grad to fly jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew within himself that he had the capacity to learn fast
enough to keep up with almost any academic experience,'' Stockdale
said.
</P>
<P>
   By launch day, Glenn will have spent nearly 500 hours in
training. He will know the essentials of living in orbit from
sleeping to using the bathroom (the toilet is vacuum sealed with
spring-loaded clamps that hold the astronaut in place). He'll
understand the rudiments of the shuttle life support systems and
radio operations, and he's been put in charge of the flight's still
and video photography.
</P>
<P>
   When he's done Glenn still won't be schooled in how to fly the
shuttle, but he'll be qualified for a job as a television news
cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Senator's down here we try to keep him busy because
we do have him for a limited period of time and we want him to be
as prepared with all the orbiter systems as we can,'' said Curt
Brown, Glenn's shuttle flight commander. ``Plus, he has a whole
suite of life science experiments that he has started.''
</P>
<P>
   He returns to Washington saddled with reading material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we load him up,'' said Steve Williams, training
manager for Glenn's flight, ``but he loads himself up. He's a real
interesting man to work with. He wants more than is the minimum
required to perform the job. We give him the information that's
required to do the job, and he's looking for the next level of
detail, the next level of depth of knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Industriousness is not something Glenn developed for NASA. Or
the Marines for that matter. Growing up in New Concord, a pretty
Presbyterian town about 70 miles east of Columbus, Glenn got a car
only when he made a clunker on his dad's Chevy lot run. (Mr. Glenn
was a plumber by trade, but had a car dealership in tiny New
Concord.) And he only got money as a boy by harvesting rhubarbs
from the family garden and selling them from a wagon. ``I was the
rhubarb king of New Concord!'' he boasts.
</P>
<P>
   He also was a model airplane builder who loved the taste of
speed. That old Chevy was a convertible whose top had long ago
rotted away, and Glenn never replaced it. He drilled holes in the
floor to drain the rain, and has had rag tops ever since. Yes, even
today.
</P>
<P>
   But flying was something Glenn took to as soon as he could.
Muskingum College, right there in New Concord, offered flying
lessons for physics credit under a federal program designed to
build a supply of combat pilots as World War II approached. The
class was taught on a grass field 50 miles away, but that didn't
deter Glenn. No surprise there, he just drove.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Glenn insists the whole space shuttle thing began
accidentally. He swears he wasn't fishing for a way back into the
astronaut program, to get that second space shot he was denied
during Project Mercury. President Kennedy reportedly had decided
Glenn was too popular to risk his life with another rocket flight.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was preparing for NASA's budget hearings in the summer of
1996 when he stumbled across a medical chart that listed the
multitude of physiological reactions the human body has to
prolonged weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   He saw muscle atrophy and cardiovascular shifts, and
sleeplessness and weakening of the immune system. Brittling of the
bones. Dozens of changes to the body that astronauts endure in
weightlessness before recovering fully soon after returning to the
gentle pull of earth's gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn had a thought. He snatched a medical book on geriatrics,
and there he saw another chart listing the many painful effects of
normal human aging. Muscle atrophy and cardiovascular shifts,
sleeplessness and weakening of the immune system. Brittling of the
bones.
</P>
<P>
   As a man in his 70s, Glenn was becoming familiar with some of
these conditions, though he has been stalling them as best he could
with a diet of perpetual moderation and a devotion to brisk 2-mile
walks four or five times a week.
</P>
<P>
   NASA already was working with the National Institute of Aging, a
part of the National Institutes of Health, on some of these same
issues but experts there hadn't yet proposed sending an elderly
person into space to see if an aged body would react any
differently than younger astronaut bodies do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into this thing and developed what I thought was a
rationale for somebody (in his age group) going,'' Glenn said, ``to
look into these particular areas. And if I could do it, why,
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn admits it wasn't really that casual for him. What he
saw in those medical books was more than some interesting facts
that made him curious. What Glenn saw in those medical books was a
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Within months he was on the floor of the Senate reading from
NASA documents about the similar effects of aging and space travel,
sharpening his rationale, taking it to the public through C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have the very personal attention of every
person in this country who is 60 years of age or older,'' Glenn
said from the floor. ``One thing that has happened in the look into
the life and biosciences in the NASA program has been that we find
some notable parallels between what happens to astronauts in space
and what happens to the elderly right here on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we can find what triggers some of these similarities,
perhaps we will have a whole new handle on approaching difficulties
that people have right here on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before that, he'd gone to see NASA Administrator Dan
Goldin, a President Bush appointee who found himself being asked to
approve sending into space a man born not many years after the
Wright Brothers triumphed at Kitty Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the issue was more than age because this was not
just any fit-as-a-fiddle grandfather. John Glenn is a national
icon, a Cold War and Real War hero, the very personification of
America's pioneering work in space. Glenn didn't just ride
America's first space capsule into orbit, he designed the
instrument panel. It would be like bringing back Henry Ford to race
the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   It was an opportunity of great poetry and great danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space frontier is unforgiving to error,'' Goldin said.
``It was a very big decision that had to be made. You know, it was
not a comfortable decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to be the guy whose decision to send America's John
Glenn back into space accidentally kills him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was uncomfortable in the sense, here is a national hero,''
Goldin said. ``President Kennedy made just the opposite decision. I
mean, the President of the United States decided not fly him
because he was a national hero. So it was uncomfortable in that
sense because I was going to override what President Kennedy had
decided some 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin made a list of requirements that would have to be met
before he'd agree to the flight. The science experiments would have
to be legit, Glenn's health would have to be a certainty, the White
House would have to stay out of the process, and Glenn's wife Annie
would have to be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know her and I called her,'' Goldin said of Glenn's wife
since 1943. ``You know what she said to me? `This is what John
wants to do. I've been with him for 55 years, I'm going to support
him.' ``
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, Glenn, as he is want to do, just kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   Need the experiments peer reviewed? Fine, tell me if I can
provide anything to help. Want me to pass a physical? Fine, you
pick the doctor. Need my medical history? No problem, I've been
sending NASA my annual physicals every year since I left the space
program in 1964. Between NASA and the Marines, the government has
most every one since I was in college.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin insisted on no medical waivers, ``and I said, `Fair
enough,'' Glenn said. He told his 52-year-old son David, a
physician in California, about all the medical tests he'd undergone
and the younger Glenn concluded that NASA had done everything but
an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn was not content to sit back and wait for the signal.
He started calling Goldin. To check. How's it going? What's cooking
on my idea for a shuttle flight? Have you heard anything new? Can I
get you any more information?
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Tom Miller got a call at home in Arlington.
This is the same Arlington house he lived in back in 1962, which is
next door to the house the Glenn's owned at the time -_ the Millers
and Glenns built the houses side by side _ the house where Annie
Glenn and the two teenaged Glenn kids watched America's first
orbital flight, and where Vice President Lyndon Johnson dropped by
that historic day.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goldin was on the phone. He needed suggestions for dealing
with Glenn, Miller says. The senator was driving folks at NASA
crazy. But Miller didn't have much advice to offer on taming this
guy he'd known since flight school 50 years ago. It was more like a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Dan, `You're in contact with the most persistent person
I've ever known.'''
</P>
<P>
   NYT-07-15-98 1308EDT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
