<HEADLINE>
BROTHERS PRAISE JURY FOR PUNISHING ABUSIVE PRIEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two California brothers on Friday praised a
jury's decision to order the Catholic church to pay them $30
million for failing to prevent a parish priest from molesting them
repeatedly over several years.
</P>
<P>
   James and Joh Howard, who were awarded $6 million in
compensatory damages and $24 million in punitive damages Thursday
in Stockton, Calif., claimed the Stockton diocese knew the Rev.
Oliver Francis O'Grady was a child molester and did nothing to stop
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're raised Catholic, you're raised to respect and revere
these people,'' James said. ``Issues of sexuality were taboo and
there was a lot of guilt and shame associated with that.''
</P>
<P>
   James, 23, who now lives in Berkeley, Calif., and works in San
Francisco as a structural engineer, said he was molested by O'Grady
from the time he was 5 years old until he was 12. He said he
learned only five years ago that Joh, 19, and his two older
brothers had also been abused by the priest, who was a close
advisor of their mother's, when he brought the matter up with his
siblings at his sister's wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit brought by the two older brothers was thrown out, he
said, because the statute of limitations had expired.
</P>
<P>
   O'Grady was convicted in 1993 of molesting James and Joh Howard
between 1978 and 1991. He is serving a 14-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   The civil trial that resulted in Thursday's verdict began in
early June. The case revolved around the question of whether or not
the diocese knew about O'Grady's sexual deviancy and, if they knew,
whether or not they were responsible for allowing him to be around
children.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony of Los Angeles, who was bishop of Stockton
from 1980 to 1985, denied in court that he knew O'Grady was a
molester at the time. But that testimony was contradicted by two
therapists who had treated O'Grady and said Mahony knew of his
condition, said Clohessy, who worked with the Howard family during
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The current bishop of Stockton, Donald W. Montrose, issued a
statement Thursday afternoon asking the Howards' forgiveness ``for
this horrible evil that was inflicted on them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the diocese made a sincere effort to respond to the
matter. I regret we did not understand the depth of the problem,''
he said. ``Father O'Grady spent many years in therapy and during
this time, the diocese believed it was acting responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Clohessy, director of the Chicago-based group
Survivors Network of those Abused by Priests, said the church
should have taken steps to remove O'Grady after he admitted in 1976
to molesting a 14-year-old Lodi girl, or after his therapist called
Child Protective Services in 1984 about another incident, prompting
a police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Anderson, an attorney for the Howards, said the large
punitive damage award should impel the church to take allegations
of abuse more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big-time message,'' he said, ``one that has to be
heard across the land in every diocese.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Montrose said the jury's decision will ``punish the
diocese in a way which will effectively destroy virtually all of
the services provided by the diocese to its people and the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the punitive damages of $24 million, Joh and
James Howard each were awarded $2.75million for past and future
mental and emotional pain and suffering, and $100,000 for damage to
future medical care and therapy. Joh Howard was given $450,000 for
future loss of wage-earning capacity, whereas James received
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came less than a week after the Catholic Diocese of
Dallas agreed to pay $23.4million to nine former altar boys in a
similar case.
</P>
</TEXT>
