<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-TRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS CALLS FOR MORE TRAINING FOR NEW YORK TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New teachers will have to take 175 hours of
training every five years or risk losing their certificates under a
far-reaching plan by the New York state Board of Regents that aims
to improve teacher performance.
</P>
<P>
   The new requirement, effective Sept. 1, 2000, was part of a
package of reforms endorsed by the state in an effort to overhaul
the way teachers are certified, disciplined, trained and recruited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what occurred today is history for teaching in New
York and across the nation,'' said Regents Chancellor Carl T.
Hayden. Thursday's vote put an end to more than two years of debate
on the best way to update teacher standards. The regents have
already established higher graduation standards for students, more
rigorous tests and annual School Report Cards in an effort to
improve academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're placing everything we do in alignment today,'' Hayden
said. He said the reforms not only challenge teachers to do better
but the education programs that prepare them.
</P>
<P>
   The plan represents a compromise. Teachers faced mounting
pressure to overhaul tenure, with some critics calling for
mandatory periodic testing for teachers to remain certified. The
regents plan falls short of such a requirement, but requires
periodic training instead for new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's plan requires all teacher education programs to be
accredited and essentially shut down programs in which fewer than
80 percent of their graduates pass the state certification exam.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it would require school districts to evaluate
teachers on an annual basis and require all teachers who are rated
unsatisfactory to embark on a ``teacher improvement plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the plan was generally positive on Thursday, despite
concerns over who will pay for the 175 hours of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the chief concern of our membership,'' said Judy Warde,
assistance executive director of the state School Boards'
Association, ``that there won't be enough money to do the work
that's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The regents plan anticipates state funding to cover the training
at an annual cost of up to $100 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Antonia Cortese, first vice president for New York State United
Teachers, said the union would lobby to secure that money, so
poorer districts aren't at a disadvantage. ``We'll be working to
make sure the state provides its share of the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   NYSUT, the state's largest teacher's union, came out in favor of
the 175-hour professional development program after the Regents
agreed not to make it mandatory for existing teachers. A
last-minute amendment to lower the requirement to 125 hours failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important step forward,'' said Cortese. ``It says we
value teachers. It says what they know is important for what kids
need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the battle to require such training for all
teachers, several board members said they hoped current teachers
would take advantage of continuing education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, school districts will be required to have a
professional development program in place for all teachers by Sept.
1, 1999 or face state sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe teachers, if given the opportunity, will take
advantage of it,'' said Bill Hirschen, spokesman for the state
Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   Several school district officials said they support the
requirement for continuing education, despite uncertainly over how
such programs will be funded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to cause a great burden and it has a
lot of potential for improving what goes on in the classroom,''
said Schenectady School Superintendent Raymond Colucciello.
</P>
<P>
   Albany School Superintendent Lonnie Palmer also said the new
requirement will fit into what the district is already doing to
hone staff skills.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of plan include a requirement that all new
teachers complete their master's degree within two years of
starting their careers. The current standards gives teachers up to
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea that there's a master's
requirement,'' said Palmer. But he said he was concerned about
teachers not getting enough hands-on experience. ``I think it's
crucial that those graduate education programs are immersed in real
teaching experiences.'' Other highlights of the plan include:
Requiring new teachers to pass three exams in liberal arts, their
content speciality and teaching skills before they can be
certified; Providing all new teachers with a year of state-funded
mentoring experience; Setting up a statewide ``Professional
Standards and Practices Boards,'' to maintain teacher standards and
accountability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
