<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO MILITARY BASE HOUSING PLANS MOVE FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECILIA BALLI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Government officials describe it as a quality of
life nightmare: Unable to provide adequate housing, the military
gradually is dissuading service men and women with families from
re-enlisting.
</P>
<P>
   But with a much-awaited turn toward privatizing base
construction and maintenance, local military leaders say they
finally have the financial muscle to replace deteriorating housing
units and reduce two-year waiting lists commonplace for enlisted
personnel with families.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2-and-1/2 years have passed since Congress authorized the
Pentagon to contract with private builders and developers to
replace dilapidated military housing.
</P>
<P>
   Progress has been slow, but plans to construct 840 new family
housing units at Fort Sam Houston and Lackland AFB are inching
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the Army is approaching business today is truly unique
in my experience,'' said Col. Bill Thresher, post commander at Fort
Sam Houston in San Antonio. ``There is certainly a sense of
entrepreneurial spirit that did not exist prior, which gives us the
facility to investigate very good buying decisions that affect the
military and the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Before privatization, military bases had to rely on relatively
small amounts of construction money doled out in yearly
congressional appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   However, those funds often are earmarked for the renovation or
one-for-one replacement of shabby military family homes not for
adding to existing base housing stock.
</P>
<P>
   With 61 percent of the nation's military population married
compared to 42 percent in the 1950s the housing crunch threatened
to become perpetual.
</P>
<P>
   Since the go-ahead to do business with developers, however,
there's hope Bexar County military bases finally will begin to add
housing units, cutting into waiting lists that can reach 30 months.
</P>
<P>
   Take Lackland, for example. With funds appropriated this fiscal
year, the Air Force plans to replace 50 units built in the 1950s
units plagued with water leaks, worn roofs, termite damage and
heating and cooling problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lackland officials are negotiating with an
Austin firm to build a multimillion-dollar, 420-unit complex for
married enlistees by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of those units will replace hundreds of homes
slated for demolition, the privatization project will also yield
148 surplus units.
</P>
<P>
   ``That typically doesn't happen in military construction, ''
said Debra Harkiewicz, chief of the base's privatization office.
``There isn't that kind of money at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Sam Houston is now one of five Army posts waiting for
approval to enter its own private construction venture.
</P>
<P>
   In six years, Thresher said, officials hope to replace 320
family units and construct an additional 100 nearly enough to
satisfy the post's need.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, roughly one-third of all military families live on
base. In the San Antonio area, only about 10 percent to 25 percent
of those stationed at Fort Sam Houston and at other air bases in
the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
