<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAY-LENO-TRIPP-JOKES-     07-17 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAY-LENO-TRIPP-JOKES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAY LENO: NICE GUY (MAYBE). FUNNY JOKE (NOT) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Jay Leno: Nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   That's what everyone says about him. Popular wisdom says the
``Tonight Show'' host is one of the most decent celebrities around
_ a hardworking everyman who's never too busy to sign an autograph
or pose for a photo.
</P>
<P>
   I can think of at least three or four friends of mine who have
pictures of themselves with Jay. Arms tossed around each other, big
grins. These aren't people who work in the media and would have
special access to Leno _ they're fans who have met him in the Billy
Goat or at Mr. Beef or somewhere in LA.
</P>
<P>
   They all had the same thing to say about their encounter. It was
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   You never hear about Leno brushing off a fan in some diner or
being rude to a waitress. He's more likely to don an apron and
pitch in behind the counter for a half hour, all the while posing
for snapshots and cracking jokes and reminding everyone what time
every night he's on NBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I've long thought there's also something disturbing about
the guy. Any grown man who would hide in a closet to eavesdrop on a
conversation between network executives, as Leno did when he was up
for the job as Johnny Carson's replacement, has a bit of a dark and
sneaky side, wouldn't you say?
</P>
<P>
   There's also a dichotomy between the ever-grinning Leno who
comes out before a show's taping in denim work shirt and blue
jeans, working the crowd, and the often mean-spirited monologuist.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment lore says Leno trumped David Letterman in the
ratings in July, 1995, with the infamous ``What the hell were you
thinking!'' interview of then-scandalized Hugh Grant. While that
show did give Leno a ratings boost, he actually started gaining
steadily on Letterman earlier that year _ when he peppered each
night's monologue with joke after joke about the O.J. Simpson
trial. Who can forget the Dancing Itos?
</P>
<P>
   Letterman, the supposedly mean one, refused to do O.J. jokes for
months, despite pleadings from his staff. ``I just don't think
double murder is funny,'' said Dave.
</P>
<P>
   Leno had no such moral qualms; he mined the trial for every
nugget of humor he could find, never worrying about stepping into
tasteless territory. By the time Letterman gave up his stance and
started cracking wise on O.J., it was too late. The ratings war was
over.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Letterman was the one who held off for so long
on the O.J. jokes, all the headlines about Leno said, ``Nice Guys
Finish First.''
</P>
<P>
   You want further proof Jay's a good guy? Consider how he reacted
last week when he was criticized for a joke he made after attending
Harley-Davidson's 95th Anniversary Reunion in Milwaukee. Leno said
that while he feels fat in Los Angeles, all those big bikers in
Brat-town made him feel thin by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. He called some bikers fat. You know what? Some of 'em
are.
</P>
<P>
   But Leno reportedly received reams of mail from Milwaukeeans who
were steamed about the remark, including some nasty threats. He was
also criticized in the Milwaukee media.
</P>
<P>
   Weird. It seems as if half the jokes Leno made on his most
recent visit to Chicago were about our love of pizza and beef and
other thick foods, and I can't recall a single complaint. Guess
they're touchier in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Super-nice Jay's reaction to the criticism? Major mea culpas. He
telephoned Milwaukee Journal Sentinel columnist Joyce
Evans-Campbell to apologize, telling her, ``I didn't mean anything
by it. It was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Leno called a thin biker who was featured in
Evans-Campbell's column, to apologize to him. How nice can you get?
</P>
<P>
   Well. I guess it depends on whose looks you're mocking. Even as
the biker controversy was brewing, Leno had this to say about the
sex scandal in Washington: ``Linda Tripp testified last week. For a
minute, I thought they were rerunning the movie `Tootsie.'''
</P>
<P>
   And: ``Linda Tripp has her own Web site on the Internet. There's
one Web site you pray they don't have nude pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny. Cheap. Easy.
</P>
<P>
   So in other words, it's all right to mock the physical
appearance of a stout woman, even if that woman is the mother of
two children, but you should apologize if you make fun of
big-bodied bikers.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting how the mind of a nice guy works sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
