<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0044 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-BOMBING-CONFESSI     07-17 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOMBING-CONFESSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, U.S. BEHAVIOR IN LATIN AMERICA MUST BE ADDRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A confusing and rambling, but revealing, interview granted last
week to The New York Times by Cuban exile and self-styled terrorist
Luis Posadas Carriles has helped uncover a convoluted and painful
issue in U.S.-Latin American relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban's confessions of planting bombs in Havana hotels last
year, and killing an Italian tourist, but also of carrying out
assassination attempts on Fidel Castro's life in the early 1960s,
raises an issue that has been lingering on the U.S.-Latin American
agenda for several years.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a central point, nor one that will be addressed
promptly or easily. But it should be faced, as the century comes to
a close and a full decade passes since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, the two superpowers waged a surrogate
war around the globe. The former Soviet Union paid its dues bylosing the Cold War _ its penitence lies in the humiliating defeat
that brought its existence to an end. The United States bore much
of its burden domestically _ part of the Cold War's cost was paid
for by the internal dissension and distress wrought by Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But although the damage provoked by the superpowers in Latin
America was nowhere near what occurred elsewhere in the Third
World, neither the Soviet Union nor the United States have really
come to terms with this dark history, nor made amends for what
happened. The USSR is no longer around to revisit the past; the
United States is.
</P>
<P>
   Posadas' confessions regarding his participation in terrorist
bombings as recently as last year, as well as his claims that these
and other terrorist acts were directly financed by Jorge Mas Canosa
and the Cuban-American National Foundation, bring the problem to
the fore.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation, a powerful anti-Castro lobbying group, has been
welcome at the White House for nearly two decades. It also has
tax-exempt status and has received federal support for many of its
projects. It denies involvement, but is now accused by its most
ardent supporters, not simply by Castro's intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA and FBI have also dimissed any connection ``for years''
with Posadas, but given their track record on such matters, the
denials are less than credible. The real question is whether it is
time for the Clinton administration, on its own, to open an
independent investigation of U.S. behavior in Latin America during
the Cold War, and whether that behavior was compatible with
perennial American laws and values, and not merely the political
imperatives of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for the United States to sit in judgement of its own
history in Latin America, as other nations have done, for example,
in regard to World War II. The point is not for others to judge the
United States _ this has already been done, and for better or for
worse, most informed Latin Americans have their views on the
subject. Washington should delve into its own archives, testimony,
confessions and recollections to determine what was right and what
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out, as many suspect, that at least part of what was
done ran flagrantly counter to American principles, then apologies
are in order. Although what occurred was partially explainable by
the Cold War logic of the time, if U.S. laws and norms were
violated, it should be so stated and Washington should ask to be
forgiven by those who became the victims of its illicit acts.
</P>
<P>
   The process already has begun in these better-known cases:
</P>
<P>
   _ the CIA-sponsored coup in Guatemala in 1954 that ushered in a
45-year period of violence, repression and instability which is
only now beginning to subside, and which has included instances of
CIA involvement in highly questionable acts as recently as five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ the Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba in 1961, the official
investigation and report of which was just recently issued by the
CIA. A force sponsored, financed and trained by the United States
invaded a sovereign nation whose government was recognized as
legitimate by the world community.
</P>
<P>
   _ the full-fledged invasion of the Dominican Republic in April
1965, where the presumed threat of instability and ``communism''
warranted, to the Lyndon B. Johnson administration, an open
occupation of the island.
</P>
<P>
   _ the various CIA-organized dirty tricks against Salvador
Allende of Chile, between October 1970 and September 1973, which
though partially investigated by the congressional Church Committee
in 1975, were always tempered by the arguable thesis that the
Chilean people wanted to overthrow Allende.
</P>
<P>
   _ the financing, training and sponsoring of the contras in
Nicaragua during the 1980s, where the United States openly sought
to overthrow a government with which it had diplomatic relations.
Yet this administration was fully recognized by the local and
international community, and had committed no hostile act against
the United States other than strident rhetoric and unfriendly
votes.
</P>
<P>
   _ the Christmas invasion of Panama in 1989, where Washington
unleashed the bloodiest, most costly and disproportionate drug-bust
ever against Manuel Noriega, someone who probably deserved to spend
years in jail, but not at the cost of hundreds of lives, and
millions of dollars in damage.
</P>
<P>
   All of these instances can be judged from two perspectives: the
Cold War rationale of the time, and the more lasting criteria of
American and universal values of morality, respect for the rule of
law and international coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   One can understand the logic of the moment, but it cannot be an
eternal standard. If that were the case, aberrations such as
slavery, segregation, colonialism and torture would all be
perpetually justified. At the time they occurred, they were either
legal, accepted or tolerated. Yet today, with other values and
other views, they are all deemed immoral, reprehensible and wrong.
Governments, states and leaders are increasingly responding to
demands for a revision of their past, for a more balanced judgement
of their history, and for apologies when they are due.
</P>
<P>
   Events transpired cannot be relived, and there are undoubtedly
more pressing problems to address at present, but the uncertainties
of the future can perhaps best be faced by getting on with this
wrenching but necessary settling of scores from the past.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
