<SLUG> BC-DOG-CUSTODY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREYHOUND STILL STUCK IN ALASKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LORENA FIGUEROA  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ ``Rapido Sable'' may have a slow race back home.
</P>
<P>
   Sable, a 3-year-old retired racing greyhound, is caught in the
middle of a custody battle between her temporary owner in
Fairbanks, Alaska, and Greyhound Pets of America's San Antonio
chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Elsy Bless, president of the Helotes-based non-profit
organization, had raised money for Sable's return to San Antonio
after a military family that adopted her moved to Fairbanks and
abandoned her at a dog pound there.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Cook, who works at the Fairbanks pound and was taking care
of Sable pending her return here, does not want to send her back,
Bless said.
</P>
<P>
   So Bless did what anyone does in a custody fight: she has
consulted a lawyer and is preparing to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going with this until the bitter end,'' Bless said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook declined to comment on Bless' allegations or say whether
she planned to keep the dog.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared at a Fairbanks television program that aired on
Monday, announcing the dog was up for adoption, Dawn Dearden, a
reporter for KTZF-TV in Fairbanks, said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, a dog handler at the Fairbanks Animal Control Facility,
has kept the dog at her home for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She turned her back on me,'' Bless said. ``Everything was all
right until Wednesday, when my lawyer told me that Tina did not
want to return Sable.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopted in February in San Antonio, Sable was left at a dog
pound June 30 in Fairbanks by her owners, Charles and Kathy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Bless requested, and got, a reprieve from the pound to keep
Sable from being euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   Cook offered to take the dog home July 2 to give Bless time to
find another owner or to raise enough money to bring the dog back
to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bless said she last talked to Cook on Saturday evening, and she
seemed cooperative about a planned return of the dog Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tina even volunteered to take the dog to the Anchorage
airport,'' Bless, who said she had planned to pay Cook's expenses
for keeping the dog, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank Tina for keeping Sable, but it makes me angry she is
trying to put the dog up for adoption without my authorization,''
Bless said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Gardner, an attorney who volunteered to work with Bless
free of charge to get Sable back, said the organization plans to
file a lawsuit next week against Cook and the Williams couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thinking of filing a sort of claim,'' said Gardner, who
has talked with Cook four times and had kept in touch with her
until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sable saga, meanwhile, has generated a lot of attention and
donations, although Bless would not say how much money the
organization raised to pay for the dog's trip home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was willing to return the donation of anyone who is
satisfied the dog is out of danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate all the support from thousands of people from all
over the United States,'' Bless said.
</P>
<P>
   She is also offering a reward to know Sable's whereabouts. Bless
can be reached at 695-8441.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a hostage in San Antonio, and I feel Sable is,
too, in Fairbanks,'' she said. -30- I
</P>
</TEXT>
