<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOTERS-$ADV19-COX     07-17 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISGUST WITH POLITICS SAPPING CITIZENSHIP, EXPERTS SAY
 &HT;    1000&AMP;add. For release Sunday, July 19.
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last September, the League of Women Voters in
Athens, Ga., staged an issues forum on children's health. Ten
people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the league sponsored an event on how to steer
non-college students to technical school. Fifteen people came. In
November, a reception to meet local candidates for office fared a
bit better, drawing a few dozen participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then we served food after work,'' laments Morene Williams,
president of the league in Athens, home of the University of
Georgia. ``It seems if there is no big conflict, people aren't
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Local community leaders such as Williams are seeing first-hand
what is crossing the radar screens of pollsters, civics experts and
university professors around the country with alarming consistency:
in the great public square of American democracy, the voting
citizenry has gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Average voter turnout in primary elections is down 14 percent
from 1996, falling to the lowest level ever in the 16 states that
have held two-party primaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   The trend suggests, many experts believe, that turnout in
November's general election will be lower than 1996. In that year,
voter participation in a general election fell below 50 percent for
the first time since 1924.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved away from any sense of civic duty, civic
responsibility and civic engagement,'' said Curtis Gans, director
of the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate, who
recently completed a study on voting trends. ``We now have an
electorate of the interested and the zealous, and both of those
pose a serious threat to our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The downward trend, visible at the ballot box for the past 40
years, extends to other aspects of civic life as well. Fewer people
report that they are paying attention to candidates and what they
are talking about. Fewer say they are closely watching the
activities of government, and confidence in government has dropped
nearly 40 points since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people joining local community groups and civic
organizations has been inching down for 20 years, according to data
compiled by the National Commission on Civic Renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in danger of becoming a nation of spectators,'' says
the commission's co-chairman, former Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The forces propelling voter retreat from the public square are
numerous. Critics of the money-driven campaign system, which
requires candidates to raise and spend vast sums, say voters
believe that money, not voting, influences their elected
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reform advocates believe that American campaigning in
the 1990s, with its emphasis on attack advertising, packaged
campaign slogans and candidates who shun direct contact with
voters, is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the public being so disconnected from
Washington and so removed from political life,'' says Fred
Wertheimer, president of the advocacy group Democracy 21. ``There
is extraordinary political game-playing in Washington, there is
deep, deep partisanship, and it confirms to citizens that too many
politicians are too interested in playing games instead of
attending to their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others look at the trends more broadly, noting that
two-parent, working families have less time to become involved.
America has also a become a highly mobile society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get established in a community, so you
don't feel any sense of civic responsibility,'' says Doug Bachtel,
a noted sociologist at the University of Georgia who studies
demographics. ``We just can't blame it on disenfranchisement. There
are a lot of economic and demographic trends driving this.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, pollsters and analysts are discovering a unique paradox
among American voters. Voters are both satisfied with the status
quo and deeply cynical about politics and government.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment and inflation at record lows, many Americans
seem content to ignore Washington and the Congress, especially when
most of what they read or hear about is a fairly consistent diet of
scandal and partisan sniping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood seems to be keep the rascals in rather than throw the
rascals out,'' said William Galston, former director of the civic
renewal commission. ``People are feeling as negative about the
political system as they are feeling positive about the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Galston, a political scientist at the University of Maryland,
adds another reason for the decline in voter participation: the
breakdown of political parties at the grass-roots level. ``We have
dismantled the institutions that tended to connect the average
citizens with political leaders,'' he says. ``If the mediating
institutions aren't there, voters are going to be increasingly
detached.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of voter disenchantment, several groups are
trying voluntary reforms in states around the country to improve
the tone and substance of political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Better Campaigns, based in Washington, is
working in 10 states to encourage local television stations to
stage regular candidate debates, and exact pledges from those
candidates that they will appear in all their advertisements _ a
way to lessen the chance of negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The Project on Campaign Conduct, led by the Institute for Global
Ethics in Maine, is sponsoring pilot projects in Ohio and
Washington this year to have candidates agree to abide by a set of
campaign ethics, such as avoiding personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted by the project and released last week found
that more than nine in 10 voters believe that candidates will
engage in negative personal attacks and will mislead voters about
their records. Just less than half said they believe that most or
all candidates lie to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This question of the negativity of our process and the
demeaning civil discourse that we find ourselves stuck with is
pushing people away,'' said Rushworth Kidder, director of the
Institute for Global Ethics. ``We have got to find a level of
discourse that is based on values and not simply on interests if we
are going to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Kidder preaches the notion that politics without the common
values of responsibility, respect, fairness, honesty and compassion
can't survive.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts and observers disagree about the root causes of
voter dissatisfaction, there is widespread agreement that the
results are potentially dangerous to the well-being of a nation
that claims to be the world's greatest democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The more average voters retreat, the more politics is controlled
by special interests. Already in Congress this summer, the
legislative calendar is filling up with measures designed to appeal
to special interests. Republicans have staged several votes on
abortion, such as making it a crime to transport a minor to another
state to avoid parental notification laws, in order to energize
religious conservatives in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, are pushing for an increase to the minimum
wage, an issue that resonates strongly among traditional Democratic
voters such as labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people stay away from participation at the polls, the
more those (special) interests dominate,'' says Nunn. ``Good
government by its very nature comes from our citizens. And if you
don't have informed, participating citizens, there is no way you
are going to have good government except by pure luck. And that
won't last long.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
