<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS UNIONS WARM TO HIM, HARSHBARGER'S CAMPAIGN HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Scott Harshbarger was up on Jake Kennedy's rubbing
table yesterday, four months to the day from when the attorney
general discovered his Achilles heel. Err, tendon.
</P>
<P>
   He missed the St. Patrick's Day Parade in Holyoke because he was
flat on his back, headed for a wheelchair-cast-crutches-limping
pattern from a freak basketball injury as he ran innocently
downcourt.
</P>
<P>
   But his campaign is not limping anymore. The
Harshbarger-for-guv'nah effort is off the runway and flying, at the
moment. And thanks in large measure to a steady surge of support
from union leaders, Harshbarger is now the heavy favorite to win
the Democratic nomination that six months ago some disregarded as
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci's lackluster summer and the
virtual disappearance of any positive campaign effort from
Cellucci's surrogates, or from running mate Jane Swift, whose
pregnancy has insulated her from the rough-and-tumble of partisan
politicking, left a void.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's Republican opponent, state Treasurer Joe Malone, has
not managed to engage Cellucci to the extent he'd like (and
Cellucci would very definitely dislike). But Harshbarger had a
better spring and early summer than any of the folks running for
governor, managing to overcome at least some of the institutional
(Beacon Hill and Mayor Tom Menino's office) reluctance to embrace
the earnest Harshbarger effort.
</P>
<P>
   Former state Senator Pat McGovern, a distant No. 2 in the
Democratic race polls, managed to raise less than $70,000 in the
latest reporting month made public, and Brian Donnelly, the former
congressman, is way in the rear. Harshbarger said yesterday he was
$1.3 million in his war chest as of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative satraps and Boston mayors have never had much
influence on the gubernatorial selection process, and that is
holding true this year. And labor union chiefs have a decidely
mixed record at the gubernatorial level, choosing to exercise their
clout far more emphatically in federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the state AFL-CIO seems to have arrived at a point where the
leadership believes it is possible to dislodge the GOP incumbent,
after eight years of hostile decisions from the corner office.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger is enjoying unexpectedly warm relations with labor
leaders who took a while to thaw. But yesterday the AG nailed down
endorsements from three powerhouse unions _ Locals 103 of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, 7 of the
Ironworkers, and 285 and 509 of the Service Employees International
Union, the private and public sector branches, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's assiduous courting of labor with programs and
policy stands intended to please union members paid off. When Joe
Faherty and Bobby Haynes of the state AFL-CIO took a hard look at
the field, they were impressed with Harshbarger's dogged field
work, and a financial operation that is the only bigtime
fund-raising effort on the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger says his AFL-CIO endorsement ``has been crucial'' to
the momentum he's built up. And he pins his hopes next on an avid
courtship of the various teachers' unions that have been under
assault on Beacon Hill from a variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole agenda we've put together for working people
appealed to the AFL-CIO, and they've got 400,000 people organized.
We are taking on this guy (Cellucci) on education, health care, and
working family issues, and it shows. The others (McGovern,
Donnelly) are perfectly good people, but we've shown the union
people that ours is the campaign that can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to various published polls showing him pulling into a
near-tie with Cellucci in some surveys, Harshbarger said, ``The
polls are now showing it, but the labor people came in ahead of the
polling.''
</P>
<P>
   Union legwork was crucial for Ted Kennedy and John Kerry in
their Senate victories, and Cellucci's reputation with labor is not
generally good.
</P>
<P>
   Even Harshbarger's critics _ and there are many establishment
Democrats who are cool to his personality and his prosecutorial
penchant for targeting prominent Democrats over the years _ concede
he is a dogged and determined campaigner, a workaholic at the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger thinks he has put together the best grass-roots
organization of this cycle. ``We're a million dollars ahead of Pat
and Brian combined, and Cellucci has been helping a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger says the incumbent's stuttering performance of late,
sitting on his big GOP polling lead vs. Malone, helps spread the
sense that ``he can be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   As he submitted to yet another rehab routine at the injury
clinic, Harshbarger dwelt on how he'll spend the next 110 days:
``There's 61 days to the primary, then 47 to the final _ and it's
beginning to come together now. I think the coalition is moving
very nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother was a teacher, and you get the feeling that teachers
and parents of public school kids may be target No. 1 for the
Harshbarger ad campaign this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
