<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-ARCHEOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STONE AGE FIND IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ernest Pouliot moved into his Eliot, Maine, home in 1992. Now he
knows how popular that choice of landscape has been _ for thousands
of years.
</P>
<P>
   In advance work for the state's ambitious natural-gas pipeline,
archeologists excavating Pouliot's property have found stone tools
dating to the dawn of human habitation in New England.
</P>
<P>
   That was 12,000 years ago, or shortly after the scarred terrain
of present-day New England appeared in the retreating tracks of a
mile-thick ice sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists say that the artifacts uncovered this month on
Pouliot's land are among the oldest ever found in New England. And
their undisturbed condition makes a find of such rare antiquity
even more valuable, the researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most significant site any of us will work
on,'' said Theresa Kintz, an archeologist who helped excavate the
site with a dozen others from mid-May until last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Kintz complained that pipe construction deadlines -- the
Canada to Massachusetts pipeline is going through Pouliot's
property -- may have applied pressure on the archeologists to
excavate the site quickly.
</P>
<P>
   John Flumerfelt, spokesman for the Portland Natural Gas
Transmission System, said he ``wouldn't deny that we made it clear
we'd like it done as quickly as possible.'' However, he said,
project officials have always been prepared to halt one of the
largest infrastructure projects in state history for proper
excavation of any important historic site.
</P>
<P>
   Principal archeologist Douglas Kellogg and Maine state
archeologist Art Spiess deny that their work in Eliot was
compromised in any way. ``We had plenty of time to do what we
needed to do,'' Kellogg said.
</P>
<P>
   Kintz herself says that the work probably was as good as could
be expected under the circumstances. But she adds that in 11 years
of field work she has never seen as quick a transition from
discovery to excavation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen us roll right over from identification of a
site to full-scale data recovery in two weeks,'' Kintz said. ``I
think we could have done a better job given more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing the best excavation possible, or rerouting construction
projects where feasible, is particularly important at such sites
because of their rarity, Kintz said. Only about two dozen such
finds have been recorded in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Spiess said that the discovery is another piece in the puzzle of
the lives of the region's earliest pioneers. And what Kellogg's
company, John Milner Associates of West Chester, Pa., finds in its
study of the tools may provide more evidence of how these
inhabitants _ the ``Paleoindians'' _ ate, camped and lived.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artifacts uncovered in Eliot were scrapers fashioned
of red flint from Munsungun Lake, 250 miles away in northern Maine.
Those stone tools may have been used to separate hides from
animals, butcher caribou for food, or fashion clothing or packs.
</P>
<P>
   Also recovered was a stone drill and a burned bone, a
potentially precious clue about what kind of game was hunted. In
those days, wooly mammoths and mastodons may have shared the
tundra-like landscape of northern New England with the descendants
of nomads who first crossed the land bridge from Siberia to North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is evidence that real people lived here for thousands of
years in the Stone Age,'' Kintz said. ``Their lives were just as
fulfilling and complicated as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eliot site fits the pattern of other Paleoindian camps
discovered in New England, archeologists said. On the southern face
of a hill, protected from the north wind, the site probably
provided good views of moving herds along the Piscataqua River
floodplain, Kintz said.
</P>
<P>
   Paleoindian hunters _ probably moving in groups of about five
families or 30 people _ routinely roamed 200-mile areas of the
region in search of food. The discovery that all of their stone
came from Munsungun Lake indicates that these prehistoric Americans
had established routes through modern Maine to obtain the tools
that were essential to their survival.
</P>
<P>
   The Eliot excavation site was filled Wednesday. Now, only the
archeologists' notes remain for future researchers who wish to
recreate the area, Kintz said. Although the ancient camp is known
to extend beyond the pipeline path, Kintz said, the opportunity to
study the site as a integrated whole has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pipeline officials and other archeologists acknowledge that
more time or preservation of the site is always preferable to
pre-construction excavation. But in this case, Flumerfelt said, the
site never would have been uncovered if not for the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a tradeoff when you find a site at the last
minute in a construction project,'' said James Bradley, director of
the Peabody Museum of Archeology, which is planning a Paleoindian
exhibit at its facility at Phillips Andover Academy in Andover,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the work that has been done will help illuminate
the lives of the earliest Americans, although its significance has
yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   But, for Kintz, the site's importance is difficult to quantify.
To her, it's an incredibly rare connection with people who exist
only in legend and the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are first Americans, the first pioneers, the people who
settled North America,'' she said. ``They walked so much more
gently upon the earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
