u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     07-17 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARDS MAY NOT BE PRESSURE-TREATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 19 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The pressure-treated floor boards of my deck are 11 years old
and are rotten. Can I turn them over to expose undecayed wood? But
how in the world can I pull them off? The nails seem very tight,
and I'm afraid I might pull their heads off.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN ELWOOD, Bourne, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Pressure-treated boards are not supposed to rot, and, in
fact, do not, if they are properly pressure-treated. I suggest the
boards are not pressure-treated. Besides, if the boards are rotting
at the top and/or sides, turning them over will do no good.
</P>
<P>
   So, tear them off and install properly pressure-treated boards
(a full inch thick). Pressure-treated boards are identified by a
blue, yellow, or red plastic label stapled to one end.
</P>
<P>
   But tearing them off might still be difficult. First, chedck to
see if the fasteners are screws. If so, use a reversible drill to
back them out. If they are nails, use an extra long pinch bar (30
or more inches long rather than the standard 24 inches. Chip out
decayed wood around the nail head so you can get the hook of the
bar under a nail head. Then pry steadily. The extra length will
give you more prying power. You could put a block of wood under the
fulcrum (where the curved part of the hook rests on the floor) to
give even more pulling power.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, tear off the floor boards, leaving the
nails exposed; if you can't pull them, cut them off with a hacksaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house sits on ledge, so the yard often presents problems,
with stone formations quite close to the surface of the property.
One of those problems is a small bowl in the ledge; it fills with
water and leaves, and I am always stepping in it. How can I fill it
to prevent that hazardous situation, which is hard on the ego as
well as the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, from Abington, mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It should not be a problem. Set a whiskey half-barrel over
the depression and fill it with impatiens or other colorful
annuals. Be sure to drill holes in the barrel bottom for drainage.
Save the shavings; they have a faint scent of whiskey. You could
use any kind of a container, and you could set it over a wood
table, too, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Or, fill depression with concrete. Stick a flag in it to locate
it. But a container full of annuals is more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. How does one stop squeaks in a floor under carpeting, without
pulling up the carpet?
</P>
<P>
   H.M.M., Moline, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is an old question, answered a million times, but since
H.M.M. left no return address in his/her note, the handyman is
obliged to answer in the column. He hopes H.M.M. sees it. The
squeaks occurred when the floor boards (both the top floor boards
and the subfloor boards, or plywood) dried out and shrank. With
this shrinkage, the nails lost their grip, and the two floors move
when walked on; the squeak is the sound of the wood scraping
against the nails. The cure is to make sure the floorboards do not
move. Sometimes in summer, the squeaks go away because the wood has
taken on moisture and expanded.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to fix the squeaks. If the floor is the main
floor of the house, and the underside of the floor is open in the
basement, drive shims (tapered shingles make good shims) between
the floor boards (or plywood) and joists (the beams holding up the
floor). This will bring the floors tightly against the joists and
each other, preventing movement.
</P>
<P>
   If the floor boards are not accessible from below, try this: The
Improvements Catalog sells what it calls Squeeeeek (yes, misspelled
with no fewer than five e's) No More, a kit containing an alignment
and depth-control tool and 50 three-inch screws. Set up the
alignment tool in the right spot (preferably over a joist) and
drive the screw with a power driver to the right depth, then break
off the screw, which is scored to allow easy breaking under the
floor surface. Fluff up the carpet and you're done. It's best to
drive the screws into a joist; if you can't find the joist, second
best is to drive through both floors. This system will work on
floors without carpeting, too; the holes left by the broken-off
screws are easy to fill with wood filler.
</P>
<P>
   To order Item 110189, call 800-642-2112.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a report from Barry Ehrlich of Mount Vernon, Vt., who
called recently to inquire about re-siding his barn, which he
planned to do with ship-lapped wood boards. The handyman suggested
using white cedar shingles instead, without treatment because no
treatment is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich responded, ``I put up white cedar shingles as you
suggested, and it is just great. I don't have to do anything to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Short, sweet, and appreciated, especially on a subject the
handyman feels so passionately about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I collect rain water from my roof. Can I use it for plants?
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY GIRNIUS, Roslindale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You betcha. It's a great way to handle the water bans that
are so common this summer, as in most summers. How about high acid
content, if the water is from acid rain? Not a problem, since your
plants are already thriving on regular rain, acid or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
