<HEADER>
A0079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WHATEVER-BOS &LR;      07-17 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WHATEVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDEARING TALE OF TEEN TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WHATEVER 
Directed and written by: Susan Skoog 
Starring: Lisa Weil, Chad Morgan, Frederic Forrest, Gary Wolf,
Kathryn Rossetter, Dan Montano, John G. Connolly 
Running time: 112 minutes 
Rated: R (pervasive teen drug and alcohol abuse, language including
sexual dialogue, sexuality and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director Susan Skoog not only gets all the notes right in
``Whatever.'' Her coming-of-age film gets all the grace notes
right, too. Skoog describes it as an emotional autobiography rather
than a factual account of her girlhood in New Jersey. High school
lies behind her. In the fall, her protagonist, Anna, hopes she's
headed to Cooper Union, Manhattan's prestigious, and free, art
school. Right now _ and although it's set in the 1980s, Skoog's
film very much exists in the emotional right now _ there is a
hellish summer to get through, and some unfinished business, like
putting behind her the vexing question of which boy she's going to
lose her virginity with.
</P>
<P>
   While the bedrooms of her contemporaries are festooned with
posters of rock stars, Anna's room is decorated with art posters,
especially Georgia O'Keeffe's. The distilled sexiness of O'Keeffe
is a quality Anna understands innately. She just hasn't taken it as
far as her role model, and it bothers her. She's more than a little
irritated by all the upbeat talk from her art teacher because it
reminds her how frightened she is of not living up to her own
expectations. Wrapped in a ratty sweater and carefully keeping the
corners of her mouth turned down so she won't seem too eager or too
vulnerable, Lisa Weil's Anna is one of the most endearing
about-to-break-out heroines of any film in years.
</P>
<P>
   If Anna steals petty cash from her mother to keep herself in
cigarettes, she's also touchingly compassionate toward her single
mom, too, sensing that she's got a lot of time to find what she
wants and her mother hasn't. Movingly, Skoog reverses the usual
generational warnings. When Anna's mom, played with just the right
touch of rumpled desperation by Kathryn Rossetter, starts trying
too hard to get something going with her married boss, it's Anna
who stays cool and lovingly warns her to cushion herself against
disappointment by not expecting too much. Anna is afraid, too. What
she's afraid of is being ordinary. With an exquisitely gauged sense
of balance, Skoog nudges Weil's Anna into rebellion more dutifully
than angrily, and with a backward glance at the safety net she's
leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Anna has chosen her best friend, Brenda (Chad Morgan),
partly for her potential as a rebellion mentor. But here, too,
Skoog takes the trouble to present Brenda as dimensioned,
feelingful, and not just eccentric. If there's a certain wildness
to the arc of her flight from her family, it's because her family
gives her a lot to flee. Anna and Brenda give the film all the
heart and stylistic contrast any film needs, but Skoog rounds it
out by casting her young-men-as-trouble with an eye to humor and
more than a little authenticity of feeling, too. And Wheeling,
W.Va., does a convincing job of standing in for Red Bank, N.J. In
its quiet way, ``Whatever'' deals with believable post-adolescent
turmoil, but never self-indulgently, and it never relinquishes its
claim on your attention or compassion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
