</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET CONDITIONS REQUIRE A WAIT-AND-SEE STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 19 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I presently have two 403(b) accounts. We each
have $17,000 in Fidelity Contrafund and $41,000 in Vanguard Index
500. Each of us adds $200 a month to the Vanguard account. Since
both funds we hold are growth funds and the word is to get ready
for a market correction, I know we are too heavily invested in
stocks, and that we should balance our funds to offset a possible
plunge or correction in the market. We are both teachers, and I can
retire in four years at age 54, and my wife in six years at age 53.
We realize we won't be able to touch these 403(b) accounts until
age 59 1/2. What do you suggest we do to help balance our funds to
get the best bang for our buck?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A.M. &LR; ,  &UR; Hurst, Texas  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since your time frame here is in the area of 10 to 12 years,
I don't suggest any drastic get-ready-for-the-crash approach. For
one thing, even though I think the market in general is currently
overvalued, neither I nor anybody else knows when, or how, this
might be corrected. Sometimes overpriced markets get back to
reality by simply moving sideways for a number of months until
earnings and dividends reach levels to justify the prices.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as in 1987, a dramatic decline is almost immediately
followed by a renewed bull market; the people who got spooked when
the crash came probably missed a good part of the bull market that
followed. In fact, there are studies that show that even if people
generally manage to call the market's trends, they usually end up
in a worse situation than the buy-and-hold types if they miss only
a few days at the beginning of a bull market.
</P>
<P>
   So I don't suggest drastic changes because of the state of the
market. But I do suggest a lot of changes because your portfolio is
pretty poorly diversified. Both Fidelity Contrafund and Vanguard
Index 500 hold portfolios of stocks that represent a blend of
growth- and value-oriented large-cap stocks. Both have done very
nicely for the past few years as these large-cap stocks have
represented the primary driving force behind the market. But it's
reasonable to expect that even if the market remains healthy, these
stocks are likely to take a breather. That's why a typical
retirement portfolio will include large positions in funds such as
the two which you hold -- both of which are frequently treated as
core holdings -- but also smaller positions in mid-cap, small-cap,
international, and perhaps even a couple of sector funds. A typical
breakdown for a fairly aggressive saver who's 10 years from drawing
on the money might put 40 percent in the core holding, 15 percent
each in mid- cap, small-cap and international holdings, and the
final 15 percent split among sector holdings such as health care
and technology. A more cautious person in the same position might
hold 30 percent in the core position, 15 percent in an
equity-income fund, 15 percent in a balanced fund, 15 percent in an
income-oriented fund such as a GNMA offering, with the final 25
percent divided among mid-cap, small-cap, and international funds.
I don't know what the menu of options available to you through your
403(b) accounts, but most plans offer investment options such
categories. So I suggest you decide whether you want to take a
conservative or more aggressive stance, and then diversify along
the lines I suggest above.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 56 years old and would like to retire at age 60 with an
income of $40,000 a year. At that point, my pension will be $30,000
a year. We have $10,000 in savings, $7,000 in common stock, a
$4,500 IRA, and a 401(k) plan of $182,000 of which 30 percent is in
an equity income fund, 30 percent in Fidelity Magellan, and 40
percent in Vanguard Index 500 fund. Contributions to that plan,
including my employer's match, come to $17,500 a year. I have a
$18,000 loan against the 401(k), which I am paying off at the rate
of $300 a month. I will have an additional $300 a month to invest
beginning in September. Can we achieve $40,000 annual income at
retirement? How should I invest the $300 a month for the next four
years? How should I handle the loan balance? Am I dividing my
401(k) investments correctly?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; K.M. &LR; ,  &UR; Philadelphia &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the easy part of the answer is that you should have no
problem coming up with the additional $10,000 a year to augment
your pension in retirement. If we presume 8 percent average annual
growth over the next four years, and if we presume continued
contributions at current levels, the pool would be $329,343 at
retirement -- more than twice what you'd need to generate that
$10,000 without invading the principal.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems to me that with retirement drawing closer, now is a
good time to reorganize the portfolio both so it will be in the
right configuration by the time you retire, and also to reduce
risk. Currently you have all of the 401(k) money in common stock.
Let's presume that you decide that upon retirement you'll want to
have half of the 401(k) month in fixed-income holdings and the rest
remaining in stocks -- designed to give you long-term capital
appreciation as a hedge against in inflation during the later years
of retirement. My suggestion would be to make the move now. You
don't spell out the options in the 401(k) plan, but almost all of
them have a fixed-income offering such as a GNMA fund, a government
bond fund, or a bond index fund. I suggest you change the current
allocation so 50 percent is in such a vehicle, and also direct that
half of the ongoing contributions go there as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $300 a month you will be able to add to your
investments in September, I suggest that you begin by adding that
amount to your 401(k) loan repayments, accelerating the process of
eliminating the loan. Once that's done, I would open a Roth IRA if
you are eligible to do so, and if not open a taxable account, again
invested in a fixed-income investment such as I spelled out above.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that this may seem to contradict the advice I gave to
A.M. above, but even though you both will retire in about four
years, he will be leaving his funds untouched for 9 1/2 years, and
his wife for 12 1/2 years -- thus making those long-term accounts.
In your case, you'll be relying on about half of your savings to
produce an income stream within four years -- so that portion
becomes short-term money, and thus it should be conservatively
invested. The remaining funds are appropriate for stocks, since you
probably won't be drawing on them for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you take my advice and put half of the 401(k) money into
a fixed-income fund. I would then suggest that, like A.M. above,
you look for a little more diversification.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably in the about the same situation, with your fund
portfolios concentrated among large-cap stocks; and a broader
diversification on the stock side of the portfolio would probably
serve you better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a previous column you said if the questioner is now in a
low tax bracket and will be in a low tax bracket upon retirement,
conversion to a Roth IRA would make no difference. If $50,000 were
converted to a Roth IRA and gained at the rate of 8 percent
annually, after 10 years it would be approximately 107,000, having
growth by $57,000. Isn't this a good reason for conversion to a
Roth, even assuming the tax rate remains the same?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; D.E., Dunstable, Mass. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sorry, but the numbers work out the same. I think you're
forgetting about the time value of the money that you would be
paying in taxes upon the Roth conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose the tax on the conversion of a $50,000 IRA for a
low tax bracket person came to a grand total of $10,000, payable in
four annual installments of $2,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose than instead of converting, the person simply put
that $2,500 a year into an investment earning the same 8 percent.
After the four payments and six further years of uninterrupted
growth, the account would amount to $19,305 -- trust me, precisely
the amount of taxes that would be due on withdrawals from a
traditional IRA (provided they were made on a schedule to keep the
taxpayer in the same low bracket). The only reasons that someone
who expects to be in the same tax bracket upon withdrawal as they
are upon conversion to a Roth is the additional flexibility allowed
for withdrawal from a Roth, and the prospect that the tax structure
might change for the worse in the intervening years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
