<HEADLINE>
BIG BUSINESS, BAD BLOOD AT THE MFA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes I worry that I underestimate our fair city. This
spring, I was startled to read that Europeans regard Boston's
Symphony Hall as the finest concert house in North America. And not
until a few days ago did I know that the Museum of Fine Arts's
retail operation _ you know, the people who hustle all that Monet
kitsch _ is one of the three largest museum retail outfits in the
country. Ringing up over $40 million in annual sales, MFA
Enterprises rivals better-known sales operations like the
Smithsonian and New York's Met in both volume and profitability.
</P>
<P>
   But Enterprises has seen troubles, too. In a little over four
years, four executives have run the business. Francois Poulet, whom
insiders credit with building Enterprises to its current stature,
was summarily fired in May 1994. In Poulet v. Museum of Fine Arts,
an age-discrimination and defamation suit filed last year, Poulet
claims that the chairman of the MFA board made disparaging
allusions to his age _ he was in his late 50s _ and that the museum
twice tried to replace him with younger, less experienced
executives. Furthermore, he says that the museum understated
Enterprises profits in 1994 to make him look bad, and then trashed
his performance in interviews with the Globe and Boston Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We contend that the suit has no merit,'' says John Stanley,
the MFA's deputy director for operations. Some people who worked
with Poulet say the suit is absurd, and that he lost control of the
business during his lengthy stewardship. The legal brouhaha has
proved extremely divisive. It casts an unflattering light on the
business staff, who accept low salaries in return for the
satisfaction of working at the MFA. Also, Poulet's wife, Anne,
remains at the MFA as a curator of European decorative arts and
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Poulet, his job has turned over rapidly. His successor,
Janet Emerson, is credited with putting the business on even keel.
After less than a year, she left to become chief executive of
Learningsmith. Museum staffer Frank Heath took over after her, but
he checked out late last year in a ``difference over the direction
of the business,'' according to Stanley. Last month, Dan Reardon,
formerly of Bass Shoes, took the reins.
</P>
<P>
   Reardon's looking at a terrific 1998, because _ ker-ching! _
here comes that old guy in the blue smock again. That's right; the
MFA is going back to the well, meaning the cash register, with
another vast, overhyped Monet show, this one called ``Monet in the
Twentieth Century.'' You know what they say in the art world _ How
do you spell money? &QC; 
M-O-N-E-T.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Curious thing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin is embroiled in a trademark dispute over one of
its most valuable properties, the children's book character Curious
George. Quite by accident, a Houghton legal scout noticed that a
New York-based punk rock band named Furious George had filed a
trademark request in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, there's unlikely to be much confusion between
the benign tales of the furry little monkey and the band's work,
which features such songs as ``Betty Crocker, Punk Rocker,'' and
``Gilligan.'' (Sample lyric: ``I wear a white hat/I wear a red
shirt/They all think I'm stupid/One day I'll kill them.'') However,
FG's albums, which are hard to find, bear the same squiggly logo
type and blaring yellow graphics of the famous books by Margret and
H.A. Rey. Houghton execs aren't the least bit bashful about beating
on the band. ``There's no First Amendment issue here,'' says
Houghton corporate counsel Lois Wasoff. ``They're trying to trade
commercially on a name, look, and character that we've been
investing in for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't reach the band. However, in a letter to the New York
Observer, ``Furious George'' Trapp denounced ``the (expletives)
over at Houghton Mifflin for ``(squelching) the voice of the
people.'' Tired of this subject? You ain't seen nothing yet.
Universal Studios plans to release a Curious George live action
film some time next year. Soundtrack by Furious George? I don't
think so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
