<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE PUSHES ITS NEW BROWSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Netscape says its latest Web browser software
extends a helping hand to Internet newcomers, but critics say its
new filtering features are another step towards commercializing the
World Wide Web's anarchic nature.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape's Communicator 4.5, which debuted Thursday, is labeled
as a fractional update of the Mountain View, Calif., company's
market leading 4.0 browser. But some of browser's new capabilities
are marking it as more than a simple upgrade. Bob Lisbonne,
Netscape's senior vice president of client products, has labeled
4.5 a ``fundamental sea change'' for the browser.
</P>
<P>
   Internet civil libertarian Stanton McCandlish says its another
step in the ``TV-ization'' of the Web. What sparks these polar
opposites are two new features: ``Internet keywords'' and ``What's
related,'' collectively dubbed ``smart browsing''
</P>
<P>
   The first feature, Internet keywords, is activated when a user
types plain words instead of a specific URL into Communicator 4.5's
address box. The browser will then automatically head over to a 1.5
million word database residing on Netscape's own computers. That
list then generates a link to a Web site picked by Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's related'' is a button that now sits next to the Web
address box. Press it and up pops a list of other relevant web
sites. Those links are created from a roster of 12 million web
addresses gathered by Excite, a popular internet search and
indexing site partnered with Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbonne says the new features help users _ especially Internet
rookies _ navigate the morass of data that is the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many new users are daunted by the sheer sea of information
that's available (on the Web),'' Lisbonne said. ``(These features)
are a fast forward on their learning curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisbonne said that eliminating the information overload
generated by ordinary Web searches makes Net surfing a ``richer
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The databases backing smart browsing work by choosing _ and
excluding _ Web sites. In other words, not all Web sites will be
available to a smart browsing user.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lisbonne, Netscape is giving smart browsing
database preference to trademarks and other corporate and
governmental sites, excluding parody or other ``inappropriate'' Web
pages that Lisbonne said ``take advantage'' of the typing errors of
a less-than-careful Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when a 4.5 user types ``White House'' into the
4.5's address block, they are sent directly to the official
presidential Web site (www.whitehouse.org). A miss hit while typing
in the White House URL in older browsers has landed more than a few
people onto a pornographic page (www.whitehouse.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an appropriate use of the feature,'' said Lisbonne. The
Netscape executive is quick to point out that users can still
access any Web site they choose by directly typing the URL into the
address bar.
</P>
<P>
   McCandlish says the features raise some concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to keep in mind that there are deals going on in
the background when they're letting someone else pick their Web
sites for them,'' says McCandlish, program director for Internet
civil liberties group Electronic Frontier Foundation. ``They need
to know that they're not getting a complete response when they do
one of these simple word look-ups. And they're getting sites picked
because of corporate deals, not because they're the best sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape is anticipating future disputes over the rights to the
ownership of the smart browsing keywords and placement on the
``what's related'' lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to make some decisions on how this is covered in
the future,'' said Lisbonne. ``We'll have to work with our partners
and try and do the right thing.'' Netscape closed at 33-and-1/4
Thursday, up 1-and-13/16~.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
