<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ZORRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANDERAS CUTS A SEXY SWATH IN ZORRO'S TRIUMPHAL RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MASK OF ZORRO 
Directed by: Martin Campbell 
Screenplay by: John Eskow, Ted Elliott &AMP;and Terry Rossio (based on
Johnston McCulley's character) 
Starring: Antonio Banderas, Anthony Hopkins, Catherine Zeta-Jones,
Stuart Wilson, Matt Letscher, Tony Amendola 
Running time: 136 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some intense action and violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zorro is back, with more swashbuckling panache than ever. ``The
Mask of Zorro'' proves that Antonio Banderas can hold his own with
the long, honorable line of Zorros that began with Douglas
Fairbanks Sr. in 1920 and included Tyrone Power. There were a lot
of ways ``The Mask of Zorro'' could have gone wrong and not many
ways it could ride into the '90s with dash and richness. For a
moment you wonder as Martin Campbell reminds us he directed
``GoldenEye'' in the way Zorro strides into the frame a la James
Bond over the opening credits. But this ``Zorro'' is more than a
throwback to the acrobatic compadre of Robin Hood and The Scarlet
Pimpernel; he's a revitalization of a romantic hero who had already
staked out the franchise concept when ``Jaws'' and ``Rocky'' were
barely a couple of gleams in Hollywood's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the film confines itself to one Zorro. One of the
things that gives it breadth and weight is Anthony Hopkins's
performance as the older Zorro. He imparts gravity and nobility to
the story as an aristocrat secretly championing the poor, about to
call it a career after the sensational rescue of a trio of peasants
and the recall to Spain of the cruel colonial governor, Don
Montero. But then he's unmasked and thrown into prison over the
dead body of his wife. His infant daughter is kidnapped by Don
Montero and raised as his own child.
</P>
<P>
   The prologue sets the stage for the entrance of the new Zorro,
20 years later, as Don Montero (Stuart Wilson) returns to Mexico,
plotting to buy California from Mexico's liberator, General Santa
Ana, with gold stolen from Mexico. Hopkins's Don Diego de la Vega,
escaped from prison, is about to assassinate him when he notices
that the beautiful young woman Montero helps from a carriage is his
own daughter, who is unaware of her true parentage. So he switches
to Plan B, plucking one of two grown orphan brothers from a
cantina, teaching him everything he knows, turning him into his
instrument of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The new Zorro, naturally, is Banderas, and his initial
clumsiness is engaging. It isn't long, however, until he gets his
act together and becomes an accomplished horseman, swordsman, whip
wielder, and romancer of Don Diego's daughter, the beautiful
Catherine Zeta-Jones, who at one point engages him in a sexy
swordfight. Just as Hopkins's old fox is spoiling for a fight with
Wilson's smooth villain, Banderas builds to a showdown with the
Don's cruel and kinky right-hand man, interestingly played by Matt
Letscher as a psychotic who killed the new Zorro's brother and
carries his head around in a bottle. Overall, though, the film's
avoidance of campy humor and its reliance on solid narrative and
viscerally appealing acrobatics as opposed to mere effects is so
novel in today's moviegoing climate that it seems almost
refreshingly innovative.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's direction is usefully class-conscious, generating
suspense when Banderas's hastily trained peasant must insinuate
himself into Don Montero's social circle. There's always a gap
between Hopkins's born aristocrat and Banderas's posed one. On the
other hand, Banderas is physically all one could hope for as Zorro,
convincingly lithe and athletic, and charismatically romantic to
boot. Zeta-Jones is no passive heroine, either, and her physical
abilities more than equal her good looks. Add to that Wilson's
avoidance of scenery-chewing as the villain and the new ``Zorro''
is a handsome and satisfying balancing act. Packed with gymnastics
and richly evocative Mexican locales, it's the most resplendently
exuberant and best-looking ``Zorro'' ever, as well as the sexiest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
