<SLUG> BC-TV-NYPD-BLUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHRODER'S FUTURE IS TRUE `BLUE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; PASADENA, &UR;  &LR; Calif. _ When ABC announced that Rick Schroder
would replace Jimmy Smits on ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' this season, fans of
the show heaved a collective ``Huh?'' Little Ricky Schroder, the
blond child TV star from ``Silver Spoons,'' as a tough-talking New
York detective? You might as well pair Dennis Franz's Detective
Andy Sipowicz with Danny Bonaduce.
</P>
<P>
   But when you see Schroder today, a 28-year-old man with a
tightly wound physical presence, the casting choice makes perfect
sense. Schroder has an unexpected rough-hewn energy and a New York
accent (he's from Staten Island) that will serve him well when he
joins the 15th Precinct this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco, who created and executive-produces the series
with David Milch, says the goal was never to replace Smits, whose
Bobby Simone will be written out of the show in the first six
episodes of the season. ``We've always had in the back of our minds
that we would like to add a younger character,'' he says. Bochco
and Milch approached a number of actors for the part, and had them
read with Franz. ``In the scene that Rick did that was written for
Simone,'' says Milch, ``he did it in an entirely different way, and
brought his own colors to the performance. That's a real pleasure
for a writer, when you see an actor beat the page or turn it''
upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The ``N.Y.P.D.'' creators are keeping what they know about
Schroder's character under wraps. The only detail they will divulge
is that he will be joining Sipowicz after a stint in the narcotics
department. And they say they are still developing the details of
the young detective, who doesn't even have a name yet. Recently,
Milch says, he ran excitedly into Bochco's office, saying, ``You
know who this guy is, you know what his name is? His name is Jack
Wayne. And you know why his name is Jack Wayne? Because his real
name is John Wayne, and when Sipowicz finds out he calls him
Duke!'' Sadly for Milch, but happily for viewers, Bochco met
Milch's revelation with silence.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Bochco and Milch needed to create a new character
for ``N.Y.P.D. Blue,'' of course, they didn't have the luxury of
time to flesh out the character carefully. By the time David Caruso
decided to leave the show after its first season, the pair had
already written five scripts including him for the second season.
``David and I, David primarily, really invented Jimmy's character
on the fly,'' says Bochco. ``It must have taken us the better part
of a full season before we began to really feel comfortable with
who this guy was and how he functioned in the unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco and Milch say that Kim Delaney, whose character is
married to Smits's, will remain on the show after Smits's
departure. ``She functions in the show independent of Jimmy,'' says
Milch. Bochco says he hopes that Sharon Lawrence, who plays
Sipowicz's wife, will make more regular appearances on ``N.Y.P.D.
Blue'' now that her own show, ``Fired Up,'' has been canceled. ``I
think she's going to be very much a part of what we're doing this
coming season.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the Smits-Schroder change-over bring creative renewal to
``N.Y.P.D. Blue''? Last season, the series' fifth, was seen by
critics and many fans as its least inspired. ``In the fifth year of
any show,'' says Bochco, ``you don't have gross revelations for
your strong drama and for your strong character stories.'' He says
the show has become ``more complicated, subtle, like close
harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Milch says he does hope that Schroder's presence will bring new
energy to the show, as the characters ``are going to be adjusting
to him in very interesting ways. ... Steven and I and the writing
staff, and our actors, and, in particular, Dennis, have always
tried to embrace change and see its new possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder, who lives on a Colorado ranch with his wife and three
children, says he's never been much of an ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' viewer.
``I don't have the discipline to sit down every day at a certain
time to watch TV. ... When I do watch TV, it's usually A&AMP;E or the
Discovery Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   His family life away from the TV industry is what has protected
him from the potentially harmful effects of child stardom, he says.
``Third grade was my last grade of formal education,'' he adds. ``I
don't know why I succeeded, but I have a pretty tenacious attitude
... that works to my advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he really dislike being called ``Ricky,'' as the press has
reported over the years? ``It doesn't bother me at all,'' he says.
``My mother and my wife call me Ricky.'' Years ago, he says, his
agent suggested the change to ``create a new persona'' for him. ``I
think about it for two seconds and I say, `OK.' And then some
people ... started making fun of it. So I got really torqued one
day, being made fun of over it ... and it created this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's joining ``N.Y.P.D. Blue,'' of course, he'll need
to share not only his heart and his soul but his butt with viewers,
in keeping with the show's trademark nudity. ``My wife says I've
got a great one,'' he says confidently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
