<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BROADWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY LOVE IS BLAND IN `BROADWAY DAMAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BROADWAY DAMAGE 
Written and directed by: Victor Mignatti 
Starring: Mara Hobel, Michael Shawn Lucas, Hugh Panaro, Aaron
Williams 
Running time: 110 minutes 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Broadway Damage'' is a lot like its main characters _ pleasant
and inoffensive, with not a lasting thought in its pretty little
head.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Mignatti's fanciful film is a New York fairy tale
disguised as a romantic comedy. How else to explain the fact that
Marc (Michael Shawn Lucas) and his best galpal Cynthia (Mara Hobel)
manage to find a two-bedroom apartment in Greenwich Village for
under $2,000 a month, let alone under $1,000? Even if you have sex
with the building's superintendent, which Marc does, you
ain't &UR;  &LR; getting a Village apartment with running water, functioning
appliances, and a private bathroom for anything things less than
$10,000 under the table, and perhaps your firstborn.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Broadway Damage'' isn't as interested in reality as in the
telling of this blandly sweet gay romance.
</P>
<P>
   Marc is an aspiring actor, who can't seem to land any work
because casting directors find him to soft (read: too gay). His
nebbishy best friend Robert (Aaron Williams) is also an actor and a
musician who has a major love jones for Marc. But he believes the
hunky blond is simply out of his romantic league. Robert isn't
nearly as much of a goober as he thinks he is, but he needs to lose
the glasses, Garanimals clothing, and shaggy bangs.
</P>
<P>
   But what chance does Robert stand with a guy magnet like Marc,
who attracts the amorous attention of his musician neighbor David
(Hugh Panaro). If David seems too good to be true, of course, he
is. But the film never betrays its good, boring heart or its
inevitable happy ending. The untrustworthy David is never more than
an attractive nuisance; one look at Robert's lovelorn eyes in
Marc's presence, and you know exactly who will end up with whom.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cynthia is a Long Island rich kid determined to make
her way without Daddy's money, although she spends what little she
has at Bloomingdale's and any other store still willing to accept
her overworked credit cards. To his credit, Mignatti allows Hobel's
Cynthia to be more than Marc's zaftig het friend. She actually gets
a love scene with a marriage-minded boyfriend, and there's a
running gag about her increasingly desperate attempts to reach Tina
Brown, then editor of The New Yorker, for a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadway Damage'' is terrible. We've seen all this before, and
it's usually been better. Disappointingly, what Mignatti ends up
with is a genteel gay comedy when he needed a few more sharp
elbows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
