<HEADLINE>
MASS. LAW WOULD LIMIT SUITS AGAINST HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER   AND ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Senator Edward Kennedy, President Clinton,
and other Democrats push for a new right for patients to sue
health-maintenance organizations, a state law may block
Massachusetts residents from taking full advantage of any new
federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The state's four largest HMOs are structured as
charitable organizations. Under state law, damages for negligence
and injury against charities are capped at $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Congress makes it easier for patients to sue health
insurers, ``at first blush, our view is that the cap would still
apply to HMOs,'' said Barbara Anthony, chief of the Massachusetts
attorney general's public protection bureau. ``But we have not
thoroughly researched this issue, and we have not litigated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law leaves little room for most Americans to sue
insurers who refuse to pay for medical care, even if the result is
a cancer that spreads, a depression that deepens, or other harm.
Democrats say that if patients had more rights to sue HMOs,
insurers would no longer have a financial incentive to protect
their profits by denying patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have made the right to sue a centerpiece of their
broad HMO legislation, which would also give patients more rights
to see specialists and visit an emergency room, and require HMOs to
have a formal process for appealing decisions concerning care. The
two major Republican plans include some of the provisions favored
by Democrats, but most Republicans oppose an expanded right to sue.
Instead, they say, a stronger appeals process would protect
patients without resorting to costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The limitations on lawsuits are in a 1974 law, and they apply to
the estimated 125 million Americans whose health plans are
sponsored by their employers. The law says that a patient may sue
for the cost of a doctor visit, test or other service denied by an
insurer, but not for any harm that might have been caused by the
denial of medical care.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress expands the right to sue, it is unclear what effect
the expansion would have on the four largest HMOs in Massachusetts:
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Massachusetts, Tufts Health Plan, and Fallon Community Health Plan.
Several factors could come into play:
</P>
<P>
   _How the law is changed. Democrats are seeking to remove the
hurdle in federal law that limits lawsuits, leaving states to set
their own rules on HMO suits. That strategy would leave in place
the $20,000 cap on claims against charities, said Myra J. Green, a
lawyer at Choate Hall &AMP; Stewart in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But if Congress creates a new right to sue, which is less
likely, federal law may preempt the cap on damages, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   _The types of cases that patients pursue. Even if the cap
limited damages for an HMO's alleged negligence in denying
coverage, patients might be able to win larger damage awards by
suing under different legal theories such as breach of contract,
said Laurie Martinelli, a lawyer with Health Law Advocates in
Boston. However, other lawyers say that strategy may not succeed in
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   _Whether state courts continue to view HMOs as charities.
Anthony of the attorney general's office said that the Supreme
Judicial Court has never ``definitively'' decided that HMOs are
charities for the purposes of the state cap on damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   At Blue Cross, spokeswoman Susan Leahy said that the company's
charitable status was written into the state legislation that
helped create the company. At Harvard Pilgrim, spokesman Alan
Raymond said the company's charitable immunity was challenged only
once, in a 1981 tax case, ``and our charitable status was upheld in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen J. Lyons, a lawyer with the Boston firm Klieman &AMP;
Lyons, said an HMO may be sued for more than $20,000 if the damages
arise from actions that are not part of a charitable mission. He
said the Supreme Judicial Court had ruled, in a case not involving
an HMO, that an activity is not charitable if it is intended to
raise revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
