<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE THOROGOOD KICKS BACK INTO GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conversing with George Thorogood is like riding a runaway
stagecoach. Be prepared for some wild one-liners. ``Rock 'n' roll
never sleeps. It just passes out,'' Thorogood says with a laugh
from Los Angeles. Then this admission: ``People used to say I was a
maverick and that I did things my own way. Hey, if I knew the way,
I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yup, George is back, in all his wise-cracking glory. He never
pretended to have all of the answers, but he's sure got a few of
them. ``I didn't write the book, but I read it,'' he says of his
basic love of showmanship. ``I just do it the way it's supposed to
be done _ the same way that (Bob) Seger, the Stones, and the Geils
Band have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   That way is to go all-out in concert _ something that Thorogood
has done for years as leader of the Destroyers, formerly the
Delaware Destroyers. The bill also features Bo Diddley, Kelly
Willis, Nils Lofgren, Steve Morse (no relation to this writer),
James Cotton, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Thorogood is back in business after several years in which he's
switched managers, switched record labels (look for him to pop up
with an album on BMG next year), and welcomed the arrival of a
daughter, who's only a few months old.
</P>
<P>
   He still performed, but not as often as his barnstorming days.
``I've been keeping my hand in and doing a little spot-pouring, you
might say,'' he notes of his recent low profile, which has come
after years of vigorously hitting the road with a repertory heavily
steeped in Thorogood-ized covers of songs by Chuck Berry, John Lee
Hooker, Bo Diddley, Johnny Cash, Hank Williams, and other roots
luminaries, along with some witty, boys-night-out original songs
such as ``Bad to the Bone,'' a big hit on MTV during the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Thorogood, a former semi-pro baseball player who used to book
concerts around his baseball schedule, has never quite fit in,
wherever he's been. ``Hey, you wouldn't be in rock 'n' roll if you
were a popular guy in high school,'' he says from personal
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In his one overt plug for the Gibson Guitar Festival, he says,
``If it weren't for the Gibson company, I wouldn't be talking to
you now. I can't play any other guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorogood, who hails from Wilmington, Del., used to play the New
England area frequently when he recorded for Rounder Records in
Cambridge, Mass. in the late '70s, before moving on to a major
label. He used to call his shows ``rock 'n' roll hootenannies.''
Talking about those shows, he says, ``I used to play `One Bourbon,
One Scotch, One Beer' for 40 minutes. You guys thought I had great
energy, but I just didn't have any more songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorogood's Destroyers were originally a trio with bassist Billy
Blough and drummer Jeff Simon, but they added saxophonist Hank
Carter in the '80s. ``He's our Clarence Clemons,'' Thorogood says,
referring to Bruce Springsteen's sax man.
</P>
<P>
   When last seen in this area four years ago, Thorogood &AMP; Co. were
co-billed with Little Feat at Great Woods. They toured with ZZ Top
for three weeks last summer, but were not on the Great Woods show,
even though their name was advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do three more weeks with ZZ Top, but we never got
a confirmation,'' he says. ``But promoters went ahead and printed
it up as if we were going to do it. Sometimes promoters are
overeager.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Thorogood, who did a legendary tour with the
Stones and Geils Band in the early '80s, wanted to do some dates
with John Fogerty, but those didn't happen. ``I've always been a
fan of packaging. The fans get more wallop that way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   You can expect that wallop in Newport next weekend. It's a
great-sounding package _ and you know Thorogood &AMP; Co. will be there
to take care of business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Folk in the hills:  &LR; Two of the summer's biggest acoustic
festivals are coming up. The Winterhawk Bluegrass Festival runs
Friday (July 17) through Sunday at the Rothvoss Farm over the Mass.
border in Ancramdale, N.Y. Artists include Sam Bush, Ralph Stanley,
Bela Fleck &AMP; the Flecktones, Peter Rowan, Laurie Lewis, Del
McCoury, Tony Rice, and many more. For info: 1-888-946-8495. The
Falcon Ridge Folk Festival is next weeknd at Long Hill Farm in
Hillsdale, N.Y. Performers include Bill Morrissey, Dar Williams,
Laura Love, Patty Larkin, Vance Gilbert, John Gorka, Greg Brown,
and the Nields. More info: 860-350-7472.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Zombie in the news:  &LR; Rob Zombie, the Boston weaned, hard-rockin'
leader of the group White Zombie, had his music used as a
brain-frying tool to ward off paparazzi at Barbra Streisand's
recent wedding. Streisand reps blasted Zombie's 1992 tune ``Thunder
Kiss '65'' from a black van parked close to where the paparazzi
gathered outside Streisand's Malibu villa. The song was played at
full volume for four hours. One photographer called it
``psychological warfare,'' but another said, ``At least it's not
Streisand music.'' Zombie has a new album, ``HellbillyDeluxe,'' due
out Aug. 25. Wonder if the Streisand reps will dig that one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
