<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SOUL-BOS &LR;      07-17 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SOUL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVING THE SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The golden age of soul music is back. Reviving the tradition of
the barnstorming bus tours of the '50s and '60s are eight pioneers
who have formed the ``Royal Soul Revue.'' Such artists as Lloyd
Price, Percy Sledge, Irma Thomas, Ben E. King, and Jerry Butler may
not strike an immediate chord with a new generation, but they are
pioneers who influenced Stevie Wonder, Van Morrison, Whitney
Houston, Mick Jagger, and other acts way too numerous to mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the ladies and gentlemen who defined soul music.
They are the originators,'' says Peter Wolf, the former J. Geils
Band singer. ``This is a real opportunity for anyone interested in
American music. I'm just going to be a gushing fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the gushing begin, because this is a package tour of
historic proportions. You'll hear two of the all-time soul ballads
in Sledge's ``When a Man Loves a Woman'' (revived a few years ago
in a Grammy-winning version by Michael Bolton) and Butler's ``For
Your Precious Love.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll hear artists who are still vital after two, three, and
four decades on the circuit, including Gene Chandler (``Duke of
Earl''), Chuck Jackson (former lead singer of the Del Vikings), and
Ben E. King (``Spanish Harlem,'' ``Stand by Me'').
</P>
<P>
   They promise a fast-paced revue evoking the heyday of New York's
Apollo Theater _ a time when Motown, Stax, and Atlantic Rec-ords
churned out soul hits with an amazing consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is excited about this tour. There's a good feeling
among the performers _ most of us have known each other for years.
And we think that the baby boomers who bought this music are the
ones who need it now to reconnect with their youth, just like the
people before us had Sinatra and Satchmo,'' says Lloyd Price, a New
Orleans star who re-corded the raucous ``Lawdy Miss Clawdy'' in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   Price, now a youthful 64, wrote the song after listening to New
Orleans disc jockey ``Okey Dokey'' Smith recite this commercial for
Maxwell House coffee: ``Lawdy Miss Clawdy, eat them mother homemade
pies and drink that Maxwell House coffee.'' The song featured Fats
Dom-ino on piano and was later re-corded by everyone from Elvis
Presley to Little Richard. Price used to sing it at interracial
dances in armories, tobacco warehouses, and other alternative sites
down South.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many white kids that the black kids couldn't get
in,'' he recalls of some shows. ``But by 10 o'clock, everyone was
dancing together. That was revolutionary at the time and the
Dixiecrats couldn't stand it. Then I was drafted (into the Army)
and the draft board told me they couldn't figure out what I was
doing with this `Lawdy Miss Clawdy' business and that's why I was
drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Price went on to make the seminal hits ``Just Because'' (which
John Lennon and Fleetwood Mac later recorded), ``Stagger Lee,'' and
``Personality,'' while forming his own rec-ord company (LL
Records), which put out the first hits by Wilson Pickett. Price was
also a bowling partner of Motown founder Berry Gordy and personal
friend of boxing champ Muhammad Ali. Along the way, he also managed
to own three clubs, two liquor stores, and live in Africa 10 years.
Currently, he coordinates affordable housing for the needy in New
York. To say he's lived a full life is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   The glory days of soul music saw a different performance ethic,
one that comes out in the current tour. Artists will sing three to
five songs each, coming out in succession and backed by the same
band _ an all-star unit directed by G.E. Smith (former ``Saturday
Night Live'' guitarist) and boasting the Uptown Horns, who have
toured with the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have a lot of downtime in a show like this. There is
never more than three minutes between acts,'' says Butler, who once
sang with the Impressions, where he shared the stage with the great
Curtis Mayfield. ``I think a lot now is lost in terms of
performance. People have to reset the stage and redo the lighting
between sets. So much is spent on technology, but the flow gets
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler now lives in Chicago and is commissioner of Cook County,
overseeing ``the paying of bills and raising of taxes,'' he says.
But he's committed to keeping the soul music era alive and is
writing a book called ``Only the Strong Survive,'' which will tell
of concert bus tours run by the agencies Supersonic Attractions and
General Artists Corporation. He recalls tours with the likes of
Chuck Jackson, Clyde McPhatter, Dion, the Shirelles, Ruth Brown,
and Illinois Jacquet.
</P>
<P>
   Butler says he remembers the first R&AMP;B song that used a string
section (the Drifters' ``There Goes My Baby'') and why the music of
the '50s and '60s was so groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music of America has always been a composite,'' he says.
``You had the European influence that turned into folk and country.
You had the black experience that turned into folk, blues, and
gospel. And layered on top was the music of Tin Pan Alley,
Broadway, and avant-garde jazz. All of this music was rolling
around in a fishbowl called America _ and all of us were stealing
from each other. You also had the civil rights era affecting it.
You had the Peter, Paul &AMP; Marys and the Josh Whites affecting it.
And you had Mongo Santamaria's `Hey Watermelon Man,' which was
really a Cuban blues, affecting it. There was never a period where
so much was going on musically.''
</P>
<P>
   Soul music, of course, borrowed from all of these _ and from the
church, where Percy Sledge got his start in tiny Leighton, Ala.,
about six miles from the famed Muscle Shoals studio where Aretha
Franklin recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say I sing like my mother,'' notes Sledge.
``We went to the Galilee Baptist Church in Leighton, a town that
had but one red light.''
</P>
<P>
   Sledge, 57, has made a career out of ``When a Man Loves a
Woman,'' a wailing, open-throated tune that he originally titled
``Why Did You Leave Me Baby.'' A disc jockey by the name of Quint
Ivy (from Sheffield, Ala.) heard Sledge sing it at a party. ``He
liked the feeling of it, but not the lyrics,'' says Sledge. ``The
lyrics didn't even rhyme. So I changed them and I put in a crying
feeling, as if everybody had left me. I just put a lot of feeling
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sledge sings it everywhere he goes _ from casinos in
Mississippi and Louisiana, to showcase theaters in Europe. ``You
can't give a show without giving your all,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sentiment of most of the Royal Soul Revue acts. They
know this is a ``pilot tour'' (it's been assembled by
Delsener/Slater Enterprises in New York), but they're hoping to
have more such tours in the future to spread the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting our end ready,'' says Wolf. ``We're looking to
have a soul house party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
