<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LEGISLATORS CALL FOR INVESTIGATION IN HIGH GAS PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California legislators Thursday asked the
state's attorney general to launch an investigation into why Bay
Area gas prices are 15 to 30 cents higher per gallon than prices in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-25 vote, the California Assembly passed a bill that
called for Attorney General Dan Lungren to look into the reasons
for the regional price differences to determine whether oil
companies and refiners are operating fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has the highest gas prices in the nation,'' said
state Assemblyman Michael Sweeney, who sponsored the bill. ``And
the Bay Area has the highest gas prices in California. ... With
refineries located in our own back yard, it is difficult to
understand why our gas prices are so high compared with Los Angeles
and other parts of the state or nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles motorists pay about $1.02 per gallon, or 9 cents per
gallon less than the national average of $1.11, according to
California State Automobile Association figures. By contrast, Bay
Area gas prices range from $1.17 to $1.32 per gallon on average.
</P>
<P>
   The state's effort comes a month after San Francisco-based
Chevron Corp., the largest gasoline seller in the state, defeated
an ordinance in San Francisco that would have restricted its
control over franchisees.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance, authored by Supervisor Michael Yaki, would have
forced oil refiners like Chevron to get out of owning gas stations
and allow franchise operators to shop around for the lowest
wholesale prices.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, franchise owners, who contract to sell major oil
company gasoline, can purchase gas only from the refiner.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many franchise owners have complained they can't
compete on price against company-owned gas stations, which can buy
gas more cheaply from refiners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's collusion. Simple,'' said Evelyn Poquez, who owns a BP
gas station franchise on Market Street. ``We are being used as a
tool to gouge customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But major oil refiners said market forces have kept gas prices
higher in the Bay Area. The Western States Petroleum Association, a
trade group representing major oil companies, said the Bay Area's
high land prices, rising gas taxes and lengthy permit processes
elevate prices at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron spokeswoman Alison Jones said the company will cooperate
with the investigation but added that previous attempts to find
wrongdoing in gas pricing came up short.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a number of these investigations into gas
pricing in California,'' she said. ``They have consistently found
that the marketplace sets gasoline prices. This will reach the same
conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill asked Lungren to submit his findings by December.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Federal Trade Commission launched its own
investigation into the differences in gas pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Yaki said the passage of the assembly bill is ``a
recognition that more and more people are beginning to understand
the gas market is being manipulated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
