<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-HUEY-BOS &LR;      07-17 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-HUEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD, HUEY AND THE 'HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A real dialogue happened the other afternoon at the
Strand Theatre. Huey P. Newton stood up and shook the hand of
Julius Caesar, who had just been released from lockup.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? There is a logical explanation. It was one of those
rare moments when art and life intersect, when a simple handshake
signifies more than a thousand academic treatises.
</P>
<P>
   What happened is this. Actor Roger Guenveur Smith is in Boston
to act in ``A Huey P. Newton Story,'' his award-winning performance
piece about the late cofounder of the Black Panther Party. He
stopped by the Dorchester theater to do a meet-and-greet with the
young actors in a summer program called New Land/Scapes. Smith,
best known for his work in the films of Spike Lee, told the young
actors that theater is sacred, it's spiritual. ``I think it's
church,'' he said. ``It's where we do the undoable.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to convince the young actors. They know about
theater that comes from the guts; they know about the
bloodcurdling, spine-straightening drama otherwise known as real
life. For eight years, local youths have been participating in the
summer program, which is run by a visionary named Brent Blair. It
operates on a shoestring budget, and Blair usually shells out his
own money to buy dinner for the young actors. Many of the
participants hold part-time jobs and support small children at
home; others have been in and out of juvenile detention centers. In
fact, the actor playing the title role in this summer's production
of ``Julius Caesar'' was just released from lockup; he arrives at
the end of the chat session with Smith and goes up to shake the
professional actor's hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's a moment to remember. Smith, who is not usually given to
reticence, is momentarily stunned after he clasps the hand of Jason
DePina.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' he begins, after a long silence. ``I have
just been introduced to Julius Caesar who has just been released
from lock-down,'' Smith says. ``You ask what art and civic
discourse is all about, and it's about that. It's about this
moment, about this young man emerging to play the Bard.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, you see, is performing in Boston under the auspices of
the Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, an ambitious project
that has brought scholars and artists together at Harvard
University for six weeks to explore the issues of our time. The
institute _ which is funded by the Ford Foundation and jointly
sponsored by Harvard's W.E.B. Du Bois Institute and the American
Repertory Theatre _ is presenting ``A Huey P. Newton Story'' as a
free performance. Smith has performed the piece all over the
country, and he says he likes to meet with young people in the
communities he visits because it provides ``a way of bringing down
that wall that traditionally divides audiences and performers.''
</P>
<P>
   There is barely a hint of a barrier between Smith and the young
adults as he sits with them in the auditorium, where a colorful
mural on the downstage wall depicts images of ``Hip Hop Boston.''
In the softest of voices, Smith tells the actors he grew up in what
he calls ``Hollywatts,'' with feet in two drastically diverse
cultures and mythologies. He recalls how he was one of hundreds of
actors auditioning for Spike Lee when he landed a role in ``School
Daze,'' how he created the stuttering character he played in ``Do
the Right Thing.'' He fields the usual kids-meet-actor questions:
How did you get your first break? What advice do you have?
</P>
<P>
   He talks about his upcoming role in Lee's ``Summer of Sam,'' the
controversial film about serial killer David Berkowitz. He touches
on his portrayal of Newton: ``It's very simple. Just one man, one
chair, and about 20 cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance, which won two Obie Awards and two Drama Desk
nominations, is hardly that simple. Smith gained exclusive access
to the archives of Newton's estate, and he spent months researching
the conflicted life of the legendary Black Panther. Before he began
his studies, he had the same image most folks had of Newton: the
image from the poster showing a man in a wicker chair, spear in one
hand, gun in the other, black beret perched on his head. By the
time he got together with composer and collaborator Marc Anthony
Thompson, Smith had a more complex picture of his subject, a man
dueling with his private demons and the baggage of his public
persona.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Smith worked together to forge a piece that
deliberately steers clear of the traditional biodrama a la Clarence
Darrow or Emily Dickinson. Instead, they came up with a staged jazz
improvisation, where the music and the words segue in a sort of
dramatic riff. At the very beginning, they just got together and
went through all the archival material, talking and searching for
the right way to present Newton, who was murdered on the street in
1989. In a week, they patched the script together and came up with
the music. But on the eve of their first public performance in San
Francisco, they panicked. Newton's widow and several family members
were coming to the performance, and it wasn't ready. So the two
collaborators went out and talked, with Thompson asking the
questions and Smith answering in character as Newton. It clicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece was never written _ it was absorbed and
regurgitated,'' Smith recalls. ``Marc Anthony just sat and asked me
questions: `What do you think of Shakespeare? What do you think of
Bob Dylan?' The result was this organic but historically informed
piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says his music strives to evoke a mood. ``It had to
sound like a very slow burn, a controlled muscle that was just
about to break, a long, slow process as opposed to a snap,'' the
composer explains during a telephone interview from New York. ``We
wanted this cauldron of emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   A long, slow burn. It happens onstage when Smith and Thompson
perform, but it also happens in its own way at the Strand Theatre
when the actor meets with the young performers. The connection is
genuine as the young actors testify about the cruel intersection of
dreams and reality, about how they want to build careers as artists
but need to find a way to pay their bills, feed their babies.
Throughout the session, Blair, the New Land/Scapes director, does a
slow burn, and then he snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard is having this big conference about art and social
discourse,'' he says, ``and most of those people have never touched
a toe in this community. They want social discourse? They want a
dialogue? Tell 'em to come down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair is echoing the common perception among many grass-roots
arts administrators who get their hands dirty every day, living and
breathing the kinds of issues the Harvard institute was founded to
study within the confines of the ivory tower. The institute
received a $1.5 million seed grant from the Ford Foundation and has
raised more funds from the Boston Foundation and other private
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a gulf between academia, black and white,
and the community in Boston,'' says Strand staffer Joyce Bishop.
``If they really want a dialogue, if they really want young people
to be a part of it, they have to be involved from the very
beginning and not just as an afterthought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop and Blair are hitting on precisely the issues the
institute was founded to examine. It was initiated as a result of
the work of its director, Anna Deavere Smith, whose plays ``Fires
in the Mirror'' and ``Twilight: Los Angeles'' explore issues that
divide various communities. The program, which was announced in
November but held its first meeting 10 days ago, has been funded
for three six-week summer sessions. Deputy director Andrea L.
Taylor says the institute is designed to be both a place where
artists can incubate new ideas about art and society as well as a
springboard to take those ideas into the community. ``We are very
open, very anxious, and very eager to learn from and engage with
the greater Boston community,'' Taylor says. ``Obviously, that kind
of work takes time. We are beginning. We're grateful (for) the
response we've received, and we know we have a lot more to do.''
The institute is holding several public forums over the next few
weeks; a program held this week attracted an overflow crowd and had
to be moved to a larger venue.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Smith (no relation to Anna Deavere Smith) listens to the
administrators at the Strand and empa-thizes, although he also says
he admires the institute's attempt to mix things up, to move beyond
the traditional models prescribed in the art world. At the same
time, he raises yet another issue that might be discussed at the
institute, which gathers about 50 artists and scholars every night
to bang heads about art and social discourse. ``I'm at Harvard, but
I'm at the Dorchester extension. Simply because I happen to be
doing a solo performance about someone who happens to be
African-American who happened to cofound a political party, I find
myself being relegated to the ghetto of sociopolitical theater or
the historical pageant.'' He's speaking softly, his voice barely
audible above the clamor of young folks rehearsing in the
high-ceilinged halls of the Strand. At this precise point, the
actor playing Jul-ius Caesar appears, and that handshake happens.
Art and civic discourse? ``It's about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TRICKY-BOS &LR;      07-17 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TRICKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICKY ON HIS OWN TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here was the scene at Tricky's two-hour-plus concert
at &UR;  &LR; Boston's Avalon last year: He stood, virtually immobile, in
near darkness, rapping as his mates played. It was jam time with a
lot of downtime _ languid, ambient grooves, cut with deep bass
lines, spiked sporadically with disorienting, mind-scrambling
sounds, both sampled and live. There were no big flashy pop hooks.
It was tense, claustrophobic. You got the sense Tricky was
burrowing deeper and deeper into a dark world. He was not singing
about peace and love. He glimpsed the future and it was both
insular and apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   Says Tricky, on the phone from his New York home, of his
performance style: ``We're not gonna go and shake our (butts) ...
for you. You've got to give something as well.'' He recently told
Musician magazine something similar, adding, ``I'm no one's dancing
monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what artists have become,'' says the British trip-hop
artist. ``All these hip-hop artists and R&AMP;B artists and all these
Alanis Morissettes _ they're really like performing monkeys.
Rec-ord companies have reduced artists to dancing minstrels.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hip-hop artists ``say my music is weird,'' he adds. ``(I
think) it's harder than any of their music. If you want to hear
hardcore music, I've got some hardcore for you. Hardcore is
confused with gangs and guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Tricky addresses these issues in song as well on his latest CD,
his third, ``Angels With Dirty Faces.'' On the melancholic
``Demise,'' Tricky rap-sings, ``I'm too scared to be a gun-toting
gangsta wan-na-be.''
</P>
<P>
   `You can get killed in that world,'' he explains in his raspy
staccato voice and a British accent.
</P>
<P>
   For the cut ``Rec-ord Companies,'' he has the late Biggie Smalls
and Tupac Shakur shaking hands in heaven while the violent
rap-warrior games go on below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm, like, trying to open people's brains a bit,'' he says.  &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tricky, 29, wants to succeed on his own terms. He admits that
his music is not, on the surface, commercially accessible: ``But I
think it will be one day, (although) that would be purely
accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   One of trip-hop's originators, Tricky is famous in his native
country, England _ ``top of the heap,'' as he says,
matter-of-factly. Tricky once worked with the guys who went on to
form Massive Attack. Three years ago, he emerged alongside that
band and Portishead as trip-hop entered the fringes of the
mainstream. His debut, ``Maxinquaye,'' was a worldwide smash,
selling more than 500,000 copies. It was a moody, mostly mellow
affair. Some mistook it to be sophisticated cocktail music, much to
Tricky's chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   He took it upon himself to push the envelope more since he's not
exactly a fan of most pop or hip-hop. ``Taking somebody's piece of
music and putting some crap lyrics on it with a chorus,'' he says,
dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked with artists ranging from Bjork to Bush to Elvis
Costello to PJ Harvey, who joins Tricky on the soulful ``Broken
Homes,'' the upcoming single. Tricky, whose real name is Adrian
Thaws, often works in tandem with soulful vocalist Martina
Topley-Bird, the mother of their young child. (The two are no
longer romantically involved.) She sings, he says, what he cannot.
Not only is he not a singer, he says, ``I'm not a musician.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement is not meant as an inverse-credibility boast or a
self-dis. He'll pen the lyrics, hum a bass line or a string part to
musicians, and work with it on his synth. ``Even if I don't use it,
it'll be the basis to write the song,'' Tricky says.
</P>
<P>
   He has no compunction about bluntly evaluating his status in the
States, where he's lived for three years. ``Here, I'm not at all
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   That's partially why he crossed the Atlantic, to work the turf.
``I got to work; I want different things now; I want to be in the
American charts. It doesn't come easy. There's more to aim for here
and I could do more damage, especially in places like hip-hop and
pop music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He tells us the new album is his first to chart in this country,
but his debut, ``Maxinquaye,'' charted as well. The new one has
reached a high point, so far, of 84.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky left the quietude of ``Maxinquaye'' behind with his
second disc, the much edgier ``Pre-Millennium Tension.'' ``Angels
With Dirty Faces'' is less agitated, but there is a familiar
entrancing soundscape: one that ebbs and flows, but is cut with
fractured jungle beats. Tricky touches base with gospel, blues, and
jazz, but he likes the idea of surprise, of disorientation. The
studio is his palette. The album has received mostly raves from
critics, though Tricky notes that it takes time to absorb and ``a
couple of press people in England'' have slammed it. You've got to
listen to it. It's not a halfway thing where people can lock right
into it. This is very personal. It's like I'm trying to talk to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   What's he saying?
</P>
<P>
   He's talking about power and its corrupting influence, about
avaricious media, about the once-popular and now-dead, about the
violence that's in the air. He's got a sweet song about his
daughter, ``Carriage for Two,'' but, mostly, his visions are dark.
He'll agree that paranoia is part of the mix. ``The energy I
receive, I give back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tricky, who is far from morose, says he is not a worrier. ``No,
no, no, not at all,'' he says. The world of conflict he writes
about, he says, is often drawn from the images on TV, the news, and
movies, where humans usually have no more value than ants.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky likes the music he's done, but it is, well, done. He'd
rather discuss what lies ahead, today. ``We've just done some new
music and it's less tense, less claustrophobic,'' Tricky says. ``I
had a bit of a time not knowing where I'm going, what I want to do,
but I know what I need now. I'm more chilled to myself, more
relaxed. I think I've developed a conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   He's just completed one track, ``Bleeding.'' Sounds like a sunny
romp through a field of flowers, right? ``It sounds dark,'' he
admits, with a laugh, ``but it's really positive, the most positive
thing I've ever written. People could sing along to it. It's crazy,
yeah, almost like Oasis. I'm not even an Oasis fan, but it reminded
me of Oasis, kind of. I know, it sounds crazy, right?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
