<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FRIGATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATING THE SEAS ON HEN FRIGATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HEN FRIGATES 
Wives of Merchant Captains Under Sail 
By Joan Druett 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 274 pp., Illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In researching ``Hen Frigates,'' an altogether fascinating
account of the joys and perils of the women who sailed with their
19th-century ship-captain husbands, maritime historian Joan Druett
drew upon 143 of their diaries, journals, and published
reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Druett, a New Zealander, found all but a few of
these accounts in libraries and historical society archives in New
England and on Long Island, that number suggests the richness of
material in this region for the historian. More significant,
perhaps, given that the preserved written records must represent a
minority of all who sailed, this suggests what a large number of
women, she writes, ``took up the strange existence in the
blue-water trade, surviving storms, visiting exotic ports, giving
birth at sea, raising children on shipboard and socializing with
other wives at scarce intervals.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sketchy biographical information about these women
indicates, ``these were ordinary, conservative, middle-class women,
certainly not rebels or adventurers.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, as Druett explains, a good reason why so many women
went to sea with their husbands _ the first voyage often being
their honeymoon. A ship captain, especially on a smaller coastal
schooner, most likely had ``invested a substantial sum of his own
money in the ship ... and could not afford to buy a house on
land.'' Besides, ``returning home to live with relatives might not
seem a pleasant option, after the excitement of the wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the accounts Druett draws on is a classic honeymoon voyage
taken by Susan Hathorn of Richmond, Maine, whose diary was the
basis of a book published last year as ``A Bride's Passage.'' There
were many like her _ such as Georgia Maria Gilkey of Searsport,
Maine, who in 1906 ``was married in her graduation dress, there
(having been) no time to make a wedding gown.'' They married a week
after Captain Phineas Banning Blanchard ``proposed to her during
one of his fleeting trips home.'' And ``after a hasty buffet
luncheon,'' they took the train to Philadelphia, where Blanchard's
square-rigger Bangalore was loading coal for a voyage around Cape
Horn to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other seagoing wives, Georgia Blanchard became a
skilled navigator. She recalled that she ``started right off
working the sights (i.e., sextant readings) each day and marking
them on my chart.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Alonzo Follansbee of the ship Logan knew how important a
skill that could be (although, Druett writes, he sometimes treated
his new bride as ``a rather witless child''), telling his wife that
knowledge of navigation and signal codes could make the difference
between life and death. ``All this and 10 times more, I have to
learn,'' she wrote in her journal, ``in case it should fall to my
lot to take charge of the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the ship Templar, the captain's daughter,
15-year-old Emma Armstrong, had to take charge after her father was
stricken with yellow fever (her mother having died a few days
before) on a passage from New York to San Francisco in 1879. ``She
assumed charge,'' Druett writes, ``finding their position every
noon and directing the few fit seamen in the setting of sails'' _
even though she was so sick herself ``that she had to be carried up
on deck in a litter to take her sights and issue directions.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was also time for romance in these ``hen frigates.''
On board the whaler Lucy Ann in 1847, Martha Brown, the captain's
wife, wrote in her journal that ``if quince groves and moonlight
nights are incentives to make love, surely moonlight nights on
shipboard are doubly so.'' And, ``naturally enough,'' Druett
reports, she became pregnant during the voyage but was set ashore
in Honolulu rather than giving birth on board, as was the case with
many other seagoing wives.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Hen Frigates'' comes from the common term for a ship
whose captain had his wife on board.
</P>
<P>
   The examples of its use cited in the Random House Historical
Dictionary of American Slang all have the connotation of
``henpecked'' _ as in the 1867 ``Sailor's Word Book,'' which
defines a ``hen frigate'' as ``a ship wherein the captain's wife
interfered in the duty or regulations.'' But seen through Druett's
lively and sometimes poignant accounts, the word that comes to mind
to describe the women is that somewhat old-fashioned one:
``spunky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
