<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ECONOMY-2TAKES     07-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ECONOMY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALLED PEACE PROCESS THREATENS EVOLUTION OF ISRAELI ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBBUTZ GEZER, Israel _ Set in the golden fields of the Ayalon
Valley, this kibbutz at first glance presents a vision of the early
Zionist ideal of working the land. Dairy cows moo in faded old
barns and tractors rumble up a hillside with a load of watermelons
from the fertile valley.
</P>
<P>
   But in a small office in the back of an old dining hall, the
future for this kibbutz and for all of Israel's economy can be
heard in the clicking of computer keyboards in the collective's new
internet service provider company called ``Gezernet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gezer's prize dairy herd may still be the bread and butter of
the kibbutz's annual budget, but its two-year-old venture into the
world of high tech is its promise for the future. It also is a
symbol for Israel's changing economy.
</P>
<P>
   As Israel celebrates its 50th anniversary of statehood this
year, it is in the process of a dramatic transformation from its
beginnings, which stressed agriculture and manufacturing, to a new
kind of technological pioneering that will take it into the next
century. Agriculture, which for decades was Israel's major source
of export earnings, now accounts for only 3 pecent of all exports.
Israel is now in fact a net importer of food.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is fast on its way to carving out a niche for itself in
the global economy as ``Silicon Valley East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an evolution, not a revolution,'' says Israeli Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman. ``Fifty years ago, the kibbutzniks were the
pioneers in this country. They were young and ambitious and
idealistic. And now this spirit will be in the field of high
technology. Young engineers and programmers will be the new
pioneers of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because Israel has relied for so long on billions of
dollars each year in American aid, it is difficult to analyze the
country's economic success. Still, its achievements over 50 years
are considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continuing heavy burden of defense spending in this
volatile region, economic modernization has raised Israel's Gross
Domestic Product to almost $17,000 per person. That far exceeds the
GDP per person in neighboring countries such as the much more
highly populated Egypt, also a major recipient of American aid,
which still struggles in poverty at roughly $2,900 GDP per person.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's growth since the 1991 Gulf War and the onset of the
historic 1993 Israeli-Palestinian peace accords has been
impressive. However, the current deadlock in the peace process
could, if it continues indefinitely, dash the hopes of Israel's new
economy. The lifeless peace process already is beginning to hurt
the economy, according to some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Israel's GDP was about $50 billion and $10 billion in
US loan guarantees were needed to finance Jewish emigration from
the former Soviet Union. Today, Israel's GDP is more than $100
billion.
</P>
<P>
   High tech is largely responsible for the growth, economic
analysts say. Israel's 50 largest high tech businesses generate
about $20 billion a year for the economy and now employ an
estimated 70,000 people. And since 1991, Israel has started some
3,000 high tech companies, the greatest number of high tech
startups in any country except the United States. About half of the
companies have survived and employ 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is making its mark mostly in the area of security and
telecommunications software. A company known as CheckPoint
Software, for example, has cornered the market on a service that
protects computer systems from viruses and hackers. The mix of a
growing entrepreneurial culture, a highly educated work force and
an extensive research and development infrastructure has also
attracted many multinationals to Israel, including Intel, IBM and
Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Helping pave the way for Israel's success is the opening of the
economy through privatization. It is a process that has evolved
since Israel's economic crisis in the mid-1980s but Netanyahu's
government has been more focused than his predecessors on breaking
up powerful, state-run businesses, such as the banking and
transportation industries.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of the unwieldly and largely inefficient
public service sector still has a long way to go, according to
Yakov Frankel, chairman of the Bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between the first 50 years and the next 50
years will be shifting the economy away from government control. It
is the only way we will be able to lower the tax burden and create
a free market,'' says Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who look at our successes, and say we
have to give ourselves time. But the hard truth is there is no
time. We are very late in entering the global market,'' adds
Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   To Neeman, there is no better illustration of the pioneering
spirit in Israel's opening economy than the story of Mirabilis Ldt.
The small Israeli software company was started by three Israelis in
their early 20s who traveled to California's Silicon Valley, saw
what was going on and brought that back to Israel, joining the pool
of 3,000 startup high tech companies. The difference between theirs
and the others is that they made it. Mirabilis, which had an
investment of $2 million by its owners, Neeman loves to point out,
was bought by America On Line Inc. on June 8 for $287 million in
cash. In 2001 AOL will make addition payments of $120 million based
on performance.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes downloadable software for chatting on the
Internet in real time. Although the firm does no marketing or
advertising, 13 million people have downloaded its software.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel should not be so quick to pat itself on the back,
some analysts caution. Despite the high tech fairy tales that have
made a few people fabulously rich, Israel is still lagging behind
the top performers in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Thurow, the MIT economist, is chairman of a program
called Technion Institute of Management in Tel Aviv that provides
advanced management training to Israel's high tech executives.
Thurow is a friend of Israel, but very tough on its economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
