<HEADER>
A0135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-17 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVEN YEARS LATER, BANK OF N.E. CREDITORS FIGHT ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's been seven years since the disasterous collapse of
Bank of New England, a painful but increasingly distant memory to
thousands of businesses and people who have moved on.
</P>
<P>
   That would not include Ben Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Branch is the trustee of Bank of New England's bankruptcy
estate, which has spent the seven years and about $40 million
trying to collect money and pursue claims on behalf of creditors,
mostly investors who were stuck holding about $700 million in bank
bonds when regulators seized the institution Jan. 6, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He's still working at it and estimates that, at best, the job
could take a couple more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years is a long time,'' said Branch, a finance professor
at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst. ``I'm not looking to
drag it out; I'd like to be done with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Branch works in a small warren of offices over a
restaurant near Faneuil Hall, just a couple of blocks from Bank of
New England's old headquarters building on State Street.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 thick blue binders filled with bankruptcy
documents line the office entrance. Two paralegals, an office
manager and one clerical worker make up the trustee's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Branch took a leave of absence from UMass for a year when he was
first appointed the Bank of New England trustee. He has gradually
scaled back his trustee work and now comes to Boston one day per
week to work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the bank estate's $40 million in expenses and most
of Branch's time has been dedicated to a civil suit in US District
Court in Boston against the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   At issue: more than $200 million Branch says belongs to company
creditors but instead fell into the hands of the FDIC. The FDIC,
the federal regulatory agency that shut the bank, denies it owes
any money.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors concede they are frustrated the estate has moved so
slowly, but generally blame the FDIC for dragging its feet in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have died along the way,'' said Gary Himber, a
securities broker in New Jersey who is chairman of the Bank of New
England creditors' committee. ``A lot of them are old. Seven years
is a long time when you're 80 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England was the second-largest banking company in
the region when it was pulled under by a huge portfolio of bad
loans, mostly backed by real estate. Dozens of New England banks
failed during that period, but none packed the painful financial
punch of the failure at Bank of New England. The company's banks
were later put up for bid by regulators in an auction won by Fleet
Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Just months ago, Bank of New England creditors received their
first payment of any kind, a $40 million interim distribution of
money the estate held from the beginning or acquired in other
settlements. Holders of senior bonds, who were on top of the
repayment pecking order, received about 15 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The payout, however, was roughly equal to the money spent by the
bank estate since 1991. About half that sum has been paid to
lawyers at Andrews &AMP; Kurth, hired by Branch to sue the FDIC and
pursue other cases for the bank estate. The Houston firm has
extensive experience battling with the FDIC over cases spawned by
the Texas banking collapse of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Branch has sued many parties as trustee, including former Bank
of New England directors and officers, as well as the public
accounting firm that worked for the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the case against the FDIC has been by far the most
contentious and time consuming. Challenges of all kinds litter the
history of the case, questioning everything from the validity of
expert witnesses and their conclusions to the right to a jury
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things drag on, and they fight you every step of the
way,'' said Himber, the head of the creditors committee.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years and a trial date finally in sight, both sides
asked a bankruptcy judge last week for permission to take the
matter to private mediation. A session with a mediator, New York
attorney Conrad K. Harper, has been tentatively scheduled for Aug.
31.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist, the FDIC is also a creditor of the bank's estate and
occasionally takes advantage of its right to challenge specific
expenses paid by Branch in his legal pursuit of the regulators.
``It is unusual,'' concedes attorney Deborah Griffin of Peabody &AMP;
Arnold, who represents the FDIC.
</P>
<P>
   The case centers on a dispute over when Bank of New England
actually became insolvent and the movement of cash within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England Corp., which issued stock and bonds, was a
holding company that technically owned its banks as subsidiaries.
Before it failed, the holding company had issued a new, $200
million round of bonds in late 1989 and promptly sent the money to
its banks.
</P>
<P>
   Once the money was moved to the banks, it fell beyond the legal
grasp of bondholders and into the hands of the FDIC for good.
</P>
<P>
   But Branch argues that Bank of New England was insolvent before
the last bond issue and well before regulators actually seized the
banks. Based on that claim, he argues the bond money should have
never been sent to the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants for Branch and the FDIC have generated dueling tomes
that measure the company's weak financial pulse in its last years
and come to predictably different conclusions on when insolvency
technically occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got an outrage perpetrated on the investing
public,'' said Julian Hertz of Larchmont, N.Y., a former criminal
court judge in New York City who bought Bank of New England bonds
on the cheap in 1990 when the company was known to be struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they were down in value, we paid considerable amounts
for these bonds. They were purchased with the thinking that this
thing was on the level,'' said Hertz.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for repayment to creditors may be reflected in the
current prices of Bank of New England's bonds, which still trade
sporadically.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England Corp. issued both senior and junior bonds.
The senior bonds are more valuable because they must be paid off in
full before junior bondholders get any of their money back.
</P>
<P>
   The senior bonds trade for roughly 33 cents on the dollar,
according to Himber. The junior bonds trade for less than a penny
on the dollar. Himber said Bank of New England subordinated bonds
with a face value of $1 million can sometimes be purchased for
about $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the estate's work grinds on. Branch believes he will
get closer to his goal of closing the bankruptcy file a settlement
is reached with the FDIC and the bank's auditors, who are being
sued in a separate case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those get resolved, everything will fall in place fairly
quickly,'' he said. At this pace, that means a few more years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
