<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0137 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JONES-BOS &LR;      07-17 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR FACES, NEW ROLES FOR JONES, DEL VALLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derrick ``Smoke'' Gainer probably knows Roy Jones Jr.
as well as anyone in boxing and he has a suggestion for World
Boxing Association light heavyweight champion Lou Del Valle.
</P>
<P>
   Leave Roy alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're better off if you don't get his attention,'' Gainer
said this week, which may be sound advice but not something Del
Valle will be likely to follow Saturday night, although it might
still be sound advice if he could.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Del Valle is that in 24 hours he will face Jones
in a boxing ring at the Theatre at Madison Square Garden and try to
add Jones's World Boxing Council version of the 175-pound title to
the WBA belt he presently owns. The likelihood of this happening is
roughly akin to the fight being snowed out.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Del Valle says he doesn't believe it will be as
difficult to hit the seemingly unhittable Jones as people keep
saying because he's hit him before. Jones, meanwhile, has grown
exasperated by his former sparring partner's confidence in the face
of what Jones sees as the inevitable _ which is an early night _
and so he has become peeved, a state of mind Smoke Gainer believes
is not a good sign for Del Valle.
</P>
<P>
   Gainer may have a point but Del Valle insists he's hoping the
ire he has caused will inspire Jones to come after him the way he
went after his last two opponents _ Montell Griffin and Virgil
Hill. Why he thinks this is a good idea in the face of the fact
Griffin was KO'd in one round and Hill in four is difficult for
some to fathom but it makes perfect sense to Del Valle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the style to beat Roy Jones,'' Del Valle (27-1, 19 KOs)
said this week. ``I've never seen him hit on the chin. He's gonna
get hit if he comes out after me the way he did Montell and Virgil
because I'm the best counterpuncher in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be hard for him to lead with his left hook. If he
does, I'll counter with my left. I feel he's going to come out real
hard like he did in the second Montell fight. He's going to put
pressure on and I believe he's going to get himself in trouble
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of Jones's most recent opponents, these are
bold words but Del Valle will tell you they come from experience _
the 38 rounds he spent sparring with Jones for $750 a week in 1995
when Jones was preparing to fight another southpaw, Antoine Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle says he more than held his own during those sessions
which is more than Byrd can claim since he, too, was knocked out in
one round.
</P>
<P>
   ``His camp knows I held my own,'' Del Valle said.
</P>
<P>
   What Del Valle believes is that the fact he's been in with Jones
for 38 rounds gives him an edge over the 36 guys the WBC champion
has already beaten (31 of them by knockout). Jones nods in assent.
</P>
<P>
   What Del Valle also believes is that the fact he's been in with
Jones for 38 rounds allows him to understand the WBC champion's
weaknesses _ such as they may be _ and more importantly allows him
to understand Jones's approach in a fight. To this, Jones nods in
assent but less enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, Del Valle says Jones is a counterpuncher, same as he is,
which could make for a slow night unless Jones (36-1) opts to
ignore his normal style and attack. To this, Jones says nothing
except this rather menacing statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted Roy Jones. Now he's got Roy Jones. But
what's he going to do with him?''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe Del Valle, he's going to move, counterpunch, and
wait for the chance to shock the world.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe Jones's stablemate, Smoke Gainer, he's going to
ignore some good advice and get himself in a heap of trouble before
he ends up in a heap at Jones's feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good counterpuncher,'' Jones conceded. ``He is left
handed and he is a good defensive fighter. I'll give him all that.
But he got nothing to keep me off him. He says he learned a lot
from sparring with me. If he did, now he knows what he has to run
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like Roy Jones Jr. believes his old sparring partner
should have taken his old friend's advice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-WALKER-2N     07-17 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-WALKER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CHICAGO: ... want to stay?  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I would love to,'' he says. ``But sometimes I
have doubts. Right now with the comments being made, well, I don't
like comments being made, know what I'm saying? Right now, I'm an
All-Star at this level. And I want to be treated like that. You
work hard to get at a certain level, you want to maintain that
level. And I can't maintain it like this when my coach isn't behind
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of this negative publicity that's been getting in
the paper. They say, ``We didn't say it like this; we didn't word
it like that.' Why not just: `No comment'?''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot unsaid in the Walker pauses. He remembers all
slights and perceived shuns. For all the Walker Wiggles and
technicals and scowls, Walker is described as a soft-spoken man who
craves the every-other-week, Sunday through Friday sessions he has
with his 4-year-old daughter, Crystal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's built just like 'Toine,'' laughs Dennis Smith, a friend
of Walker's. ``She's knock-kneed and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker remembers not receiving the Catholic League MVP at Mount
Carmel, an award that went to a rival player named Jerry Gee, who
played at Illinois. He remembers the taunts from fans, people
chastising him for showing off, people saying he couldn't read.
``And these were adults,'' said Mike Curta, Walker's high school
coach. He remembers not getting consideration for Rookie of the
Year. He remembers Grizzlies general manager Stu Jackson telling
him that he couldn't pick him third in the 1996 draft because he
wasn't projected that high. He remembers last month, how he wanted
the Celtics to draft forward-center Mohammed and how they wound up
with guard-forward Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierce is a good player,'' Walker says. ``He's a guy who can
come off the bench and give scoring to our second unit. But I know
our team needs. We need big people.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. Pierce off the bench? How about Pierce starting?
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen,'' Walker said. `` ... But I don't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker is a sensitive man. So if the Celtics choose to wait and
see how he performs in 1998-99 without first signing him to a
contract extension ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, I won't re-sign. That's a guarantee. If the
lockout works out where I can sign this year and they don't sign me
to an extension, I will not come back. If they don't sign me? I'm
gone. That's not showing loyalty to me. It shouldn't be a question.
If that happens, no matter what I do (in '98-99) I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours after her son says this, Diane Walker _ often
mistaken as a 20-something sister of Walker's _ will be wearing a
Celtics T-shirt. She knows her son is a pro star. In Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win, man,'' he says. ``I'd like to stay in Boston.
The fans are excellent. It's a great place to play. It would be
weird to go into a new city and establish a new identity when I
already have one there. But I know I was on the trading block. I
guess that's business because maybe the Celtics could get three
players for me or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is an echo in this room, with its exposed brick walls
and hardwood floors. The topic echoes, too, going all the way back
to the summer camp Walker did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you,'' he says, ``no veteran, All-Star player
shows up for a camp like that. For the rest of my career, I'll
never go to a camp like that. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp that Walker doesn't believe is a waste of time takes
place at his old high school. Walker is here, sitting at a table in
a noisy Student Center. He is eating pizza and watching a tape from
1994 when a skinny high schooler in a brown and white jersey _
No.23 _ is on his way to a 35-point night.
</P>
<P>
   Here, all Walker has to do is make sure he is around for the
children, his brothers and sisters among them. A few campers watch
as a team led by Walker and Donovan McNabb take on Miles Simon's
team. Some of Walker's friends have volunteered as coaches and
referees. They tease him as he watches the tape. ``That was a nice
move,'' Eugene McIntosh says, ``but on the next trip down, you're
shooting air, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost. Two possessions later, a confident Walker pulls up and
releases an airball. The children laugh. Walker does, too. You can
see hints of his game, then: the swagger, the ballhandling, the
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quiet off the court,'' Diane Walker says. ``On the court
is the only time he really shows a lot of emotion. It's something
he loves to do. A lot of people misread his facial expressions. I
understand that because people do the same thing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   But 20,000 people in NBA arenas have never watched Diane Walker
do the Walker Wiggle. She hasn't been whistled for 30 technicals in
two seasons. She has not been accused of being, ``the most hated
player in the NBA.'' The children here would disagree with that. So
would Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm the most loved player in the NBA,'' he says,
smiling. ``Really, people in the NBA love each other. No one in the
NBA really hates someone else. Maybe there was something extra in
the Larry Johnson-Alonzo Mourning fight, something that went beyond
the court. But most guys love each other. We're playing in the best
league in the world and many of us are millionaires; why would you
hate anybody?''
</P>
<P>
   Hall adds of the on-court Walker, ``Once you open your mouth
you've got to do something. A quiet person can get away with
playing bad and delivering nothing. But a vocal person has to
accept the criticism. When Antoine is on the court, he's
mean-spirited. When he steps out, he's a human being like anyone
else. He has compassion; he has concern for the youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall points to a gym full of smiling children. ``This is like
wanting the ball right here,'' he says. ``Creating a camp for the
kids. Giving them an opportunity to mingle with him, learn a few
fundamentals and have fun. He wants the ball. He's stepping up. Off
the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker will leave today for Miami where he will play in
Mourning's charity game. At the end of this month, he'll go to LA
and play in Magic Johnson's game. At some point, he will have to
sit down and think about his future, a future that goes beyond a
free camp at Mount Carmel High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do and I don't know what the
Celtics want to do,'' he said. ``I'm not saying I'm trying to break
the bank; I don't know what I'm looking for (in terms of a
contract). But I have a lot to think about. Right now I'm at the
point where I need to get to the next level. And that means making
the playoffs and winning a championship. I have to look at all my
options. I want to win. And I have to look at what (the Celtics)
do. Hey, we could finish 36-46 again. That's something I have to
think about.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walker's camp is over, he walks toward his car and heads
for Lakeshore Drive. He has said a lot about Pitino, about the
options he has to explore and about the Celtics' loyalty to him. He
has also made one revealing comment:
</P>
<P>
   He wants to have this camp again. Next year. In Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
