<HEADLINE>
MARV ALBERT'S BACK, BUT SHOULD HE BE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Yesssss, Marv Albert is back in the broadcast
business.
</P>
<P>
   If the reunion of Albert and Madison Square Garden surprises
you, if it outrages you in the least, then you need a refresher
course in the facts of life.
</P>
<P>
   Has the man no shame? Of course he has no shame. Shame in the
1990s lasts about as long as a keg of beer at a Friday night
fraternity party.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 months have passed since Albert pulled a courtroom
version of Roberto Duran's no mas. Albert stopped charges that he
committed forcible sodomy on his longtime lover from reaching a
jury by abruptly pleading guilty to having more hair on his palms
than on his head.
</P>
<P>
   The legal term is misdemeanor assault. A concurrent trial in the
court of public opinion resulted in convictions on the charges of
impersonating Corporal Klinger, soliciting three-way sex, planting
the idea of biting someone in Mike Tyson's head and possessing the
worst hairpiece this side of Sam Donaldson. The sentence: an
indefinite revocation of his alphabet soup privileges.
</P>
<P>
   NBC fired Albert from his job announcing NBA and NFL games. MSG
allowed Albert to resign from his job calling Knicks games. The
return of Albert to MSG is merely the continuation of the cycle of
life for the rich, famous and scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   Make trouble. Issue an insincere apology. Lie low. Rehearse
saying what people want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did was wrong,'' Albert said, an admission he wasn't
willing to make publicly last year. ``I hurt many people, including
my fiancee, my family, my friends and my employers. For that, I am
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The time for Albert to be sorry was a year ago. If Albert had
shown some contrition then, if he hadn't tried to bluff his way
through the accusations of his former lover of 10 years, then he
wouldn't have become the bite stuff for standup comics across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the guilty plea, Albert insisted any guilt on his
part was a legal technicality. When Albert made the Barbara Walters
circuit last November, he further enraged women's groups by playing
the blame-the-victim game. It's a little late now to believe Albert
is sorry for anything but the disruption to his life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the National Organization for Women should resist getting
in a hissing match with Albert. Like it or not, Albert has every
right to go back to work for any employer who wants him.
Ultimately, it's up to the public to decide the price Albert should
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that I get a second chance from viewers,'' Albert
said. ``Just look at the product on the air and make judgments from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wishful thinking. Even if Albert were to discover the cure for
cancer, it would be hard to push aside the picture painted by a
former Hyatt hotel executive who testified that in 1994 Albert
summoned her to his room for assistance. According to the woman,
Albert greeted her wearing panties and a garter belt and tried to
force her to perform oral sex on him. She said she ripped off his
toupee and fled from him.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, defense attorney Roy Black made the mistake of
suggesting the story _ even the detail about the hairpiece _ had
been conconcted from media reports. The woman testified that she
had known for years that Albert wore a toupee, prompting Black to
ask, ``Because you read it in the press?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it and see,'' Masden said. ``Yeah, it's very
apparent that he wears a toupee.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter rocked the courtroom. Can people take Albert seriously
after that? Will it hurt anything but his feelings if they don't?
He's just an announcer, not a doctor or school teacher. He's going
to do Knicks games on radio and half-hour roundup shows on
television.
</P>
<P>
   As long as there is a place in radio for G. Gordon Liddy and in
television for Jerry Springer, then surely there is an audience out
there for Marv Albert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
