<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-NEWPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE AMERICA'S CUP SAILING BACK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ They are getting ready to celebrate in the
streets of this old port, getting ready for a wild homecoming
party.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 long and lonely years, the America's Cup will be coming
home, back to its rightful owners, to the city that loved it and
lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's the scenario, anyway. Maybe it's a bit premature to
put the Moet on ice.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer in Newport, as the New York Yacht Club prepares
its assault on New Zealand _ current holders of the Cup _ there is
a growing sense of ... well, maybe it could happen. The fact is
that the next America's Cup race in 1999/2000 is the first chance
the New Yorkers will have had in 14 years to win back the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Young America, the NYYC America's Cup syndicate,
launched its newest boat, ``Spirit of Rhode Island'' from its
Quonset Point Sail Center for summer training in Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   As International America's Cup Class No. 39 prepared to sail,
Marilyn Almond, wife of Rhode Island Governor Lincoln Almond,
christened the boat and the New Yorker's $40 million campaign to
win back the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Bristol, boatbuilder Eric Goetz has been commissioned
to build two boats for Young America.
</P>
<P>
   In what is called the ``modern era'' of America's Cup racing,
Newport became synonymous with a spectacle that dominated the life
of the city every two to three years, and featured such yachting
luminaries as Bus Mosbacher, Ted Turner, Tom Blackaller, and Dennis
Conner. For 25 years the 12-meter class was used in Newport, a less
expensive alternative to the huge J-boats that were sailed up to
1937 when war interrupted the Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   And as the event grew in stature throughout the modern era,
Newport grew from a down-at-the-heels Navy town to a summer
playground with nearly the opulence of the early Cup days. Though
there was never much sailing contest (the Americans ``waived the
rules and ruled the waves'') from the mid-70s to 1983, Newport and
the America's Cup was a waterfront happening that commanded
international attention.
</P>
<P>
   From some points of view, Sept. 26, 1983 was a disaster. But it
was hard to find many Americans on the Newport waterfront who were
not rooting for the upstart Australian team with its breakthrough
design and focused veteran sailing team.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Aussie teams of Frank Packer and Alan Bond
brought huge amounts of good cheer and fun to the America's Cup,
but by 1983 they were not to be distracted by the hilarity of
Newport's party life. From mid-July in the trials, everyone knew
that Australia II was the fastest Twelve on the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   But the Australians winning the Cup was far from inevitable. In
the final series a number of breakdowns had the Australians behind
Dennis Conner's Liberty team, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   And there's scarcely a Cup fan alive who doesn't remember that
last race on Rhode Island Sound packed with thousands of spectators
who seemed to anticipate the huge change of course that was about
to befall Newport.
</P>
<P>
   For four of six legs, Conner led the Aussies, but as the air
went light on that fateful downwind leg 5, John Bertrand sailed
Australia II past Liberty for a lead the Aussies managed to hold up
the final beat. After 132 years, a foreign challenger had won the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   That night the lid came off the town. An estimated half million
fans pushed to get near the waterfront, and the champagne-soaked
bash went through the evening in what most natives say was the
wildest party Newport ever threw or witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   In the sober dawn, with their historic Cup pedestal now bare,
members of the New York Yacht Club shrank from the intensely
quarrelsome summer, and all but lost interest in the Cup. A new
generation of New Yorkers mounted a challenge in 1987 in Fremantle,
Australia, but the flawed campaign never came close, and Dennis
Conner took the Cup back to his home club in San Diego. It was the
last shot for Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, of course, John Marshall, who is president of Young
America, is not thinking victory parties yet. With six US teams and
16 total challengers, predictions are a bit premature.
</P>
<P>
   But as his two training boats sail their seven-day program off
Newport this summer, Marshall is aware of the growing buzz of
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be sailing our first real America's Cup race in October
of '99,'' says Marshall, who ran the design team that built the
victorious Stars &AMP; Stripes for Conner in '87. ``That's not a very
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   With two boats training and another two coming from Goetz
(builder of Bill Koch's Cup winner), Marshall says he is pleased
with the progress, and also the reception from the East Coast
backers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been able to stay focused on what we need to do to
bring the Cup back,'' says Marshall, whose start-up Young America
program had just one boat to work with in 1995. ``There's a feeling
around here of `We've got a home team, let's support them.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
