<HEADER>
A0153 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ECONOMY-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     07-17 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ECONOMY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (f and i coding)  
 KIBBUTZ GEZER, Israel: ... on its economy.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The statistics are a lot of hype. The fact is Israel is not
doing as well as it should be,'' Thurow said on a tour of the
country this month. ``Israel is not a miracle. There is no country
in the world with education levels as high as Israel that has such
a low per capita income.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurow compares Israel to Singapore. In 1965, Israel had 10
times the per capita income of Singapore. Today, Singapore has two
times the per capita income of Israel, even though Israel remains a
far more educated country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Well, as Israel has found out, if you take all your
talent and put it in the military, you hurt your economy. If you
don't have peace and stable trading partners, you hurt your
economy,'' Thurow explains.
</P>
<P>
   Israel today is like New England in the late 1960s, Thurow adds.
Back then there were dying industrial towns in Lowell and Lawrence
and there was a new road called Route 128 with new companies. But
they were very small. Today, New England seems to have successfuly,
albeit painfully, made the transition from an industrial to a high
tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean Israel will inevitably end up like New
England, unless it manages its future well,'' Thurow warns. ``The
dying industries can overwhelm the growing industries.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the pain of the transition of the economy is evident in
Israel as unemployment continues to climb, edging toward 9 percent
this month. The dropoff in jobs is a result of a transformation
from the lower-value-addded manufacturing sector, where hundreds of
thousands were once employed, to super-high-margin software
businesses that employ fewer, but more educated and skilled,
people. Mirabilis is a prime example. Despite its tremendous
success and the wealth it has created for its owners, the company
employs only 65 people.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's policy of maintaining an
overvalued shekel has been clearly tilted in favor of the high tech
businesses. This has kept inflation down to about 7 percent and
helped venture capitalists, but it sacrifices jobs in the
manufacturing companies that seek to export goods overseas because
it makes the goods more expensive. The bulk of the workers in
manufacturing are the working class Sephardim, or Jewish immigrants
mainly from Arab countries, who have supported Netanyahu's Likud
government. These economic policies could eventually spell
political danger for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are creating a deep class division here. And it will
create a lot of unrest,'' says Nat Shenker, the president of Oletex
Industries Ltd., a textile company in Jerusalem that employs 300
people and has been suffering in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu feels a high tech economy may be insulated from the
constant tensions in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 11 interview with Fortune magazine, Netanyahu said:
``The amazingly growing sector in Israel is the high-tech sector.
And that is the most impervious to political or military
developments... Peace would be a useful condition, but it is not
the primordial, necessary condition, which is anywhere, economic
freedom _ and we are increasing that kind of freedom by leaps and
bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are many business leaders and economic analysts who
think Netanyahu is dangerously misguided, and that the economic
fate of Israel and the region will depend on the peace process,
which for the last 16 months has been derailed. Specifically,
analysts point to declining foreign investment in Israel as a sign
that the investors' optimism that surrounded the peace process is
fading. Overseas investment in the first five months of 1998 was
$806 million, down dramatically from $1.5 billion in the same
period last year, according to Israel's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Ezer Weizman, whose role is largely ceremonial
and rarely confrontational, has taken Netanyahu on by boycotting an
annual economic conference last month. He blames Israel's economic
stagnation and what he sees as the economy's failure to live up to
its potential on Netanyahu's unwillingness to break the impasse in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a clear opinion that you can't isolate economics and
security from the policies of war and peace,'' Weizman said. ``The
peace today is sputtering and is limping -- and the economy along
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the successes and the more recent vascilations of the
Israeli economy may have more to do with the process of change
through the half century of Israel's existence.
</P>
<P>
   The kibbutz movement during and before the founding of the
Jewish state in 1948 was at the center of ``overturning the Jewish
pyramid,'' as kibbutzniks called it. It meant taking a highly
educated population of Jews from Europe after World War II with few
agricultural or industrial skills and creating a broad Jewish
workforce out of it. The ethos of Zionism and its Labor Party was
to glorify working the land and working with your hands to build
Israel. They needed brawn, not just brains, to create a state that
could survive economically and militarily.
</P>
<P>
   Israel now finds it needs once again to turn the pyramid, to go
back to the focus on education and continue its transition from an
agricultural and manufacturing economy into a global economy and
its requirements for a highly educated and trained workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Shulman, 42, an international lawyer who works with a
software company in Jerusalem, lives on Kibbutz Gezer and supports
the new high tech venture on the collective. Most of the nation's
250 kibbutzim and the roughly 120,000 people who live on them have
fallen on lean times in the last decade. But it's not because they
don't work hard. Although they represent only 3 percent of the
population, they provide 40 percent of the country's agriculture,
about 8 percent of its industrial output, and 10 percent of its
tourism. The reality is that the ethos of collective living has
faded, and so the kibbutzim will have to look for creative ways to
stay alive in the historic shift in Israel's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways the kibbutzim are economically conservative. It
was a big risk for us to invest in Gezernet. But it is the right
decision,'' says Shulman, who lives on the kibbutz with his wife
and six-year-old daughter. ``Not only because information and
technology are the future. But because we will have to come up with
new ways to keep the next generation on the farm. We're doing it to
keep our community together. It's all about the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
