<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI &LR;      07-17 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Saturday, July 18, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   BABBITT (Undated) _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, one of the
few Western voices with an ear at the White House, understands that
environmental politics can cause a split as wide as the canyon
lands dividing Arizona and Utah. But he has also been around enough
to know that progress is often a product of compromise with one's
political adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BABBITT-TENURE (Missoula, Mont.) _ More than five years after
striding into national office, Bruce Babbitt has been battered by
the currents of national politics. Although he has not reeled in
the big legislative catch, he continues to push his views on
conservation through persistence and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BABBITT-PREDECESORS (Undated) _ A look at some of Bruce
Babbitt's predecessors, their successes and failures. (Suitable for
graphic treatment.)
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-SMITH-COLUMN (Undated) _ A few years ago a guy walked
into an El Torito restaurant in Orange, Calif., and while munching
into his taco, bit off the head of a frog. Or so he said. This is
the kind of public relations creature from the black lagoon that
can give corporate executives nightmares, and can even bring down
an organization. That's where Michael Sitrick comes in.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CRITICS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ ABC hopes to climb out of its
ratings funk this fall with the help of a little sports and a
little fantasy. More specifically: ``Sports Night'' and _ don't
laugh _ ``Fantasy Island.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SEATTLE-DUCKS (Seattle) _ Seattle has long had guided
tours in its downtown streets and tour boats in Lake Union, but a
new venture will do both in the same trip. PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (Story will move in the ``t'' category.)
</P>
