A0199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV19-BO     07-17 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW FIELDS A CONVERTIBLE WITH A TRULY REMARKABLE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, July 19 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Convertibles are the cars of summer,the perfect chariots for
balmy days, top down, wind in the hair, sun shining _ at least
that's the image. The convertible is the car that everybody dreams
of, longs for, but that hardly anybody buys. Everybody wants one
sometime, but hardly anybody wants one all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The ragtop is a car of youth and of second childhoods, of
yearnings and romance. A practical car it is not. Well, that's the
common wisdom, but the columnist does harbor some contrary
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, a convertible shouldn't be thought of as strictly
topless summertime transport. In fact, summertime is frequently the
worst time to be driving sans roof, especially if you are balding.
The wind in what's left of your hair won't prevent sunburn, and the
protection afforded by a hat is difficult to secure at road speed.
When it's 90 degrees in the shade, the seats are hot, the wind is
hot ... this driver keeps the roof in place and cranks up the air
conditioning to the ``meat locker'' setting.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to lower the canvas, in my opinion, is late
afternoon/ early evening, just before the sun goes down. The sun
low on the horizon is less of a burn threat, the wind in your hair
a distinct treat in the absence of blast-furnace heat. Yes, the
mosquitoes seem to swarm at sundown, but they have a tough time
catching you at 55.
</P>
<P>
   The modern convertible with well-fitted, insulated top and a
glass backlight (that's trade jargon for the back window) with
electric defroster is an all-weather car. And snow on the roof is
easily removed; just get in and give the ragtop a few thumps with
your fist.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best moments for the convertible are those first
warm days of spring when the snow is on the run and those lazy
afternoons of Indian summer with the foliage assuming the bright
hues of autumn. The ragtop is _ or at least can be _ a car for all
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the way I was viewing things on a balmy summer
night as I discovered to my delight that the BMW convertible just
delivered had a high-tech, one-touch motorized top. I have never
been a fan of manual tops, although some of them have been
engineered to be simple _ the Mazda Miata comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible awaiting was the M3 ragtop, a handsome little
performance model in Dakar yellow _ Dakar is a city in Africa, and
I never knew it had its own color _ with a black roof. One key
stroke in the door opens all the locks, so I dump the papers and
stuff in the trunk where they won't blow all over the roadway, slip
behind the wheel, crank up the 240-horsepower, 3.2-liter
six-cylinder, and press the magic button. Let the dance begin.
</P>
<P>
   A ballet it is as the top unhooks from the brow of the
windshield, the rear deck opens, and the canvas rises, bends,
convulses into the innards of the car, and the lid snaps shut. Off
we go, but the wind isn't blowing the hair much; the Expressway is
a crawlway at 6:15 p.m. Soon, I am sweating, beginning to feel
gritty _ that's gritty as in dust-covered from the Boston's Big
Dig. But the creep through town is interesting for those of us
curious about the construction processes, equipment, and structural
details. Why, for example, is part of one of the new elevated
roadways that are replacing the old elevated roadway in the name of
``depressing'' it, built of prefab concrete pieces that suddenly
join a deck laid on steel frames? And what is being depressed,
exactly, other then the commuters ... but I digress.
</P>
<P>
   By 6:45 or so, I'm on Route 1 and the speed has increased some;
it is necessary to crank up the radio volume. The radio controls
are the pits, not meant to be manipulated while in motion. Finally,
I turn onto Interstate 95; the wind is positively whistling across
the pate, the sun is a fierce orange ball on the rim of the
horizon, and David Brudnoy is waxing eloquent on the air waves _
with the volume set to Blaster, I can hear him. This is the
convertible at its best.
</P>
<P>
   This is the topless version of the BMW performance model, the
M3, a rear-drive speedster with a gutsy six-cylinder engine mated
with a very smooth 5-speed manual gearbox. The multi-valve engine
is elastic enough _ and powerful enough _ that the car in high gear
might as well be an automatic; in fifth, you can accelerate quite
smartly, coast down to relatively low speed, then boost it back to
real speed quite nicely without ever changing gears. Accelerate in
any gear.
</P>
<P>
   Although most people tell me that manuals are not what you want
when negotiating the latest undulations of the Big Dig in rush
hour, I do find that it is possible to creep in low gear without
constantly braking and declutching. Yes, some people do jump in
front as the space opens now and then, but they don't get anywhere
any faster for the effort and they aren't really impeding my small
progress. But BMW manuals do have their drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hampton (N.H.) Toll Plaza, I encounter said drawbacks. I
pay the toll, slip the shifter into first and step on the gas. The
M3 bolts backward _ I'm in reverse. I try again, paying more
attention this time. I go backward. The guy behind me is not seeing
the humor of this situation. OK folks, I know what some of you are
thinking, but I do know how to operate a manual gearbox, I do know
how to drive, dammit, and BMW is dead wrong not to gate the
transmission so that reverse is well differentiated from first.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be a matter of cost. How much can such a small change
add to the price of a $45,900 _ plus $570 delivery _ automobile?
That's the M3 ragtop's main fault: price.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, while the trunk is sacrificed for the rooftop
retractors, the back seat remains usable for adults _ but not this
adult. On the minus side, although the car is generously equipped,
the dual mode climate control doesn't quite hack it. With a driver
wanting cool and a passenger wanting warm, the passenger still gets
a cool breeze from the vents. If the passenger is warm, so is the
driver. Nor is the system fully automatic; the AC must be engaged
manually.
</P>
<P>
   The seat controls are less than convenient, and interior storage
is somewhat limited _ small glove box and door bins. An armrest
covers two cupholders and a coin holder _ why does a proper driver
need an armrest?
</P>
<P>
   BMW may have fumbled details, but there is no denying the
excellent performance, the sheer joy of driving the topless M3. The
ride is firm, forgiving, the handling precise, crisp, indicative of
a rigid chassis. Excellent acceleration (0-60 in 5.8 seconds) is
complemented by quick controlled braking. BMW's all-weather
traction control promises winter performance, too. Fuel mileage
isn't bad, either _ 24.54 miles per gallon over 1,155 miles
tracked. I guess I really liked it to drive it that much _ about
1,500 miles total _ in a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
