</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't told us exactly what the nature of our violation
is,'' says Darrell Jordan of Hughes &AMP; Luce, the Dallas law firm
representing Parsons. ``But it seems pretty clear they are
targeting software.''
</P>
<P>
   Another publisher of self-help legal software, Nolo Press of
Berkeley, Calif., has been notified that the same subcommittee will
hold a hearing next month to determine the legality of its product.
Two other producers of legal software are also thought to be under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Quicken software can be used to draft documents such as
wills and leases. In a section called ``Ask Arthur Miller,'' the
famous Harvard lawyer of the same name appears on video and
expounds on issues ranging from choosing a lawyer to deciding
whether or not you can afford to buy a house.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ticer, the Dallas lawyer who chairs the Supreme Court
subcommittee, insists that it is not singling out software. In
1992, he says, a book written by someone with no legal
qualifications was judged to have breached the statute invoked
against Parsons Technology. But Ticer argues that the Quicken
program may represent a more serious breach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It asks you questions, selects forms for you, and a lawyer
pops up and gives you advice. If that isn't dispensing legal
advice, what is?'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Nolo's associate publisher, Steve Elias, says he does not
see how computer code can be accused of practicing law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers know the difference between a lawyer and a
program,'' he says. ``The idea of the program being a lawyer in a
box just doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out that the software's introductory screen tells its
users: ``You must use you own judgment and, to the extent you
believe appropriate, the assistance of a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if such programs were to be outlawed in Texas, he argues
that the ruling would be unenforceable, as the software could still
be downloaded from the Internet or ordered from booksellers
operating on the Web. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
