<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0215 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABBITT-TENURE-SPI &LR;      07-17 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-TENURE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABBITT'S TURBULENT TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. _ Cameras snap and videotapes roll as Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt steps into the swirling Big Blackfoot
River.
</P>
<P>
   Encased in chest waders, Babbitt casts a fly behind a boulder.
He flips the fly onto the currents again and again, but he doesn't
get the flash and splash of a biting trout.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, Babbitt clambers out dripping wet and tells
reporters that ranchers and the government are working together to
restore the river's fish.
</P>
<P>
   More than five years after striding into national office,
Babbitt has been battered by the currents of national politics.
Although he has not reeled in the big legislative catch, he
continues to push his views on conservation through persistence and
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining how his approach has changed, Babbitt offers a
football metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came in naively expecting that we'd be throwing a
lot of long passes into the end zone,'' he said. Instead, he
adopted the strategy of former Ohio State University football coach
Woody Hayes, who ran the ball forward in short, hard-fought bursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three yards and a cloud of dust,'' Babbitt said. ``Just keep
grinding away.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt is crisscrossing the country as much as ever these days.
On this occasion, he has come to Montana to showcase river
restoration. On other trips, he has released transplanted wolves,
planted fish and inspected parks across much of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Babbitt is promoting conservation through a strategy of
cooperation, not confrontation. This collaborative style _ which
has drawn criticism from both right and left _ has colored his
policies. Early political defeats in Congress and a moderate White
House have caused Babbitt to back off plans for rapid environmental
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt claims the more measured approach is winning new friends
for his efforts to protect the environment. One limited victory
Babbitt points to is protecting the 1973 Endangered Species Act and
developing new ways to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   The act was under mounting attack from conservatives who called
it an inflexible burden on private property owners. Many
environmentalists feared it would be dismantled. But Babbitt has
helped sustain it by advocating compromise agreements called
Habitat Conservation Plans that allow for private use of land in
return for improvements that lessen harm to endangered and
threatened species.
</P>
<P>
   These deals let miners, loggers and real estate developers
continue to use the land for profit, but force them to do so in
ways that don't destroy their own and neighboring habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Before he took office, only 15 such plans had been written. But
Babbitt grabbed the concept and expanded its use. Although the
scientific grounding of some of the plans has recently been
challenged, there are about 225 in place around the country, and
more are being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bean, a leading authority on wildlife law at the
Environmental Defense Fund, believes Babbitt has been an effective
secretary. ``He's probably had far more impact on the Endangered
Species Act than any of his predecessors,'' Bean said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt _ a fan of noted naturalist and wildlife biologist Aldo
Leopold, and a reader of Wallace Stegner, whose novels chronicle
the evolution of the new West _ went to Washington, D.C., in 1993
with big ideas. He wanted to rewrite federal timber, mining and
grazing laws. He hoped to spearhead legislation to increase grazing
fees for ranchers and to stop miners from ravaging federal lands
for token fees. But Babbitt's efforts to impose wholesale change
ended with the election of a Republican Congress in 1994 and have
not recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Law of 1872 remains on the books, despite Babbitt's
protests that it forces the government to give away billions of
dollars worth of federal minerals for a pittance. And while grazing
fees have inched upward, ranchers continue to get bargain-basement
grass on federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that we've been able to stymie this
administration on so many fronts,'' said Nancie Marzulla, executive
director of Defenders of Property Rights, a Washington, D.C.-based
group.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups believe that Babbitt and his staff have effectively
achieved modest change through compromise and administrative
avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bypass Congress and go off on their own,'' said Chuck
Cushman, leader of the American Land Rights League, a
Washington-based grass-roots property rights group.
</P>
<P>
   A practical politician who learned how to balance the interests
of opposing groups during nearly a decade as governor of Arizona,
Babbitt helped shepherd Clinton's Northwest Forest Plan into
effect. That plan limited the logging of old growth trees on
federal timber lands, but did allow for some cutting in coastal
national forest areas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Babbitt's policies have given environmentalists and
recreation groups more influence over federal grazing land
management by establishing Range Advisory Councils to bring modest
reforms to rules governing the grazing of cattle and sheep. He has
also been instrumental in convincing Congress and Clinton to expand
the national park system and to help fend off efforts to diminish
environmental protections offered by the Clean Air Act of 1970 and
the Clean Water Act of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP, however, has blocked some of his favorite programs,
including halting the money needed to fund the National Biological
Survey, a study that aimed to provide information needed to use the
ecosystems as a focus for conservation policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, deals have been cut to increase the amount of water
flowing into the Florida Everglades, California's Central Valley
and the Platte River; to protect suburban wildlife habitat in
places including Austin, Texas, and Denver; and to boost wildlife
safeguards on millions of acres of timberland from North Carolina
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And the Habitat Conservation Plans that Babbitt has encouraged
as the most realistic way to protect endangered species are having
especially big effects on the Northwest. After an initial period of
caution, big timberland owners have increasingly taken advantage of
the program. In five Western states, plans are complete or are
being drafted to cover more than 11 million acres _ including about
one-quarter of the region's non-federal commercial timberland, an
area the size of Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island and
one-third of New Hampshire, combined.
</P>
<P>
   To many landowners, the key change that made participating in
the plans acceptable was Babbitt's ``no surprises'' policy, which
generally promised landowners that if they agreed to do certain
things for a troubled species, the government wouldn't come back in
a couple of years and demand more.
</P>
<P>
   ``They created the thing that was missing in the law:
Certainty,'' said W. Henson Moore, president and CEO of the
American Forest and Paper Association and a leader of the
Endangered Species Coordinating Council, a group of industries
seeking changes in the law.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt is proud the plans are being used by a broader range of
participants and sees them as an example of balancing the needs of
property rights and the protection of biological resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're writing a new and important chapter of
affirmative conservation history,'' he said. ``We've refashioned
the Endangered Species Act from top to bottom administratively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Defense Fund's Bean agrees. ``I think Babbitt
has done a great deal to rescue this act from the political
oblivion that it came close to and made it work effectively on the
ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups, however, complain bitterly that
Babbitt has resisted listing certain species as threatened or
endangered. They also claim that many of the habitat plans give
landowners leeway to harm rare species in exchange for vague
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without true public participation and scientifically
defensible components, which many plans currently lack, they run
the risk of being dangerous and deceptive political
accommodations,'' said James Wyerman, vice president of the
Defenders of Wildlife, a Washington, D.C.-based environmental
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have added to the criticism. The most exhaustive
study of the plans so far, led by University of Washington
researcher Peter Kareiva, found that the plans commonly lack sound
data, analysis and monitoring to show they will help conserve
species.
</P>
<P>
   While the use of habitat planning has grown, the concept is
still vulnerable to being overturned by the courts that may
interpret it as not effectively meeting the criteria demanded under
the Endangered Species Act. Babbitt, though, said that he no longer
fears a sustained and debilitating backlash against the act. He
pointed out that polls show ``overwhelming support'' for the act,
especially in areas that are undergoing urbanization.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really eager to preserve the values that drew the
growth in the first place,'' Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a tinge of gray in his brown hair and a deepening of the
lines in his face hint at the toll that 5{ years in Washington,
D.C., has taken. A quarter-century of politics has toughened him,
said Babbitt, who tries to deflect the attacks he gets _ from all
sides _ with practiced humor. He has even been razzed at the family
dinner table by his son, T.J., a Stanford University student, over
what is meant by ``managing'' wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``No good deed,'' Babbitt says, using one of his favorite
phrases, ``goes unpunished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
