<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TSAR-BURIAL _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Spot coverage of the
royal burial ceremony for Russia's Tsar Nicholas II and his family.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-COUPLES _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Cupid might not have to sneak
around Iran anymore. Young Iranians say they now encounter fewer
problems when they step out together in public. They see fewer
``Beseigi'' patrols, snatching young lovers out of parks and
restaurants for hours of questioning over suspected breaches of
Islamic modesty. They've even heard, through Iran's murky mix of
rumor and vague political pronouncements, that some government
officials want to relieve the pressure on the country's young.
Iranian youth say it's now all right to walk with a loved one as
long as you don't hold hands. Others know the parks, stores and
cinemas that are safe, as long as the rules don't change. ``It is
easier now,'' said Alex Petrosian, 28. ``But, if (a religious
leader) says something about it at Friday prayers, it's terrible
for the next couple weeks.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday, July 16, in both the (i) International and
( l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HOMOSEXUALITY _ WASHINGTON _ The Human Rights Campaign holds a
news conference where ``former ex-gays,'' including Candace
Gingrich and Newt Gingrich's cousin, Darrell, will ``refute the
claims that homosexuality can be changed and cite the damaging
effects on such efforts.'' (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   FARMS _ WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and other
House members hold a news conference to announce introduction of
emergency legislation to address the ``acute financial distress''
facing U.S. farm country. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HDTV _ WASHINGTON _ When the Federal Communications Commission
recently sought to frame the rules that will govern television in
the digital era that dawns this fall, it defied the rules on the
way regulatory business is usually done in Washington. In nearly
every case, the commission and Congress quietly decide the issues
beforehand. Only then do they put their views out for public
comment, which rarely produces much change during the final hearing
process. That's the way things worked in the 1960s, when the FCC
decided that all car radios had to carry FM stations. But when it
came time to consider whether cable TV operators should be required
to carry the digital signals of broadcasters, the commissioners and
the FCC staff observed strict neutrality. The agency's reluctance
to choose sides reflects a deep division between the interdependent
cable and broadcast industries on ``must carry,'' as the issue is
known in trade circles. (Glass, Cox News Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Wednesday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories and will be repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ MURPHY, N.C. _ Watching developments in the search for
Eric Rudolph, wanted in the fatal bombing of a Birmingham abortion
clinic and three bombings in Atlanta. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINIC-BOMBING _ WASHINGTON _ Emily Lyons, injured in the
bombing of an abortion clinic in Birmingham, Ala., testifies at a
House Judiciary subcommittee hearing that focuses on amending the
Racketeer-Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act in a way that it
might not apply to such bombings. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENTER-REBUKED _ GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Texas Department of Human
Services officials have reprimanded a Georgetown assisted-living
center for negligence after an 83-year-old resident who fell asleep
during a sightseeing outing was left in a parked bus for five hours
as the temperature reached 97 degrees. (Wishard, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
