<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABBITT-PREDECESSORS-     07-17 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-PREDECESSORS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Headquartered in a cavernous building at 18th and C streets in
Washington, D.C., the Department of the Interior has long been
considered the West's seat in the federal Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Its domain ranges from such conservation-oriented agencies as
the National Park Service and the Fish and Wildlife Service to the
historically development-minded Bureau of Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt's paneled office is a
wall with paintings of his predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them include:
</P>
<P>
   _Albert Fall, Interior secretary under Warren Harding from 1921
to 1923, who was convicted of bribery and served a year in prison.
Fall was a central figure in the Teapot Dome Scandal, in which
lucrative petroleum-bearing properties in California and Wyoming
were leased to oil barons Edward Doheney and Harry Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   _Harold Ickes, Interior secretary under Franklin D. Roosevelt,
who served from 1933 to 1946, the longest tenure in the job. He
also ran the U.S. Petroleum Administration during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Curmudgeon,'' as he was nicknamed, presided over vast
reclamation projects in the West as well as major expansion of the
national park system.
</P>
<P>
   _Stewart Udall, Interior secretary in the Kennedy and Johnson
administrations from 1961 to 1969, who championed Native American
rights and conservation. But, as an old Arizona politician, he
supported a bid by the Bureau of Reclamation to build two dams in
the Grand Canyon. That angered environmentalists. ``Would you flood
the Sistine Chapel so tourists could get closer to the ceiling?''
asked a famous Sierra Club newspaper ad. The proposed dams were
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Udall had arranged for Lyndon Johnson to proclaim a huge
national monument in Alaska's Brooks Range just before LBJ left
office in 1969. Using his own authority, however, the Interior
secretary renamed Washington, D.C.'s municipal stadium after
Johnson nemesis Robert F. Kennedy. An infuriated Johnson refused to
sign the monument papers.
</P>
<P>
   _Walter Hickel, Interior secretary under Richard Nixon from 1969
to 1970, who was a pro-development Alaska governor who went
``green'' in office. He championed creation of urban parks and
wrote a letter urging Nixon to be sympathetic and tolerant toward
student protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Hickel was fired for the letter, prompting political cartoonist
Pat Oliphant to show a bear running through the forest shouting,
``They got Wally!''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the Alaska statehouse, where he was surrounded by
lumber workers, miners and some of the country's most vociferous
old-style boosters. There, as governor from 1991 to 1995, Hickel
tried to build roads across national parks and wildlife refuges.
``We can't just let nature run wild,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   _Cecil Andrus, Interior secretary under Jimmy Carter from 1977
to 1981, who is responsible for perhaps the department's greatest
achievement of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Using gentle persuasion and hard-ball politics, Andrus persuaded
Congress to set aside 103 million acres of Alaska as new national
parks, wildlife refuges, wilderness areas, monuments, and wild and
scenic rivers. The Alaska Lands Act more than doubled the national
park system.
</P>
<P>
   _James Watt, Interior secretary under Ronald Reagan from 1981 to
1983, who caused an uproar by trying to expand oil and mineral
exploration into wilderness lands. ``I don't like to paddle, and I
don't like to walk,'' Watt said in a famous speech to national park
concessionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups had a field day with Watt until he made an
offensive remark about blacks, women, Jews and the disabled. That
remark created a national uproar and led to Watt's resignation. The
Sierra Club had 179,000 members when Watt became Interior
secretary. It had 350,000 by the time he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   _Manuel Lujan, Interior secretary under George Bush from 1989 to
1993, who was a New Mexico congressman pressed into service after
Western Republican politicians vetoed GOP Sen. Dan Evans of
Washington as too much of a conservationist.
</P>
<P>
   Lujan had a low profile and took a hands-off management style to
the agency. He was surprised in 1990 one morning when he picked up
his Sunday New York Times to discover a front-page story about how
Olympic National Park managers and other Interior officials were
pressing for removal of two dams from the Elwha River. This was the
first Lujan had heard of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
