<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SEATTLE-DUCKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADDLE YOU KNOW? DUCKS MAKE A SPLASH ON SEATTLE TOUR SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle has long had guided tours in its downtown
streets and tour boats in Lake Union, but a new venture will do
both in the same trip.
</P>
<P>
   Using reconstructed World War II-era Army amphibious vehicles,
the tour company will offer 90-minute land and water tours of the
city that include a street excursion through downtown from the
Seattle Center to Safeco Field, the future home of the Seattle
Mariners, an amphibious excursion into Lake Union, and a side trip
through the Fremont neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, ``Ride the Ducks Land and Lake Tour,'' operates two
former Army amphibious trucks _ known by their wartime acronym of
``DUKW,'' said Brian Tracey, a co-owner of the operation with Tom
Ismon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a rusted out bucket to start with,'' Tracey said
as he climbed up the rear gangway ladder into the passenger area.
While the wartime vehicles were essentially floating cargo trucks,
the redone versions have been heavily modified for the convenience
of passengers. Features include comfortable seats, a solid canopy
roof, roll-up windows and interior heating.
</P>
<P>
   Each vehicle is operated by a ``captain'' who must both be
qualified as a passenger coach operator by the state Department of
Licensing and also hold a master's certificate from the Coast
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Blackburn, a captain of boats used in the Gulf of Mexico,
is one of the Seattle duck drivers. ``I went from commanding a
230-foot-ship to driving a 40-foot duck,'' he said with a laugh.
``Why? Because this is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   A captain has to be articulate and entertaining. He provides the
commentary as the ungainly duck vehicle trundles down the city's
streets.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent test hop, one passenger asked Blackburn for the
difference between the tour duck and its wartime counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original DUKW had bullets whizzing overhead,'' he drawled.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn spent as much effort cajoling passengers to quack like
ducks on cue and accosting pedestrians and other drivers with
wisecracks to make them smile, as he did wrestling the 40-foot
vehicle through the city's packed streets.
</P>
<P>
   The original concept for the DUKW was borne out of wartime
necessity, Tracey said.
</P>
<P>
   During the early months of World War II Army planners
contemplated the problems of moving and sustaining military forces
across an amphibious beachhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of amphibious assaults was basically a dismal tale
of defeats and stalemates,'' wrote military historian Geoffrey
Perret in his account of the Army in World War II, ``There's a War
to Be Won.'' ``No one had ever mastered it.''
</P>
<P>
   An early attempt to create a floatable version of the Army jeep
failed because it had ``the amphibious qualities of a safe,''
Perret wrote. But a naval architect named Rod Stephens came up with
a modified design of the Army's 2{-ton truck.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyancy was provided by giving the truck a body of sealed,
empty tanks, with a pair of small propellers to provide forward
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's faster in water than any truck,'' Stephens said, ``and
she'll beat any boat on a highway!''
</P>
<P>
   Perret concludes the DUKW was one of the five most important
pieces of equipment fielded in World War II that helped assure
allied victory (the others were the bulldozer, the jeep, the 2{-ton
truck and the C-47 transport plane).
</P>
<P>
   More than 21,000 DUKWs were built during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the 90-minute Seattle-area tour takes place at
a city boat ramp near Gas Works Park on Lake Union. After a sprint
from downtown, Blackburn slowly eased the DUKW down the boat ramp
into the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a lever, he switched the transmission from the
vehicle's tires to a small propeller mounted underneath the hull,
and the DUKW motored out across the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wonder if this thing is gonna float or not,'' he
announced to several dozen guest riders.
</P>
<P>
   They loudly quacked back.
</P>
<P>
   Tours will depart every hour between 10 a.m. and 7 p.m. from the
``Ride the Ducks'' ticket stand at the corner of 5th Avenue and
Broad Street near the Space Needle. Tickets are available from a
kiosk at the Space Needle across from the Monorail terminus. Prices
are $20 for adults and $15 for children under 12 years. The
operation will continue daily through Sept. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
