<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PR CRISIS EXPERT KNOWS ABOUT JUMPING TO CONCLUSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago a guy walked into an El Torito restaurant in
Orange, Calif., and while munching into his taco, bit off the head
of a frog.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he said.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a story with legs. David Letterman said it was the
slimiest thing served in the restaurant since O.J. Simpson's
defense team had eaten lunch there. Jay Leno said he planned to try
the chain's new Kermit Taco Supreme. The story leap-frogged from
one media outlet to the next across the country.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of public relations creature from the black
lagoon that can give corporate executives nightmares, and can even
bring down an organization.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Michael Sitrick comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Sitrick is a miracle worker for corporations in crisis. He's a
spin doctor, the guy who makes the bad story disappear.
</P>
<P>
   When a company is facing bankruptcy, a scandal or a lawsuit,
they often call Sitrick, who has finessed such high-profile PR
crises as the Food Lion debacle or the bankruptcy of Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what one might expect, he doesn't do it by lying or
evading the truth. His strategic moves present the facts of the
matter from a different point of view _ his client's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really good spin is anything but dishonest,'' he said. ``You
present the facts in such a way _ they are so compelling _ that the
story has to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like being a trial lawyer, he said. ``Everyone is entitled
to a PR defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Sitrick, whose firm Sitrick and Company is based in Los
Angeles, has put what he knows about crisis public relations into a
book, ``Spin, How to Turn the Power of the Press to Your
Advantage'' (Regnery, 1998, $24.95.) It's intended as a how-to book
for companies needing to defuse potential public relations blowups,
but for anyone _ journalists and consumers alike _ it's an
entertaining account of the ways we are manipulated, by both sides,
in any budding controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Sitrick relishes a good fight.
</P>
<P>
   In the Food Lion case, the company's reputation smelled worse
than the tainted food it had been accused of selling in a PrimeTime
Live news show.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company eventually won its case against the
reporters for using false pretenses, it had already lost in the
court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   That is until Sitrick saw raw footage from video shot by ABC's
undercover reporters. The outtakes told a different, often
contradictory story. In one case, for example, the television
broadcast showed an employee complaining about chicken that didn't
smell right. It didn't include the rest of the tape, which showed
her being instructed to throw out the suspect poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Using those kinds of examples, Sitrick was able to shift the
battle from the issue of whether investigative journalism is in the
public interest, no matter what the means, to an issue of honesty
and journalistic integrity. He won.
</P>
<P>
   There are several simple rules of spin, Sitrick said. But
there's only one unbreakable one: Always tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Sitrick has fired clients for lack of ethics and refuses to take
any who won't give him total access to their operations. Former
reporters investigate each case before he takes it.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond telling the truth, there are some other secrets to
getting a company's side of the story out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake companies make (in a crisis) is not
talking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if they don't tell their side of the story, someone else
will _ with a different spin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect reporters to take the corporate version at face
value, however. A company's word isn't enough, he said. Give them
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   If a company has actually done something wrong and is in
trouble, it should own up to the problem and focus on whatever
steps it is taking to ensure the situation can't happen again, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The whole art of spin is not to change the facts of the matter,
but to put them in a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the frog?
</P>
<P>
   In the El Torito case, it turns out that frog forensics revealed
no teeth marks matching those of the man who claimed to have bitten
it. In fact, the head was still attached.
</P>
<P>
   Sitrick's team also discovered the alleged frog biter had filed
for bankruptcy, been convicted of credit-card fraud, and once told
a girlfriend about a get-rich scheme involving planting a frog in a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   That put a whole new spin on the man-bites-frog story that had
threatened to destroy El Torito's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, the story croaked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
