<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PLANE!' RESUMES FLIGHT ON ABC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ ABC hopes to climb out of its ratings funk
this fall with the help of a little sports and a little fantasy.
More specifically: ``Sports Night'' and _ don't laugh _ ``Fantasy
Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers may be surprised that ``Sports Night,'' though scheduled
after ``Spin City'' on Tuesday nights, is not your everyday
half-hour comedy. And the new ``Fantasy Island,'' while faithful to
the Aaron Spelling original in many ways, is intended to be more
than a nightlight for the rec room.
</P>
<P>
   The team behind ``Fantasy Island'' has quite the pedigree. It
includes acclaimed movie director Barry Sonnenfeld (``Men in
Black,'' ``Get Shorty'') and his partner, longtime film producer
Barry Josephson, as well as the multi-honored Diane Frolov and
Andrew Schneider, who spent five years keeping ``Northern
Exposure'' from going south.
</P>
<P>
   If adjectives like ``dark,'' ``quirky'' and ``edgy'' come to
mind when contemplating those names, bingo. This is not your
father's ``Fantasy Island.'' With the iconoclastic Malcolm McDowell
in the role of Mr. Roarke, the mysterious island where people go to
fulfill their fantasies may seem more like Club Dread than Club
Med.
</P>
<P>
   Josephson is polite in comparing the new ``Fantasy Island'' with
the old. But he admits it won't be the same. (For one thing, it
will be shot in Hawaii, not Burbank.) ``I don't think we're shying
away from the old show,'' he told critics in Pasadena this week.
``I just think we're a different show (with) different characters
and different stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so coincidentally, ``Sports Night'' also has a link to the
movies. Its creator is Aaron Sorkin, the man behind the screenplays
of ``A Few Good Men'' and ``The American President.'' To produce
the show, Sorkin hooked up with Ron Howard's Imagine Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' is a half-hour series that doesn't follow the
usual sitcom format of setup, punch line, setup, punch line. More
in the tradition of ``MASH,'' it tells a story that may be funny
and poignant at the same time _ and there's a chance it'll run
without a laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Larry Sanders'' sort of way, the series goes behind the
scenes of a cable-TV sports show not unlike ESPN's
``SportsCenter.'' Peter Krause and Josh Charles play two anchors
who are not Ted Baxter buffoons, but serious professionals whose
lives are not all fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the mix of comedy and drama is catching everybody's
attention,'' Sorkin said. ``The truth is, I don't really do either
one of them enough to only do one of them. My fastball isn't fast
enough and my curveball doesn't break enough. If I'm going to get
the batter out, I'm going to have to mix up the pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Christian, the ``Good Morning America'' weather
forecaster these past 12 years, will depart the show in January and
join KGO-TV in San Francisco, an ABC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News president David Westin said Christian's successor has
not been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Christian will be the last of the old guard to leave ``GMA,''
whose overhaul Westin has made a top priority in a bid to regain
some of the audience the once-mighty morning show has lost to NBC's
``Today'' program. Lisa McRee replaced Joan Lunden as co-host last
September, and Kevin Newman claimed Charles Gibson's co-host chair
in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
