</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ The chief justice refuses to stay
Kenneth Starr's subpoena of Secret Service agents to testify before
the grand jury; other developments.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COCKELL (Washington) _ A look at Larry L. Cockell,
Clinton's lead protective agent. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-HEARING (Washington) _ The Nuclear Regulatory Commission,
under attack from Congress and utility industry for being too
tough, holds a daylong session to hear criticism from nuclear
industry and support from anti-nukes. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   UAL-LABOR (Undated) _ Federal officials will announce results
this afternoon in what could be labor's largest organizing victory
in the private sector in decades: the International Association of
Machinists is seeking to organize 19,000 reservations agents and
other passenger service workers at United Airlines. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-ELECT (Undated) _ Federal officials will announce
whether they have the $8.6 million to assure federal supervision of
the teamsters election. If not, the election might go unsupervised.
By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-UNION (New Orleans) _ At the American Federation of
Teachers convention with Sandra Feldman speaking.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMES-TRIBUNAL (Rome) _ Negotiations over establishing the
world's first permanent war crimes tribunal go down to the wire. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CZAR (St. Petersburg) _ Russia buries Czar Nicholas II in
true imperial fashion. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Parliament continues debating measures to
resolve the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ELECT (Prek Tnaut, Cambodia) _ Whether the election
scheduled for July 26 will certify Cambodia's arrival as a mature
democracy _ a claim the country's leaders and weary reform
advocates in Europe and Asia are eager to make _ is a matter of
grave doubt in the country. Cambodian intellectuals, human rights
monitors, foreign aid workers and some diplomats say Hun Sen's
party has so intimidated the electorate, and so thoroughly controls
the election levers, that no opposition group stands a fair chance
of dislodging him. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS (United Nations) _ In the first public hint that
Iraq's hopes for an early lifting of sanctions have been set back
by discoveries of nerve gas in Iraqi warheads, Saddam Hussein says
in a speech the embargo was more likely to crumble over time. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-FRANCE (Paris) _ Syrian President Assad completes talks
with French leaders without giving any public signal of change in
the impasse over Israel's hold on the Golan Heights. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires) _ Peronists hold their
convention: They might give President Menem the nod for re-election
and the party could split. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Pressure mounts on the Nigerian
military leader to commit himself on transition to democracy after
his speech is repeatedly delayed. He seems ready to anger
opposition groups by keeping army in place until elections are
held, without having a civilian government organize the polls. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   MANDELA-BIRTHDAY (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ If you were a
man who had grown up in a tiny village in rural South Africa, spent
27 years in jail for your political beliefs, and succeeded in
changing the course of history, what would you ask for on your 80th
birthday? A bride? Newspapers across this country are betting that
that's just what President Nelson Mandela will get on Saturday when
his schedule says that he is spending his 80th birthday at home
with his family in the northern Johannesburg suburb of Houghton. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-PROSTITUTES (New York) _ The police say more than 20
officers may be involved in a scandal in Manhattan's Midtown South
precinct in which they are accused of receiving sexual favors from
prostitutes in return for lax enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-PRECINCT (New York) _ How the problem was allowed to
fester in the precinct.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-NEIGHBORHOOD (New York) _ Fallout in the neighborhood,
long known as ``Hell's Kitchen,'' which has a long history of
coping with a booming sex industry. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-WOMAN-CUSTODY (Miami) _ A judge's ruling that a divorced
woman could not gain primary custody of her children because of her
long work hours provides a cautionary tale for parents who try to
balance child-rearing with professional ambition, and also for
professional firms that try to run profitable practices while
accommodating employees who want to spend more time at home.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ Reflecting the Asian economic crisis,
the trade deficit in goods and services widened 10 percent in May,
to a record $15.75 billion from $14.28 billion in April. Exports
fell 1.3 percent, while imports rose half a percent. The trade
report was the latest evidence that the economy's growth slowed
substantially in the second quarter. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-NORTHROP (Undated) _ More about the failed Lockheed
Martin-Northrop deal.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Developments in the General Motors
strike. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE-CLINTON (Washington) _ With neither General Motors nor
the United Auto Workers asking for intervention, the President is
quite happy to ignore the strike against the biggest auto company.
By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Beijing) _ China's economy grew at an annual rate of
7 percent in the first half, down from 8.8 percent last year and
the slowest pace in seven years, casting doubt on Beijing's plans
to reform money-losing sate enterprises. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was down 6 points at 1:50 p.m.
</P>
