influential Russian Orthodox Church Abroad. That church, a branch
established by Russian exiles following the revolution, already has
conferred sainthood on Nicholas II and tenaciously has refused to
accept the remains in Russia as those of the last czar.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a sense of tradition and dignity punctuated the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The robed and bearded priest, assisted by deacons, chanted the
burial ritual as incense wafted through the 18th-century cathedral
and a choir sang. The rites culminated with a thrice-repeated
prayer asking ``eternal remembrance'' for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the cathedral along the banks of the Neva River, cannon
thundered a 19-gun salute _ two shy of the traditional 21, since
the burial was not formally recognized as that of the czar.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the coffins were lowered into a crypt in the floor.
Nicholas II was the last to descend, his coffin topped with his
sword and scabbard.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives, some weeping, then paraded past, each scooping up a
handful of white sand, representing earth, to toss into the grave,
a ritual that serves as a final farewell common to the Russian
Orthodox and other Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One branch of the Romanov clan was notably absent, the family of
17-year-old Prince Georgy, living in Spain, a leading aspirant to
the throne, should it ever be restored. He, his mother and other
family members attended a rival service at a monastery near Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The service in St. Petersburg was limited to dignitaries and
Romanov relatives, but was available to millions of Russians via
live television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this burial will change our lives here in
Russia,'' said Valery Gavrilov, manager of a wine shop in St.
Petersburg. ``But from the point of view of history, this was the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The family, like Yeltsin, placed the emphasis on Russian unity
and an attempt in the long-overdue burial to allay lingering doubts
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time people will recognize and understand what we've done
today,'' said Nikolai Romanov, 76, a distant cousin of Nicholas II
who is widely regarded as current head of the dynasty. ``It will
take time to bury the rest of the horrors of the past 80 years. But
once we do, we will all be freer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's attendance _ he stopped in St. Petersburg while en
route to a vacation in the nearby Karelia forest _ was praised by
the family, most of whom live outside Russia, as a constructive
gesture and ultimately good for Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably the only Romanov ever democratically elected to
public office and I'm speaking as a politician now. With an event
of this importance, for the chief of state not to have been here
would have been a public relations tragedy,'' said Paul Ilyinsky,
the mayor of Palm Beach, Fla., and son of a cousin of Nicholas II.
</P>
<P>
   Taking their cue earlier from the church and Yeltsin's original
decision to avoid the service, other high-ranking Russian
politicians decided to stay away. Their reluctance to attended
underscored the uncertain implications of an ornate royal burial at
a time when most Russians are suffering amid the country's economic
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The government scaled back original plans for the event and
spent less than $1 million on the three-day observance, which began
Wednesday in Yekaterinburg, the city where Nicholas and his family
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   But the more modest ceremony, without the accompanying hype of
world leaders in attendance and Russian politicians elbowing for
the limelight, served to make the funeral what a funeral should be:
a dignified family affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, this was unfinished family business,'' said Rostislav
Romanov, a British banker and leading member of the clan. ``Those
people deserved a proper Christian burial and they got it today.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
