<HEADER>
A0278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURVEILLANCE-CAMERAS-     07-17 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVEILLANCE-CAMERAS-$ADV19-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERAS GO UNDERCOVER TO STOP THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on
Sunday, July 19.) (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When private investigators David Hutchinson and
George Sexton were hired by a local bar owner who suspected he was
being ripped off at the till by a bartender, they needed a new
tool.
</P>
<P>
   A standard still camera with a telephoto lens would be too
obvious. Ditto for a video camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   Even going undercover themselves night after night in the bar
was no good because they might be distracted or their view blocked
at a crucial moment.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson and Sexton instead opted to install a security
surveillance system at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   A video camera the size of a matchbox with a wide-angle lens was
concealed behind an opening no bigger than a pin hole.
</P>
<P>
   The camera was mounted behind a framed liquor ad above the cash
register, with wires snaked through a hole drilled in the wall. The
wires plugged into a videocassette recorder hidden in a case of
potato chip bags among a pile of supplies in a storage area behind
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender was caught on camera skimming off the top,
bypassing the cash register with wads of cash he stashed in a
secret cannister hidden in a tabletop.
</P>
<P>
   After seven days of clandestine recording, in which the
bartender was recorded stealing on more than one occasion, the
evidence was incontrovertible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner was shocked. This was a trusted, longtime
employee,'' Hutchinson said. ``The owner didn't want to believe it,
but the evidence was there in living color.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A picture is worth a thousand words,'' Sexton said.
</P>
<P>
   The bar rip-off could amount to hundreds of dollars on a busy
night, potentially tens of thousands of dollars of cash skimmed off
in the course of a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender was fired and the stealing ceased. By contrast,
the cost of seven days of surveillance was $700. ``We think it's a
good investment,'' said Sexton.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton and Hutchinson, state-licensed private investigators,
both of Clifton Park, N.Y., recently formed Hidden Eyes, a company
that rents, installs and monitors security surveillance systems.
</P>
<P>
   The two P.I.s hooked up in 1990 during the Greyhound bus strike
in Albany. Sexton was hired for security by the company. Hutchinson
was videotaping the strikers for Greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   In local newspaper ads run last month, Hidden Eyes touts its
miniature cameras for home or office to monitor spouses, baby
sitters, children, employees and contractors.
</P>
<P>
   While several businesses like the bar have used the Hidden Eyes
service, the home market has proved a tougher sell. For instance, a
local woman who discussed contracting for a hidden camera in her
teenage son's room because she suspected he was using drugs behind
closed doors eventually backed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are reluctant to bug their own homes,'' Hutchinson
said. ``We're having a hard time cracking into residential
applications. I think deep down people don't want to see what they
suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   In the brave new world of surveillance technology where people
are increasingly under surveillance where they work, where they
shop, where they drive and where they pass through public buildings
the final frontier of one's own home, a supposed sanctum sanctorum,
has been breached.
</P>
<P>
   ``By putting these surveillance cameras in the home, it does
seem to cross another line many of us thought should not be
crossed,'' said Bob Cohen, executive director of the Albany chapter
of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``We're very concerned about
the not-so-creeping losses to our freedom day by day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say eavesdropping on spouses or children in the
family home is a quantum leap against personal privacy, to say
nothing of a breakdown in fundamental social discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are parents teaching their children when they don't trust
them enough so they bug their rooms?'' asked Evan Hendricks, editor
and publisher of Privacy Times, a biweekly newsletter based in
Washington, D.C., that reports on erosions of privacy. ``There's
something terribly wrong with society if we fall back on gadgets to
solve human problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such use of surveillance cameras in private homes when
authorized by a resident or owner of the home is not illegal, the
issue raises a deeper moral and ethical quandary. Just because the
technology exists, is it right to use it?
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider this doing something bad or evil,'' said
Hutchinson, 45, a former probation supervisor for Albany County,
who became a licensed private investigator in 1984 and formed
Hutchinson Investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the tables were turned, if Hutchinson was being
spied upon rather than the one doing the spying? ``If my wife
wanted to bug me, of course I wouldn't like it,'' Hutchinson
admitted. ``It's an intrusion and it would make me uncomfortable.
But this is legal, people want our service and all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Posing the same question to Sexton made the 50-year-old former
U.S. Army military police officer and licensed private investigator
for the past 11 years squirm as well. ``I wouldn't like it if it
was used on me,'' Sexton said. ``But we're doing it with permission
of the person who owns the house. I agree it's on the boundary of
being intrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson and Sexton consult with attorneys, who often refer
clients to them, prior to installing the hidden cameras. Clients
must then sign a contract. The rate for Hidden Eyes is $100 per day
for video surveillance and an additional $100 per day for audio
surveillance. That includes set-up, review and writing a report.
</P>
<P>
   The hourly fee for the private investigators for on-site human
surveillance is $50 per hour, plus mileage and expenses. It's $100
per hour for both Hutchinson and Sexton to work a case.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny cameras can be hidden almost anywhere in a private
home. Once, they stuck the camera behind living-room draperies. In
another local house, where the homeowners wanted to observe a baby
sitter, a book was hollowed out and the camera recorded through a
hole cut in the cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book sat right on a bookshelf in the living room and the
books were very dusty, so we knew they were for show and not for
reading,'' Sexton said.
</P>
<P>
   Many hours of videotape were reviewed from this ``nannycam,''
but no abuse or neglect was observed. The parents considered it a
sound investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave them peace of mind,'' Hutchinson said. ``We think
that's what this technology can offer the homeowner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The apocalyptic celluloid vision of the recent movie ``The
Truman Show'' in which Truman Burbank (played by Jim Carrey),
unbeknownst to him, has every move of his life recorded secretly by
scores of video cameras for broadcast to an audience of millions
suddenly seems not so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   That movie and other recent developments such as the explosion
of navel-gazing Internet offerings (the infamous ``JenniCam,''
``HamsterCam,'' ``CatCam'' and scores of other live cameras that
beam the minutiae of mundane lives into cyberspace) is troubling on
many levels to those who take the pulse of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it so sad that people think their lives are not
important or complex or interesting enough to protect them from
public view,'' said Robert Ellis Smith, publisher and editor of
Privacy Journal, a monthly newsletter based in Providence, R.I.
``That whole live Internet camera trend leaves nothing to be
intimate about with your spouse or partner, trusted friends and
confidantes.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer and journalist, Smith formed his monthly newsletter in
1974 and has built it up to an estimated readership of 20,000
people. It reports on new technology and the impact on privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said technology marches on, making eavesdropping equipment
cheaper and smaller. Once the sole domain of government officials
and large corporations, cameras that fit in ballpoint pens or tie
clips and portable camcorder units in briefcases are available in
mail-order catalogs at accessible prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electronic surveillance has become democratized in this
country,'' Smith said. ``It's available to anyone now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
