<HEADER>
A0289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZORRO-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      07-17 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZORRO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZORRO': DUELING DERRING-DUO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No car chases. No gargantuan guns. No spaceships. No asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue from the swashbuckling movies of the '30s and
'40s, ``The Mask of Zorro'' is a refreshingly low-tech action film
whose frontier California setting doesn't keep it from generating a
rousing sense of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Director Martin Campbell, who steered the spy-guy ``GoldenEye''
toward massive profits, must have seen this traditional western as
a challenge, not a handicap, given today's gaudy and gimmicky
action-movie market.
</P>
<P>
   If necessity is the mother of invention, then imagination is its
other offspring, and ``The Mask of Zorro'' ripples with both.
</P>
<P>
   Blending classical derring-do with today's state of the art in
stunts and on-camera effects, this zealous picture jumps through
hoops to entertain. Indeed, it sports ample dazzle even for today's
overstimulated audiences, who are so overly conditioned by the
loony literalism of bizarre computer-generated effects.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the witless sensory overkill of today's dominant action
films, ``The Mask of Zorro'' is both spirited and friendly, and its
sentiments have more honesty than hokum.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing mayhem with strong doses of humor, romance, tragedy and
personality, it delivers an epic-scaled story whose
larger-than-life heroism is offset by accessible humanity.
</P>
<P>
   This owes in large part to two ideally-cast stars playing Zorro
at two stages: Antonio Banderas and Anthony Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins first bursts from the gate as the masked, black-garbed
Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Douglas Fairbanks a half-century ago _ and belying his
age of 60 _ Hopkins dashes through an opening scene in which the
masked hero halts an execution and flamboyantly defies soldiers who
keep early 1800s California in the grip of Spanish tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so he befriends two peasant boys, including Alejandro,
Banderas' character as a lad.
</P>
<P>
   After Don Diego (Zorro) is imprisoned, the film jump-cuts 20
years later, when Alejandro is a scrappy, scruffy rogue with his
own reasons to hate Spain's monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   When Don Diego finally escapes, Alejandro comes under his wing
and learns the ways of the sword so he can take up the torch of
Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   In a richly complicated subplot, he's also smitten by the fiery
Elena, played by Catherine Zeta-Jones. She is Don Diego's daughter
_ yet doesn't know it. She had been stolen from him as a baby and
raised by his enemy, the power-mad Don Rafael (Stuart Wilson).
</P>
<P>
   Don Rafael isn't the best of villains. Grasping for land, gold
and social status, he's more dandy than devil. He also relies too
much on an American mercenary, played by Matt Letscher with an eye
toward Gen. George Custer's arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they're hardly a match for the young or old Zorro.
Then again, they have an army on their side.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a classic clash, the film maintains an eventful
momentum _ but only to a point.
</P>
<P>
   Like many movies today, ``The Mask of Zorro'' is too long. It's
not as bloated as the 2{-hour ``Armageddon,'' but its 136 minutes
still misses ``leave 'em laughing'' status.
</P>
<P>
   It's also too grim at times. A scene with a decapitated head is
a grisly jolt, and by story's end the action veers too much toward
bloodshed and away from dashing style.
</P>
<P>
   But on the whole, it works.
</P>
<P>
   Banderas adds self-effacing charm and sly charisma to the stout
heroism for which Zorro is known, and Hopkins has more weight,
command and dignity than any glorified action potboiler deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Zeta-Jones also shows promise as a heroine who can hold her own
in a sword fight, and the James Horner score is richly romantic.
</P>
<P>
   Whether all this will fly is perhaps the summer's biggest movie
question.
</P>
<P>
   Low-tech, retro heroes such as the Phantom haven't fared well of
late, and the similarly nonsuperheroic Batman _ who Bob Kane
created in Zorro's image _ has fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   But one encouraging fact remains: Even if the world isn't ready
again for Zorro, Zorro is ready for the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
