<P>
   ANTHONY-STANTON (Undated) _ It wasn't until three years after
the first women's rights convention at Seneca Falls, N.Y., in 1848
that Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton met. Yet the
partnership they formed blossomed into an independent women's
rights movement that would eventually win women the right to vote
and set the foundation for 20th-century feminism's critique of
American society. Throughout their decades-long friendship, the two
women maintained an intense and fascinating correspondance. The New
York Times asked three writers to respond to excerpts from a letter
Anthony wrote more than 140 years ago. Anthony's letter to Stanton
describes a debate Anthony had with the spiritualist and reformer
Andrew Jackson Davis over the differences between men and women. By
Patricia Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY-TEXT (Undated) _ Excerpts from Anthony's letter to
Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY-MARGULIS (Undated) _ Lynn Margulis, a microbiologist,
responds to the Anthony letter.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY-PATTERSON (Undated) _ Dorothy Patterson, Southern Bapist
who believes women should ``submit graciously'' to their husbands,
responds.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY-POLLITT (Undated) _ Katha Pollitt, feminist author,
responds.
</P>
<P>
   SLAVERY-BOOK (Undated) _ For many people today, thinking about
slavery in America conjures up the image of bent black backs
toiling on enormous cotton plantations patrolled by whip-cracking
overseers. But in ``Many Thousands Gone: The First Two Centuries of
Slavery in North America,'' to be published by Harvard University
Press in September, Professor Ira Berlin of the University of
Maryland says the actual picture is much more varied and complex.
Billed as the first comprehensive account of American slavery,
Berlin's book is causing a buzz among scholars. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other culture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CROCODILES-THEATER-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Street of
Crocodiles,'' part of the Lincoln Center Festival. Reviewed by Ben
Brantley.
</P>
