<DOCNO> NYT19980717.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0295 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUFFALO66-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      07-17 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO66-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUFFALO 66' A DARK AND PAINFUL COMEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few movies deserve the label black comedy as much as ``Buffalo
66.''
</P>
<P>
   Few dramas are as depressing as this movie. But the film just
stays in your mind _ so how many mainstream movies have done that
lately? _ growing funnier and more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a tour de force by actor Vincent Gallo, who stars,
wrote, directed and even composed the often intriguing soundtrack.
His worldview, if indicated by this movie, seems to be that a nice,
big lump of coal in your stocking at Christmas is more than anyone
has a right to expect.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a well-disguised vein of sentimentality is
the only explanation for the harsh ain't-life-mean-to-me tone of
much of ``Buffalo 66,'' and for a gimmick ending that offers some
hope of a kind of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo plays Billy Brown, named, apparently, for the Buffalo
Bills, the hometown football team that means more to his mom than
Billy does. (He was born in Buffalo in '66; hence the title.)
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with Billy being released from prison. If we
didn't suspect Billy was one of life's losers from his greasy hairy
and cat-in-the-headlights look, we figure it out when he asks if he
can get back inside to go to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   For what seems like hours on a cold Sunday morning, Billy
searches Buffalo desperately and unsuccessfully for a place to find
relief. When he finally gets into a men's room, he becomes
inhibited because he thinks some guy is watching him. Billy (Gallo
has said) is filled with shame over his imperfections, real and
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of his search for comfort, Billy takes time out to
panhandle phone change off Layla (Christina Ricci), a waifish dance
student with bad makeup, and calls his folks to say he's coming
home for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   When Billy went to prison, he told his parents he was leaving
town on business. He sent them postcards saying he's happily
married and doing well in another town.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to impress his folks, Billy grabs Layla and forces her
to go with him to his parents' house. She is supposed to make him
look good by saying she's his loving wife, though she looks more
like his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Layla offers only mild resistance, then passive acceptance and
finally enthusiastic support, leading us to question her own
strange psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's parents, played with painful disinterest by Anjelica
Huston and Ben Gazzara, indicate with every word that they hardly
realized Billy was gone for five years, and don't care that he's
back. The visit home is funny, but excruciating.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's mother serves him chocolate. He reminds her that he's
extremely allergic to chocolate. She insists repeatedly that he
always loved chocolate. A little home movie pops into a corner of
the screen, showing baby Billy, his face covered with chocolate and
hideously swollen.
</P>
<P>
   Billy has two other items on his first-day-out agenda. One is to
go bowling _ it was the one thing he ever did well.
</P>
<P>
   The other is to kill the Buffalo field goal kicker whom Billy
blames for his prison term. Billy, no bright light, got into
betting big money on sports. Even dumber, he bet his heart instead
of the odds. He lost.
</P>
<P>
   When he couldn't pay off, Billy's bookie (Mickey Rourke in a
cameo) gave Billy an option: get his legs broken or go to prison in
place of one of the bookie's pals. Billy had to plead guilty to the
crime, and do the time.
</P>
<P>
   Dark and gritty doesn't begin to describe the look and feel of
``Buffalo 66''. From the grainy film to the harsh lighting (no
doubt intentional) to the seamy locations, Gallo drags us through
Downertown.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, who has been in numerous independent films, clearly has
talent, coupled with a dead-earnest attitude. The film takes itself
very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a little surprising and disappointing that the twist
ending undercuts the film's harshness with a dim ray of hope. (On
the other hand, what little bit of sympathy we develop for Billy
gladly grasps at that hope.)
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, who is suddenly competing with Parker Posey as
independent film's leading leading lady, has always shown talent,
since the ``Addams Family'' films. Her performance here is nowhere
as fun as her deliciously wicked bad girl in ``The Opposite of
Sex,'' but it is more real and pathetically poignant and perfectly
in tune with what Gallo is doing.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy is hugely understated. Many people will not find
anything funny about it at all. Even if you laugh, you may find it
painful. And slow.
</P>
<P>
   Try to see this movie on a weekend night, when there will be a
larger audience; it will play much funnier with a crowd, especially
if the crowd views itself as hip and cynical.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna Arquette and Jan-Michael Vincent have small roles.
</P>
<P>
   The film is unrated. It has no nudity, but one bizarre shot of
graphic violence.
</P>
<P>
   And a bad attitude. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-17-98 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
