<HEADLINE>
LATEST AUDI GIVES BENZ WAGON A RUN FOR THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Audi is making a strong bid to regain its place in the American
market sunshine, and its latest offering looks like a challenge to
Mercedes-Benz. The 1999 Audi Avant is an all-wheel drive luxury
station wagon that bids to equal at least, perhaps surpass, the
Benz AWD 320E wagon in performance, and undercut it in price by
more than $10,000. To make the point, Audi wheeled its new wagon
into Boston to show it off to the New England Motor Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Avant is the A6 with a wagon body offering versatile
seating/ cargo arrangements and an interior generously trimmed in
wood. Audi does not speak of interior trim so much as of
``atmospheres,'' interior styling arangements on different mood
themes using different woods, varying colors and materials.
</P>
<P>
   The Avant is priced at $36,600 plus $600 delivery vs. $49,250
plus $595. The model shown in Boston came with a few options _
leather, Bose sound _ with a price tag just under $40,000, still a
significant challenge to Mercedes when you remember it's another
luxury German wagon with lots of room and all-wheel drive. Audi was
_ is _ the leader in AWD technology, offering a system that shifts
power between front and rear axles and from side to side on each
axle depending upon where the available traction lies. The only
problem with the Audi system is the overconfidence it may engender.
</P>
<P>
   The engine in the Avcant is 2.771-liter, 200-horsepower,
30-valve V-6 _ you read that right, 30-valve. Each cylinder has
three intake valves, two exhaust valves for maximum breathing
efficiency _ breathing in a gas engine is inhalation of fuel mix,
purging of exhaust from the cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   The transmission is a little different, a Tiptronic five-speed
automatic, just like the high-performance Porsche roadsters. With a
Tiptronic, you may opt for fully automatic gear changes or effect
lightning-fast shifts with the touch of a finger without letting go
of the wheel. Fuel mileage is expected to be around 20 miles per
gallon combined city/highway on average. So, what you have here is
performance car masquerading as a family wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The Avant is a knockout for looks, offers good room fore and aft
but comes with a couple of faults, in this columnist's view. For
openers, the roof rack on this wagon consists of a pair of stylish,
bright-metal rails sans crossbars or rubbing strakes. Cross rails
are optional, Audi explained. In addition, for some reason known
only to Audi, the radio antenna is mounted on the roof _ in the
middle just ahead of the rear hatch. So much for canoes on the roof
_ unless you care to remove the antenna and forgo radio reception,
a fairly easy option to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   A rear-facing child seat is available as an option. Picture the
family that sees the convenience in that trying to find a place for
the luggage that would have gone where the kids are sitting. The
whole arrangment is justified on the basis of `interior
convenience'' _ I see that _ and exterior style. Somehow I would
think the German engineers would be up to the challenge of
designing a rooftop on a wagon that was at once elegant and
supremely utile.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, the Avant retains the red dash illumination, a distinct
inconvenience, sometimes hazard, to the color-perception impaired.
But, the good news is that Audi does intend to change that; 2000
models will add white light but not dispense with the red
altogether. The change, Audi says, should accommodate the
color-impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the A6 winter performance, the Avant has got to be
dynamite in the white stuff. Winter has been conquered; now if only
Audi would pay a bit more attention to where we put the goods of
summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
