A0329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MATHIS-BOS &LR;      07-17 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MATHIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNNY MATHIS SAYS MODERATION KEEPS THE VOICE VELVET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Mathis &UR;  &LR; says he learned a lot about the virtues of
moderation _ both in food and his professional life _ from local
hero Julia Child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of hers,'' the velvet-voiced Mathis, 62, said on
the phone from his Hollywood home. ``I cook all my meals. I learned
from my Mom and Dad, who both cooked. Julia pooh-poohs
(eliminating) butter and fat and says that everything in moderation
is fine. A little of everything, she says, but not too much of
anything. The secret is in keeping the balance between doing what I
want to do and what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who love to sing want to be famous. They want
to be big stars,'' said Mathis, who started singing professionally
at 19. ``I don't. I'm shy. I like my life private. I have a
reticent personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Few performers have rivaled Mathis's professional popularity.
Almost 40 years passed between his first hit, in 1955, and his most
recent. ``I know I won't be able to leave here (Cohasset) without
doing some of them, like `Chances Are,' `Misty,' or `The Twelfth of
Never.' I'll do a medley from the Broadway show `Kismet.' I have an
orchestra, and when I'm not singing I like to make sure the music's
pretty. People like to hear the violin, the oboe, the French
horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis says over the years he's seen a lot of performers fritter
away good will with their excesses. ``There's a lot of money. There
are also the pitfalls, the drinks, the rich food. It's easy to
forget what brought you here. Some people want to be famous. Others
want to be good. You can do both. Look at Sinatra. I never met him,
never even shook hands with him, which is unusual in this business.
But I've read a lot of books on him and the only thing I've read
about how he cared for his voice is(chuckle) that five days before
a concert he'd stop drinking and smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Mathis, ``I smoked until I was 25 or 26. I drank wine
until then, not hard liquor. Five years ago I changed my diet
because I had a cholesterol problem. When you get older, you have
to start thinking about what you can get rid of.'' The singer says
he doesn't preach his lifestyle _ ``it's just what suits me.'' And
he concedes he's been lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My voice was high originally and then it matured and I've had
no problems vocally. I've also been lucky in that people have liked
the sound of my voice. It's pleasing to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the luck to have a dad who was a big influence. I had a
voice teacher when I was young that gave me lessons free in
exchange for doing chores and housework. I was lucky to be signed
by Columbia, which specialized in middle-of-the-road music, and
then in hooking up with Mitch Miller, who liked me but didn't like
the way I sang and taught me how to sing certain songs. Then I was
lucky enough to decide that this was what I was going to do. Also,
I kept up with my singing lessons. That was important. In the
beginning my teacher said my voice was very delicate and she taught
me how to utilize two of the muscles in it. The voice is like your
body. If you make it strong, there'll be no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis seems equally fastidious in his approach to performing.
He's on for 2 hours and 15 minutes. A signature of his appearances
is performing for 25 minutes before his opening act ``opens,'' a
practice he began years ago after attending a rock concert at Yale
Bowl in New Haven. A riot ensued after the headline act failed to
appear after several opening acts. ``I like to assure the audience
that I'm here,'' Mathis says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
