<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-35-HOUR-WEEK-HNS &LR;      07-17 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-35-HOUR-WEEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OF BERKELEY CONSIDERS A 35-HOUR WORK WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Voters in the Bay Area will decide in
November on a measure that would shorten the work week to 35 hours
and provide double-pay for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley city council voted to place the measure on the
November ballot after a small group of activists known as Share the
Work gathered 3,073 signatures from city residents in favor of the
initiative. The council had the option to approve the measure, but
decided to leave the controversial issue up to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Barish, spokeswoman for the California Federation of
Labor, said that she had not heard of any city that had legislated
a shorter work week than is mandated by the state. And there is
some question as to whether the initiative would hold up to legal
scrutiny if passed by voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first problem would be that the California Constitution
gives authority to regulate labor laws to the Industrial Welfare
Commission,'' said San Francisco labor lawyer Matthew Righetti.
``Any municipal decision is preempted by the commission, which has
set the work week at 40 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Righetti said that the commission is composed of citizens
appointed by the governor and the Legislature and meets
periodically to review and decide labor laws and policy.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley Mayor Shirley Dean and several council members
expressed concern that, if passed, the petition would hurt city
revenues and business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anyone on on the council who was in favor of this
measure,'' said council member Kriss Worthington. The measure
ignores the fact that most of the big businesses in the Bay Area
where employees work very long hours and overtime are outside of
Berkeley, he added.
</P>
<P>
   While Worthington said he is in favor of a shorter work week, he
believes the initiative is too harsh because it would deny a
business license to any employer who chose not to comply with the
35-hour restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progressive voters in Berkeley will not be deceived by an
illusory measure that is counterproductive and devisive,''
Worthington said. ``This (intiative) has two chances of passing _
slim and none.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative would require the same weekly pay for 35 hours as
workers received in September 1997 for 40 hours, and all overtime
work would be voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   A city staff report said city services would have to be reduced
by at least 12 percent to pay the increased city-employee overtime
estimated to be at least $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the amount of money (that the city would pay in
overtime and more workers) the cuts would happen all over,
including police and fire,'' said Phil Kamlarz, assistant city
manager. ``But we think people will vote against it once they know
the repercussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the initiative said that the shorter work week and
higher overtime rate will help reduce unemployment by creating a
need for more workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of people working 70 hours a week, let's give some
other people the work,'' said Crisley Bauer, who helped gather
signatures for the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Although unemployment is reported to be lower than it has been
in years _ about 3.5 percent in Berkeley _ Bauer said Share the
Work believes that there is more unemployment than is reported by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term temps are not counted as unemployed and people who
have been out of work for a long period are not counted either,''
Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley Chamber of Commerce is concerned that the measure
would hurt businesses in Berkeley and would not ultimately supply
many news jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses will leave and go somewhere else,'' said Berkeley
Chamber CEO Rachel Rupert.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert also said that the measure could not be imposed on
UC-Berkeley, the city's largest employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``UC would be exempt because they are governed by the laws of
the state, so this is not going to effect them,'' Rupert said.
UC-Berkeley employs 11,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert said the chamber plans to study the issue and attempt to
educate Berkeley voters about its pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``No study has looked into the qualifications of those who are
unemployed and how well they might match up with the businesses in
the city,'' Rupert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
