  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR JULY
17, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- YOUTH. Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman introduces a bill
today that would award $5 million a year to projects designed to
combat youth violence. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- COLUMN. Weekly column with U.S. Reps. Dan Miller,
R-Bradenton, and Porter Goss, R-Sanibel. Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. Wallison
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- NAPALM. A Texas company is beginning to recycle the
the Navy's napalm only weeks after protests in East Chicago forced
a local recycling plant to cancel its $2.5 million dollar contract
to recycle the gooing gas. What does Texas know that NWI doesn't?
Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- OCS. Louisiana could get an annual $264 million
windfall for environmental protection from the federal government
if a new proposal unveiled in Congress today becomes law. Egbert
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- FARMS-GOP. Rep. John Boehner, R-West Chester, and
Republican agriculture leaders will announce emergency farm
legislation Friday. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- PATIENTS. (RE-SENT) Both Republicans and Democrats released
their versions of a ``Patients Bill of Rights'' on Thursday. Rep.
Dave Hobson, R-Springfield, and Rep. Deborah Pryce, R-Columbus, are
on the Republican Health Care Task Force, which wrote the GOP bill.
Rep. John Boehner, R-West Chester, is a co-sponsor. Story will have
Ohio-specific numbers. Barton &AMP; Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- BOEHNER. (FRIDAY, for the weekend.) Hour-long interview with
Rep. John Boehner, R-West Chester, to discuss Republican
priorities, national politics, Ohio politics and a few local
issues, such as Fernald and Anthem. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- FEC. A look at the latest campaign fundraising
reports for Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, and his Republican
challenger, Tim Holloway. Also trying to get Rep. Bud Shuster's
report. Kane
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- COALITION. A coalition from the four states bordering
Mexico are in town to raise awareness of the region's needs. The
Rio Grande Valley is the most active region in the group, which has
helped bring millions of dollars in aid to the southern tip of
Texas. Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -- FARMS. Texas farmers may have access to needed federal
government funds sooner than they think. Brown
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- ZONES. The Virgin Islands will be eligible for
a new federal program that encourages businesses to locate in
lower-income areas, V.I. Delegate to Congress Donna Christian-Green
announced this week. Williams
</P>
