<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      07-17 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 19, will move Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE-CLASS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Something is wrong. For all its
vaunted importance as the chief beneficiary of American life, the
middle class is finishing last in the current economic boom.
Graphic. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLIGH-POPULARITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ To be sure, Europeans are
not about to give up their native tongues. But the trend toward
using English runs deep and not just among globetrotting
executives. Europe is uniting rapidly, as the adoption of the euro
shows, and Europeans recognize that in a world of collapsing
distances and borders, English is the language that the Old
Continent, like its infant central bank, uses to communicate. By
John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-NAMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The age of the mundane monicker
is over. How else to explain the Florida BeachDogs of the
Continental Basketball Association, or minor league baseball's
Everett (Wash.) AquaSox? By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   MACAO-REVIEW (Macao) _ Macao is helping Hong Kong cope with the
latest of a string of indignities that have befallen the former
British colony in the 12 months since it reverted to China. From
the Asian flu to the bird flu, little has gone right for Hong Kong
under Chinese rule, so with Macao's own handover set for Dec. 20,
1999, people here might be expected to fear for their future. For
the most part, though, the Macanese are welcoming the Chinese with
open arms. Graphic. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SAFETY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Justice Department's Office
of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Presvention has a surprise
summer hit: a free publication called ``When Your Child is Missing:
A Family Survival Guide.'' By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-REVIEW (Ballymoney) _ All it takes in Northern Ireland
is a trace of one religious background in people to make them
enemies in the murderous minds of people from the other side. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CON-JOB-REVIEW (Washington) _ It occurs with alarming frequency
in the United States, but the con job is perhaps the least
prosecuted of all petty crimes. But what happens when the con
artist leaves a few dead bodies buried in a trail of ingenious
scams and old liens? Is that enough to get the attention of the
police? By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-REFORM-REVIEW (Washington) _ Democrats hope to win back
the House come November in large part by backing a ``patient bill
of rights,'' whose purpose is to compel HMO's to take good, rather
than cheap, care of their members. Last week, Senate Republicans
signed on grudgingly, issuing as less sweeping proposal than the
Democrats'. The two parties, however, remain far apart on one
controversial provision. The Democratic version would enables
workers to sue their HMO if they suffer injury because their plan
refused to cover a physician-prescribed treatment. By Michael
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   DEVALUATION-REVIEW (Undated) _ Back in the 1970s, it was
considered a fairly benign cure for recessions and export slumps.
As recently as a year ago, it was the prescription for the excesses
that plagued Thailand and other Pacific Rim economies. Today,
however, it is regarded about as safe as bloodletting, and
countries as disparate as Russia and China are being urged to just
say no. The ``it'' is, of course, devaluation, that mysterious
force of international finance that talking heads on television
never bother to explain or distinguish from depreciation. Graphic.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   ZAPRUDER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ For Kennedy assassination
buffs, it was the ultimate collectible. Sure, it had been played
and replayed on television, but the actual raw footage of the
motorcycles swinging into view and the limousines speeding by _
and, of course, the split second that fueled endless conspiracy
theories _ was available only on bootleg copies. Until last week.
By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-HARASS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sexual harassment laws have always
been notoriously confusing, so there was much cheering when the
Supreme Court clarified things by issuing new harassment guidelines
last month. In clarifying matters, however, the Court invited new
kinds of sexual harassment complaints, from people who turned down
sexual advances or felt threatened in the workplace but did not
suffer professional harm and from men and women intimidated by the
behavior of people of the same sex. By Margot Slade.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
