<SLUG> BC-MCGUIRE-SOUVENIR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kid scores off McGwire homerun
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Like thousands of other kids, 12-year-old Nathan
Adams of Oakwood arrived at Busch Stadium in St. Louis last Sunday,
July 12, hoping for a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   He left with the ball that became Mark McGwire's 39th home run.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, McGwire couldn't quite reach the left field
bleachers, where Adams sat. The ball landed in the Houston Astros
bullpen, then bounced onto the field, where an Astro gloved it and
flipped it into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As Adams reached for the ball, so did an adult fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was, my cousin knocked the ball down with his
cap, trying to catch it,'' said Nathan, who attended the game with
his mom, a couple of aunts and several cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bounced between a guy and myself. The guy grabbed it pretty
much at the same time I did. He let it go. It was really nice of
him to do that, because it's not every day you catch Mark McGwire's
39th home run. I looked at it for a couple of seconds. I had this
amazed look on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   And he had his souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cousins were all over it,'' Nathan said. ``They were
rubbing the ball, saying they'll catch one, too, if they could get
magic Mark McGwire dust on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit No. 40 later in the game, but nobody in the Adams
family went home with it. Nathan, who was in St. Louis visiting
family, said he ``follows baseball a lot'' and roots for the Reds.
``I guess now I'm just a bigger McGwire fan than I was before.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: sean_mcclelland(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
