<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Orleans GM hired for job with new Round Rock team
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Jay Miller, the general manager of the
Houston Astros' Triple- A affiliate in New Orleans, will assume the
same position with the minor-league baseball team Nolan Ryan wants
to move to Round Rock, Reid Ryan said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the end of this season, Miller, 39, will become the
GM of the Jackson Generals, the Astros' Double-A affiliate, which
is expected to move to Round Rock for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, known for outrageous promotions designed to draw people
to the ballpark, has been the general manager for the New Orleans
Zephyrs for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Minor-league GMs typically are in charge of the team's
day-to-day operations, promotions and marketing. They do not decide
which players are promoted to the major leagues; that is up to the
parent organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get to know me, you'll see I do a lot of crazy
things,'' Miller said recently at Nelson W. Wolff Stadium, where
the Generals were playing the San Antonio Missions.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans every Friday there are fireworks, and Thursday is
dollar beer and band nights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll tailor the antics to the community,'' he said. ``New
Orleans is a party town. But basically my job is to get people into
the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Miller's successful ploys this year is to arrange a
wedding between the team's mascots on Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is already sold out,'' Miller said. ``The people like
our mascots better than our players.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Zephyrs' attendance jumped to 507,162 from
180,485 the year before, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went to New Orleans, Miller was director of customer
relations for the Texas Rangers, a job, which, as he put it, meant
his main responsibility was basically making sure fans had a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he met the Ryans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we needed tickets to the Rangers game when my Dad was
pitching, Jay would take care of us,'' Reid Ryan said. ``He knows
how to make fans feel special. Whether it's the guy with the $2
ticket in the bleachers or someone who owns a suite, he treats
everyone the same.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 to 1993, Miller was the Rangers' director of stadium
administration, in charge of stadium and ticket operations and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he would spend most of his time in Round Rock next
year, and assign his assistant to run things in Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to concentrate on Round Rock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
