<SLUG> BC-SWTEXAS-DIRECTOR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SWT athletic director Alden leaves for Missouri
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Alden isn't certain he would be the University of
Missouri's new athletic director if not for DeLoss Dodds.
</P>
<P>
   Alden, the Southwest Texas State athletic director who was
introduced as the Tigers' AD, said he thinks Dodds, the University
of Texas athletic director, played a pivotal but discreet role in
his landing the job. Dodds is close friends with Chuck Neinas, who
served as a head-hunter to Missouri in its search for the successor
to Joe Castiglione, who resigned in April to become AD at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd talked to DeLoss when the (Missouri) job opened and he
said it was a good job,'' Alden said. ``He asked me if I was
interested and I said yes. Then not long after that, Chuck called.
So I think DeLoss played a role in this, absolutely. He's been a
real good adviser and acquaintance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodds was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Alden, 40, who in only two years at SWT helped reverse the
athletic financial fortunes of the Southland Conference school in
San Marcos, will take over at Missouri on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at SWT from the University of New Mexico, where
he was an associate AD for development for four years, Alden helped
revive Bobcat athletics. This fiscal year, which ends in August,
will see earned income hit about $1 million, nearly double from the
previous year. The Bobcat Club booster organization set a
membership record this year of 635, surpassing the previous high of
605 set 15 years ago. Improvements are being made to various
athletic facilities, and there are plans for a new facility to
house staff offices, locker rooms, a weight room and additional
training rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he were staying,'' said Dr. James Studer, who oversees
SWT athletics as the school's vice president of student affairs.
``Those two years went by quickly, but Mike accomplished a lot in
those two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Studer said the search for Alden's successor will begin
immediately. ``I think it's reasonable we could have someone by
late December or early January, maybe sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The main disappointment for me is having to put off fund
raising until we get a new director on board,'' Studer added. ``I
was really hoping we could keep Mike. I thought it was reasonable
he could be with us for four or five years, but when we have the
kind of immediate success we had with him, it's natural people are
going to come calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Alden said he probably still would be SWT's fifth AD if it
hadn't been the Missouri job that opened. Alden's father lives on a
farm , 30 miles from Missouri's main campus in Columbia, on land
Alden's grandfather bought 52 years ago. An uncle lives in
Columbia, and Alden's brother is the head of a hospital emergency
room in Mexico, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hadn't been Missouri, I wouldn't be looking to go
anywhere. But it was just too much to pass up,'' said Alden, a
Chicago native. ``Southwest Texas gave me a great opportunity. The
people there have been good to me. It's been a great place to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   While Alden's new job is a considerable step up in visibility
and prestige, he inherits many problems similar to those he faced
at SWT. Missouri ranks 11th in the Big 12 in athletic budget ($13.7
million annually) and has a full-time athletic staff of about 80,
which is low by NCAA Division I standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are similarities between the problems at Missouri and
the ones we had at SWT when we got there,'' Alden said. ``They're
just on a grander scale at Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
