A0439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX     07-17 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everyone's atwitter about birdhouses
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Judging from my mail, there has been a sharp upsurge
in the number of homeless birds, giving rise to a new humanitarian
movement called Habitat for Avian-ity.
</P>
<P>
   We have bird bungalows, bird Tudors, bird Cape Cods, bird ranch
houses, bird apartments -- anything that humans enjoy living in --
scaled down and fitted with holes instead of doors. There must also
be a lot of people who must outdo their neighbors by erecting ever
more sumptuous wren palaces, martin high rises and titmouse town
houses.
</P>
<P>
   I have before me now two new birdhouse books from Sterling,
which seems to have hatched quite a few of them. As far as I know,
Sterling is not in business for the benefit of birds, so there must
be a market for these things.
</P>
<P>
   And, setting aside my jaundice for a moment, why not?
Woodworking isn't all serious stuff, although some of these things
look pretty serious. There's no reason not to build birdhouses and
have fun doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painted Birdhouses'' is a $25 hardback authored not by a
person but by a thing, called Plaid. I assume this is a magazine of
some sort, but I find no elaboration beyond references to Plaid
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   It contains 29 projects, few of which, surprisingly enough, are
actually birdhouses. There are birdhouse lamps, one of them with
matching curtainholders, a mawkish ``Bless our Nest Chest'' whose
only claim to avian residency appears to be the birdhouses painted
on it, and a lap desk with the same distinction. There are buckets
with birdhouses painted on them, T-shirts emblazoned with
birdhouses, and for all I know, birds wearing T-shirts. Suffice it
to say there is not much in here for woodworkers.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point is ``The Ultimate Birdhouse Book,'' a
paperbound version of a previously published collection of 40
birdhouses, nearly all actually intended to house birds, and many
of them nicer than the birds around my place deserve. Most are made
of wood, although there are a few gourds in the mix. At $14.95 it's
half the price of ``Painted Birdhouses'' and worth twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   More to the taste of the hardcore woodworker, but still with
plenty of playfulness, is ``Making Wood Handles, Hinges and
Knobs,'' by British woodworker-authors lan and Gill Bridgewater. As
far as I know, this is the first book devoted to hinges and pulls.
There are half a dozen handles, seven knobs -- most of them, of
course, turned -- five kinds of hinges and five latches and
catches.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are designed and made as free-standing projects;
they are not attached to anything at all, leaving you free to adapt
and adjust their design to whatever project you have in mind. All
of them are handsome, and some quite ingenious.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is another chip carving book by Wayne Barton, this one
a paperbound collection of award-winning designs (``The Art of Chip
Carving,'' $17.95, Sterling). There are some remarkable things
here, including Mickey Hudspeth's turned and carved containers and
Diana Kwan's painted and carved panels, which are astonishing
interpretations of Chinese and Japanese art.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
