<HEADER>
A0450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-FUNDS18-COX     07-17 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-FUNDS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH BUILDING POTENT POLITICAL OPERATION
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His opponent has raised no money, he already has $1
million in the bank and he has a list of contributors that would
make other politicians green with envy.
</P>
<P>
   So why does House Speaker Newt Gingrich continue to raise and
spend vast sums of money as he cruises toward re-election?
</P>
<P>
   In reality, while Gingrich is running in Georgia's 6th
Congressional District, he uses his campaign account to fund a
national political operation worthy of a presidential candidate,
replete with a high-priced consultant, costly legal help and
extensive direct mail fund solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich already has raised $4.8 million and spent $4.6 million
in the past 18 months, far and away the largest totals in the House
of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Consultant Joe Gaylord makes $10,000 a month from Gingrich and
another $3,000 from Gingrich's political action committee, or about
$150,000 a year. He also does consulting work for the National
Republican Congressional Committee, run by Rep. John Linder, a
Gingrich ally and Georgia colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three months, Gingrich has spent $238,000 on
mailings across the country. He reported raising just over a
half-million dollars in the small contributions _ less than $200 _
that direct mail is designed to elicit.
</P>
<P>
   The money comes in handy now, but the ability to tap into a vast
network of contributors might be particularly useful in, say, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say Speaker Gingrich does have presidential ambitions at
some point. Building this kind of network could be very valuable
down the line,'' said Paul Hendrie, a spokesman for the Center for
Responsive Politics, which analyzes political fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shields, Gingrich's campaign spokesman, said the speaker's
political campaign, formally called Friends of Newt Gingrich, or
FONG, exists solely to help him win re-election in his suburban
Atlanta district.
</P>
<P>
   Gary ``Bats'' Pelphrey, the Democratic candidate in the 6th
district, has yet to report raising any money, but Shields said
Gingrich will be prepared in any event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The liberal labor unions will put together a coordinated
effort to smear the speaker politically,'' Shields predicted.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the 1996 campaign, when cookie maker Michael Coles
spent $3.3 million, including $2 million of his own money, in his
failed campaign to unseat Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   But even against a well-financed challenger, Gingrich held a
comfortable edge in money. The speaker collected $6.2 million and
spent nearly $5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Paying his lawyers has been a steady drain on his campaign
coffers. Gingrich paid the Atlanta firm Arnall, Golden &AMP; Gregory
nearly $250,000 in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Shields earlier said he could not list in detail the legal
services, but said Friday that some of the money was paid for
lawyer J. Randolph Evans's work in setting up the payment of the
$300,000 sanction the House imposed on Gingrich for his ethics
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's campaign account is so flush that the speaker
considered using it to pay his penalty. For political reasons,
Gingrich decided to use personal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said last year that the speaker might claim a deduction on
his income taxes for the ethics payments. Asked if Gingrich has, in
fact, claimed a $50,000 deduction for the money he repaid in 1997,
Gingrich spokeswoman Christina Martin responded with a terse, ``No
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
